<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia     10-30 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grenade Goes Off in Terrorist's Hands, Killing Him and Policeman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A terrorist and a policeman were killed
by a grenade that burst as the terrorist prepared to toss it at a
passing police patrol Monday night, police said.
   They said an accomplice and a second police officer were wounded
in the explosion in El Minuto de Dios, a northwestern suburb of
this capital city of 6 million people.
   Two other bombs exploded late Monday in south and central
Bogota, but no casualties were reported, authorities said.
   One bomb destroyed part of a bank front and neighboring
buildings and the other caused minor damage at the social security
building.
   The latest incidents, following violence late Sunday that
wounded two journalists, apparently came in response to a decision
by the government of President Virgilio Barco to refuse to
negotiate with drug traffickers.
   The government declared war against the drug lords and their
hired killers on Aug. 19 after leading presidential candidate Sen.
Luis Galan was assassinated.
   Since then, at least 237 bombings and bombing attempts have
taken place throughout Colombia, mostly in Bogota, Medellin,
Barranquilla and Cartegena, resulting in the deaths of 33 people.
   Earlier Monday, eight people were killed and 30 injured when a
bus sped off the side of a ravine near Bordo, 340 miles south of
Bogota, police said.
   The bus was traveling north from Ipiales near the border with
Ecuador. Police said the bus apparently was traveling too fast.
</TEXT>
