<FIRST>r i AM-India-Clashes     10-30 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Clashes,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Recover 48 bodies After Clashes in India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-eight more bodies were recovered
on Monday in Bhagalpur, a remote town in Bihar state hit by
Hindu-Moslem violence, and another person was killed when police
fired at an angry mob, news reports said.
   Since Sunday, 171 people have died in Bhagalpur and in three
villages stretching across a 125-mile swath of Bihar state, one of
the poorest and most violent in India, news media said.
   United News of India said the official death toll in Bhagalpur
stood at 145 since clashes began last Tuesday.
   Press Trust of India put the Bhagalpur toll at 200.
   In a dispatch from the state capital of Patna, UNI quoted Bihar
Home Affairs Commissioner Jiya Lal Arya as saying police fired when
the mob attacked homes. Police rescued at least 150 residents.
   Bhagalpur is on the Ganges River, which is sacred to Hindus. The
town is about 110 miles east of Patna and 220 miles northwest of
Calcutta.
   Some clashes coincided with processions by Hindu militants who
are collecting bricks to build a temple at Ayodhya, in neighboring
Uttar Pradesh state, where Hindus and Moslems lay claim to the same
religious site.
</TEXT>
