<DOCNO> AP891030-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 2355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PlantExplosion     10-30 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plant Explosion,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memorial Service for Victims of Plant Explosion, Three More Bodies
Found</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 25,000 people attended a memorial
service Monday night for 22 workers who died in a series of
explosions at a plastics plant last week, and three more bodies
were recovered from the rubble.
   Among those attending the 45-minute service at the John Ray
Harrison Convention Center were 259 relatives of those who died in
the Phillips Petroleum Co. plant disaster last Monday.
   ``No one can really explain why happenings such as this occur,''
said S.R. ``Buddy'' Jones Jr., chairman emeritus of Bank One of
Texas here. ``I surely don't know, but I do know this: a tragedy of
this magnitude brings us all closer together and demonstrates the
love, the care and the concern we have for one another.''
   Sgt. Jim Cluck, chaplain of the Police Department, asked
Phillips employees to honor those who died by having the strength
to return to work and live their lives ``the way they would want
you to live.''
   The recovery of three bodies brought the confirmed death toll to
17. The remains of five workers remain missing. The explosions
injured 124 people.
   Despite thunderstorms and heavy rain, work crews continued
moving tons of steel and concrete in hopes of recovering the last
of the victims.
   U.S. Rep. Mike Andrews, D-Texas, whose district includes this
city of 119,300, toured the plant and met with authorities.
   ``You really have to be here to see how absolutely devastating
that blast was,'' Andrews said. ``Fully a quarter of the plant has
been eliminated. There is still a safety factor at the plant site.
There are still fires burning. It is an awesome sight to see.''
   Much of the search has concentrated on the plant's control and
finishing rooms, where debris is stacked as high as 40 feet,
officials said.
   The polyethylene plant maufactured almost 20 percent of the
nation's production of plastic pellets used to make milk jugs and
grocery bags.
   Phillips officials believe flammable hydrocarbon vapor from
ethylene and isobutane gases escaped from a leaking chemical
reactor, triggering the explosion. But company officials have said
they don't know how the gases were ignited and won't concentrate on
finding a cause until all the missing victims have been found.
</TEXT>
