<DOCNO> AP891030-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 0107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     10-30 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Looking Into Decline in US Oats Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decline in U.S. oats production is prompting
Congress to look into the situation, and Agriculture Department
analysts say consumer demand for oatmeal is one of the many factors
for consideration.
   Some believe the government's price support program for oats
should be modified to encourage farmers to plant more oats instead
of turning to other feed grains such as barley, corn or sorghum.
   Whatever remedies are forthcoming, the United States since 1982
has been a net importer of oats instead of an exporter. Canada,
Sweden, Finland and Argentina are the major foreign suppliers.
   ``The U.S. market share of all world (oats) imports rose to an
annual average of 44 percent in 1985-88, largest of all importing
countries,'' says the department's Economic Research Service.
   The agency, in a new staff report prepared as background for
1990 farm legislation, said oats are grown in most states but are
concentrated in the North Central region, including the Dakotas,
Minnesota, Iowa and Nebraska.
   In the 1950s, oats were grown on more than 40 million acres, and
annual farm prices averaged 58 cents to 72 cents per bushel. In
recent years, oats have been produced on 6 million to 10 million
acres, with farm prices climbing from $1.21 per bushel in 1986 to
$1.56 in 1987 and a record $2.67 in 1988.
   The value of oats production in 1987 ranked 16th among major
U.S. field crops at $606 million. By comparison, corn was $14
billion; soybeans, $11.3 billion; hay, $9 billion; and wheat, $5.5
billion.
   ``The principal domestic use of oats is for livestock feed,
although it has recently become a specialty feed for race and
pleasure horses,'' the report said.
   Oats as human food includes the traditional oatmeal, along with
oat flour, natural cereals, meat product extenders, cookies and
breads, granola, oat bran and baby food.
   ``Recent medical research has shown that certain fibrous plant
materials in the diet can lower serum cholesterol concentrations,''
the report said. ``The fibers, however, must be water soluble. Oat
bran is water soluble, but wheat bran is not. Water-soluble dietary
fibers also lower post-meal blood glucose levels in
insulin-dependent diabetics.''
   The report added: ``Thus, oat bran or whole oats is beginning to
play a larger role in improving health through diet. Oats
consumption by humans appears to be increasing, as U.S. diets seem
to be shifting toward cereal-based foods and away from fatty,
high-protein animal-based foods.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Department scientists say they
have developed a new lethal snack for cockroaches, grasshoppers,
crickets and fire ants that smells too yummy to resist.
   The bait includes corn mash left over from the manufacture of
fuel-grade alcohol, ethanol, and a water-absorbent gel. The mixture
is laced with a slow-release insecticide.
   According to the department's Agricultural Research Service, the
new bait was initially designed to use against cockroaches. But
researchers at the agencies insect laboratory in Gainesville, Fla.,
found it attracted the other species, too.
   Entomologist Richard J. Brenner said the combination of corn
mash and gel tends to retain moisture and ``remains aromatic under
high temperatures and dry conditions.'' That makes it particularly
attractive to roaches, which become hungry and thirsty when the
temperature rises.
   The bait has been tested in the field as well as in the
laboratory, and is waiting on approval by the Environmental
Protection Agency, he said.
   Although the mash-gel combination was developed by Brenner and
an agency colleague, Richard S. Patterson, there are two other
co-inventors: Roger R. Pierce of Pierce Services Inc., Cashier,
N.C., and Marvin Hult of Air Vent Inc., Peoria, Ill.
   Air Vent and Pierce Services signed research agreements with the
USDA agency in February 1988 and hold first rights to license the
bait when a patent is granted.
   Pierce, to protect the bait's aroma and moisture during storage,
suggested wrapping the bait in wax film that a hungry cockroach can
open easily. Hult recommended using a bait holder, which would
extend the shelf life of the mixture and protect it until ready for
use.
   Brenner said that while the corn mash attracts roaches, hoppers,
crickets and fire ants, it doesn't attract warm-blooded animals as
do baits of fruit, bread, raisins or beer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's rice production is expected to
rise slightly in 1989-90 but will fall short of meeting global
demands, according to Agriculture Department projections.
   Significant harvest increases are expected in China, Indonesia,
the Philippines and Japan, said the department's Economic Research
Service. India's production may drop 6 percent from last year's
record level but still would be the second-largest.
   Total foreign rice production was forecast at 326 million metric
tons, and the U.S. crop at 4.93 million tons, milled equivalent.
   Analysts said that would be the fourth straight year that U.S.
rice production has fallen short of total use, meaning another
reduction in the U.S. rice stockpile by next Aug. 1.
</TEXT>
