<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-KCDesegregation     10-30 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-KC Desegregation,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court to Hear Arguments on Kansas City Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Prenoon lead planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court is being asked to decide
whether a federal judge may impose a tax increase to pay for
court-ordered school desegregation in Kansas City, Mo.
   At issue in today's oral arguments is a federal judge's 1987
order doubling the property tax of residents in the Kansas City
school district to finance a court-ordered plan for racially
desegregating the public schools.
   Legal scholars and education officials say the court's decision
could shape future school desegregation plans across the country
and define the federal courts' power to remedy constitutional
violations involving issues from prison overcrowding to fair
housing.
   The state of Missouri is asking the justices to overturn a
decision by the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals that upheld the
property tax increase ordered by U.S. District Judge Russell Clark.
The state contends that the federal courts lack the power to order
higher taxes even to correct a constitutional violation such as
racial discrimination in schools.
   The school district and a group of school children, who brought
the original desegregation case in 1977, are urging the high court
to uphold the tax decision. The district contends that state
property tax law and local voters cannot be allowed to frustrate
the constitutional rights of Kansas City's minority schoolchildren
to an equal educational opportunity.
   Clark ordered the tax increase in September 1987 after the local
school district was unable to pay its share of a more than $400
million desegregation plan he had approved for capital improvements
in buildings and establishment of special ``magnet'' schools.
   State law says local property taxes may be raised only with
voters' approval, and in some instances only with a two-thirds
majority. District voters had not approved a levy increase since
1969, with four tax increase proposals rejected in 1986 and 1987 to
finance the desegregation plan.
   In addition to doubling the property tax, Clark imposed an
income tax surcharge on those people living or working in the
school district.
   The appeals court struck down the income surcharge in August
1988, but upheld the district court's authority to order an
increase in the property tax. However, the appeals court modified
the procedure for imposing the higher tax levy.
   The appeals court found that state law had effectively prevented
the school district from levying the necessary taxes to pay for the
desegregation plan. It upheld Clark's order as one that ``set aside
levy limitations,'' and empowered the elected local school board to
set the needed tax levels within certain limits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0022 </DOCNO>
