<FIRST>u w AM-MurderRecord 1stLd-Writethru   10-30 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murder Record, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0406,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to clarify victim was most recent.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Capital Matches Last Year's Murder Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia matched its year-old
record for homicides Sunday with five killings during a seven-hour
weekend period that pushed this year's total to 369 homicides.
   Three of the weekend killings were linked to drugs, as are the
majority of the deaths in the nation's capital, and the other two
were a 13-year-old girl and her aunt who were found stabbed to
death in their apartment on Saturday.
   The most recent victim was a 41-year-old man found dead of
multiple gunshot wounds early Sunday. He had $11,000 cash and a
large quantity of heroin in his pockets when his body was found,
according to police homicide detectives.
   ``It's awful. But people in this community are resorting to
deadly violence to resolve conflict,'' said police spokesman Lt.
Reginald Smith.
   Police have estimated more than half the city's killings are
tied to drugs, with crack cocaine fueling much of the violence.
   They said last at the end of 1988 that 372 people were killed in
homicides, but a police revised that number downward Sunday when
they subtracted three victims of police shootings from the official
total.
   Police said they charged Steve Lewis Patterson, 24, with two
counts of murder in the deaths late Saturday night of Brenda R.
Sams, 34, and her niece, Keaena Sams. Police described Patterson as
Brenda Sams' boyfriend.
   Domestic disputes caused the second highest number of deaths in
the city last year, police have said.
</TEXT>
