<HEAD>Teen Leads Police in Low-speed Chase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager driving a stolen concrete mixer
led police on a low-speed 50-mile chase through eight towns that
ended when an officer blew out tires with a shotgun, police said.
   No one was injured in the chase, but the 15-ton truck crushed a
Haines City police car and a state Game and Fresh Water Fish
Commission vehicle. The truck was stolen from Ewell Industries in
Auburndale, police said.
   Richard Booker Branch, 18, of Davenport, was charged with
burglary, grand theft and aggravated assault on a law enforcement
officer. He was taken to the Polk County Jail.
   The incident began at about 2:30 a.m. EST Saturday, when a
police officer noticed the truck in Bartow, which is 45 miles east
of Tampa.
   Police said Branch drove the truck at speeds from 35 to 50 mph
through Dundee, Lake Hamilton, Lake Wales, Haines City, Davenport,
Poinciana and Polk. After a police officer shot out several tires,
police apprehended Branch, who tried to flee on foot.
