<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-30 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Tokyo Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against the Japanese yen today,
while share prices also fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange in
sluggish trading.
   The dollar ended the day's trading at 142.17 yen, down 0.58 yen
from Friday's close of 142.75 yen. It opened at 141.70 yen and
ranged between 141.70 and 142.38 yen. The dollar closed at 141.70
yen in New York on Friday.
   Currency dealers said dollar-buying by institutional investors
in Japan and Southeast Asia was helping to shore up the dollar
against selling pressure.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said market players are awaiting a spate of U.S.
economic data, including the country's advance economic indicators
for September, due out Tuesday, and the October employment figures,
due Friday.
   A lack of market-moving news and uncertainty over trends in the
stock market kept the market fairly quiet, said Kaneo Ogino of
Goldman Sachs.
   ``It depends on the stock market. Whatever happens there, the
dollar will follow,'' Ogino said.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which lost 151.90 points Friday, shed another 109.85
points, or 0.3 percent, closing at 35,417.44.
   Profit taking pushed the Nikkei average 141.30 points lower
early in the day but it recovered somewhat later on buying of
domestic demand-related issues like construction and fuel shares,
said Wako Securities dealer Shingo Takahashi.
   Only 600 million shares changed hands, down from 1.24 billion
shares Friday.
   Investors, who took profits Friday, remained on the sidelines
today due to uncertainty in the foreign exchange market and the New
York stock market, traders said.
   Fading expectations for lower interest rates kept investors away
from real estate shares, which notably advanced last week, said
Takamori Matsuda, an analyst at Dresdner-ABD Securities.
</TEXT>
