<FIRST>r p PM-SeattleMayoral     10-30 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seattle Mayoral,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Busing a Major Issue in Seattle's Mayoral Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-busing initiative figures strongly in the
Nov. 7 mayoral election that will result in either the city's first
black or first Republican mayor in more than two decades.
   Polls have shown strong support for Initiative 34, which is
backed by Republican Doug Jewett. They also give a slight edge to
his opponent, City Councilman Norm Rice, who is against the measure.
   Rice, 46, would be the first black mayor in a city where blacks
comprise only about 10 percent of the population.
   ``If I win, it's going to say that people in Seattle recognize
how hard people work and how well they do their jobs,'' Rice said.
   Jewett, the 42-year-old city attorney, would be the first
Republican to win the non-partisan office since Dorm Braman in 1965.
   The anti-busing measure asks, but does not require, the
independently elected and budgeted city School Board to switch from
a ``controlled choice'' attendance plan that requires busing of
about 10 percent of the 40,000 students for racial balance to a
completely open enrollment system.
   In exchange for abandoning mandatory busing, schools would get
about $4.5 million in annual sales tax revenue that now goes to the
city, with that money reserved for ``magnet'' programs designed to
encourage racial balance.
   Jewett and Rice finished one-two among 13 candidates in
September's primary.
   Rice has trumpeted his Democratic credentials, including
endorsements from the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Gov. Booth Gardner, U.S.
Rep. Jim McDermott, and outgoing Mayor Charles Royer, who decided
not to run for a fourth term.
   A random telephone survey of 400 likely voters taken Oct. 13-16
for KIRO-TV and the Seattle Post-Intelligencer, showed Rice leading
by 46-39 percent with the rest undecided.
   In the poll, which had a 4.8 point margin of error, 46 percent
favored the initiative, 32 percent were opposed and the rest
undecided.
   Many observers believe the Washington Supreme Court did Rice a
favor by refusing to strike the initiative from the ballot.
Opponents claimed the initiative violated the state Constitution,
but the court decided to hear that claim only if the measure were
passed.
   As a result, the overwhelmingly Democratic electorate can reject
busing while voting for Rice.
   Rice sees crime as the top issue. Jewett says the schools are
tops in his campaign but he accuses the news media of downplaying
his positions on crime, growth and other issues.
   Jewett helped draft the measure and has been its leading
advocate. City council and school board members generally are
opposed.
   So is Rice, who says the plan is racist in effect if not in
intent. He rejects suggestions that Jewett is racially biased.
   On Oct. 9, Rice announced his own plan for assuring racial
balance in schools with magnet programs, stronger city support for
education and incentives for housing integration. The plan would
eliminate any need for mandatory busing within four years, he said.
   Jewett promptly accused his opponent of a near-flip-flop to woo
voters.
   ``The political issue is that of leadership,'' he said.
``They've watched Norm Rice go from adamant opposition to ending
mandatory busing to embracing it.'
   Rice admits a considerable change of heart ``because of what
busing does to working families'' but said that if nothing else
keeps the schools racially balanced, mandatory measures must
continue.
   ``I still think that integrated, quality education is important
to the future of America,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
