<FIRST>r i PM-China-Dissidents     10-30 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Dissidents,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Dissidents Captured in China's Sichuan Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese police arrested four leaders of a
dissident group that was active in the pro-democracy movement and
worked to set up an underground armed force, an official Chinese
report said today.
   The report indicates Chinese authorities are continuing the
crackdown on people involved in the protests that swept the nation
last spring.
   The ``Chongqing Patriotic Democracy League'' in Sichuan province
of southwestern China was formed May 21 after martial law was
declared in Beijing, the official China News Service said in a
report appearing in Hong Kong.
   Police arrested the group's leader, Dai Weiping, and three other
key members, the news service said. The brief report did not say
when the arrests were made.
   The report from Chongqing called the organization a
``counterrevolutionary group,'' a label that Chinese officials have
been using for the pro-democracy protests.
   The news service said league members participated in illegal
marches supporting the student-led protests in Beijing, gave
reactionary speeches, and incited turmoil.
   After Chinese troops crushed the pro-democracy movement in
Beijing on June 4, the league remained active by calling secret
meetings and scheming to steal guns to set up an underground
fighting force, the report said.
   Hundreds of unarmed civilians were killed during the military's
June assault in the capital.
   Today's report also claimed that the league tried to get foreign
support, but did not elaborate.
   The South China Morning Post, an English-language newspaper in
Hong Kong, quoted unidentified analysts in Sichuan as saying they
believed the league was an organization of workers, including the
unemployed.
   China annnounced thousands of arrests at the beginning of the
crackdown. However, few arrests have been publicized recently,
probably reflecting in part government sensitivity over foreign
criticism.
</TEXT>
