<FIRST>r a PM-RiverRescue     10-30 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-River Rescue,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daring Rescue: Infant Saved from Car in Icy River</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Omard cq in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASPEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers rappelled 60 feet down a tow cable
into an icy mountain river to rescue a month-old girl from a car
that plunged off a road and was mostly submerged for 45 minutes.
   The infant's mother and grandparents were killed in the crash
Sunday at Independence Pass, said Pitkin County Sheriff's spokesman
Steve Crockett.
   The victims, Omard and Marjorie Harrison of Houston, and their
daughter, Kary Venable, 19, of Kingwood, Texas, had hitchhiked a
ride with two teen-age girls after their van was disabled in an
accident on state Highway 82 outside this ski resort town, Crockett
said. The teens survived.
   The car slid off the snowy highway and down a 60-foot cliff into
a stretch of the Roaring Fork River called ``Devil's Punchbowl.''
   The first volunteer firefighters on the scene spotted the car,
upside down and up to its wheels in the frigid water, Crockett
said. The used a truck-mounted winch to pull the car near the
shore, then two of the volunteers, Dr. Steve Ayers and Rick Dean,
rappelled down the tow cable and pulled month-old Samantha Venable
from the car.
   The child was in critical condition today at St. Mary's Hospital
in Grand Junction, a nursing supervisor said.
   The driver, Britt Rosen, 17, of Aspen, and her passenger, Maelle
Deschutter, 16, of Snowmass Village, managed to kick out the car's
front windows and escape to hail a passing motorist, Crockett said.
Ms. Rosen was treated for hypothermia and Ms. Deschutter for a
broken arm.
   Harrison, 64, and Mrs. Harrison, 61, were found dead in the back
seat, Crockett said. A dog also was killed.
</TEXT>
