<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     10-30 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major foreign
currencies in early European trading today. Gold prices rose as
much as $4.25 an ounce.
   Currency dealers said trading was calm, and the market's
attention had shifted to cross-currency trading.
   They said the dollar moved up from its lows of late Friday on
short-covering, but that interest in dollar trading was minimal.
   ``It's very quiet so far this morning,'' said one trader in
Rome. ``I don't see much space for the dollar to decline.''
   The Bank of England reportedly intervened in the market to prop
up the British pound, which fell last week following Nigel Lawson's
resignation as Chancellor of the Exchequer.
   At midmorning, it cost $1.5715 to buy one pound, cheaper for
buyers than $1.5750 late Friday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday:
   _1.8350 West German marks, up from 1.8300
   _1.6053 Swiss francs, up from 1.6005
   _6.2318 French francs, up from 6.2190
   _2.0713 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0820
   _1,345.50 Italian lire, up from 1,342.00
   _1.1745 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1746
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.58 yen to a closing 142.17 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 142.05 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $379 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $374.25. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $378.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $377, up from $373 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.46 to close at a bid of
$378.75.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.27 a troy
ounce, up from Friday's $5.19.
</TEXT>
