<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-MIAs     10-30 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-MIAs,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Vietnam Agree To Expand Work On Missing U.S. Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam and the United States have
agreed to expand joint efforts to resolve the cases of about 1,700
American soldiers missing from the Vietnam War, an official report
said today.
   The agreement was reached after two days of talks in Hanoi
between U.S. presidential envoy John W. Vessey Jr. and Foreign
Minister Nguyen Co Thach, said the official Voice of Vietnam radio.
   It quoted a joint communique as saying the two sides agreed ``to
refine and extend the process of joint cooperation to resolve the
compelling cases of discrepancies, including conducting additional
research to determine the fate of these Americans.''
   ``Discrepancy cases'' are those to which the United States has
assigned highest priority. They are cases it says the Vietnamese
should have information on, including instances where U.S. airmen
are believed to have parachuted to safety but were never heard from.
   The broadcast did not give details of how the efforts would be
expanded.
   U.S. and Vietnamese specialists are now halfway into their
eighth joint field investigation. These have involved such work as
interviewing villagers living near sites where U.S. warplanes
crashed.
   The war ended in 1975 with the defeat of the south by the
Communist north.
   The communique said the U.S. side expressed appreciation for
progress on programs to resettle Vietnamese in the United States,
including half-American children and former inmates of political
``re-education camps.''
   ``Both sides agreed to continue efforts to sustain the current
high level of cooperation on these important programs,'' it said.
   It said Vessey repeated a U.S. commitment to encourage the
efforts by non-governmental U.S. organizations to help Vietnam with
its humanitarian problems, including those involving disabled
people and children.
   In previous talks, the United States has refused to discuss
non-humanitarian questions.
   However, the communique said Vessey and Thach also exchanged
views on Cambodia, where a Vietnamese-installed government is
fighting guerrillas supported by the United States.
   Vessey traveled to Hanoi with senior state and defense
department officials and Ann Mills Griffiths, the head of the
private National League of Families of American Prisioners And
Missing In Southeast Asia.
   It was his second mission to Vietnam as presidential envoy. His
August 1987 trip resulted in Vietnam's agreement to speed up work
on humanitarian issues and a U.S. promise to encourage
non-governmental aid to Vietnam.
   The Vietnamese seek American diplomatic recognition to end their
isolation from the non-Communist world and bring in badly needed
economic assistance.
   They have complained that the United States has failed to move
in that direction since Vietnam in late September withdrew what it
called its last 26,000 troops from Cambodia. Washington had called
the action a prerequisite for establishing relations.
   However, Washington is now demanding that Vietnam work toward
reaching a political settlement to the war in Cambodia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
