<HEAD>Peres Released from Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres went home today
after two weeks in the hospital for treatment of a urinary tract
infection.
   Peres, who is also the vice premier and leads the center-left
Labor Party, said he will attend a meeting of Israel's top Cabinet
leaders Wednesday if there is discussion of a peace proposal by
U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   The finance minister criticized demands for changes in Baker's
plan by the right-wing Likud bloc, Labor's partner in the coalition
Cabinet.
   In a telephone interview with Israel Radio after leaving Haemek
Hospital in Afula, Peres said Israel should accept Baker's call for
Israeli talks with a Palestinian delegation to advance an Israeli
plan for elections in the occupied territories.
   But Peres said the government's response does not have to be
given before Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, leader of the Likud
bloc, travels to the United States in mid-November.
   Peres, 66, will spend several days resting at home. He was
hospitalized after he complained of feeling ill during a trip to
northern Israel.
