<SECOND>PM-Spence-Grand Jury, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0500,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness Tells Grand Jury About Lobbyist's Activities</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts attribution to newspaper throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury investigating former
lobbyist Craig T. Spence has heard testimony about late-night White
House tours, missing presidential china and Spence's interest in a
secret military counterterrorism unit, according to a published
report.
   The witness, who requested anonymity, described interviews last
Thursday with Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Strasser, Secret Service
agents and the grand jury in a story in today's editions of The
Washington Times.
   Spence also has been subpoenaed to testify before the grand jury
but apparently has not yet appeared, the newspaper said.
   The U.S. Attorney's Office is investigating Spence's alleged
connection to a male prostitution ring that was raided by Secret
Service agents in February. The raid uncovered credit card receipts
indicating the ring brought in as much as $20,000 a month.
   The Secret Service also is investigating allegations that two
uniformed White House guards allowed Spence to take several
prostitutes on after-hours tours of the executive mansion.
   One guard reportedly has acknowledged receiving an expensive
watch from Spence and giving the lobbyist a piece of White House
china.
   ``They pulled out a picture book containing the White House
china collections and asked me about the Truman china,'' the
witness, identified as among those who took an unauthorized tour of
the White House on July 3, 1988, told the Times.
   ``They wanted to know if I had seen anything like that. They
strongly intimated that more things were missing.''
   Federal prosecutors asked the most detailed questions about the
tour, the witness was quoted as saying.
   The prosecutor also appeared to be investigating the use of
credit cards to procure prostitutes and trying to determine the
identity of a young man Spence had frequently introduced as his
son, the witness said.
   According to the Times, Strasser also asked the witness about
Spence's reported gift of an $8,000 Rolex watch to a member of the
armed services, whom Spence pressed for information on the Delta
Force, a Fort Bragg, N.C.-based counterterrorism unit.
   ``They asked me what I thought Spence wanted to know about the
Delta project,'' the newspaper quoted the witness as saying. ``I
said it could mean he was just interested in the young guys there
or something else.''
