<HEAD>Two Papers Endorse Young Opponent in Mayor's Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both Detroit's major newspapers endorsed Tom
Barrow, the 40-year-old accountant who has never held public
office, in his race against front-running Mayor Coleman A. Young,
who is seeking a fifth term.
   The Detroit News and Detroit Free Press in Sunday editions
endorsed Barrow in the Nov. 7 election. Barrow drew 39 percent of
the vote in his 1985 campaign against Young. Polls show the
71-year-old mayor, first elected in 1973, is likely to win.
   Both papers said it was time for a change.
   ``The plain fact is that Coleman Young has run out of steam,''
the News said.
   The Free Press said a vote for Barrow `is really a protest vote,
an almost desperate cry for the kind of sustained effort to achieve
change that the city needs.''
   ``I can't explain the Detroit media,'' Young said during a radio
interview. ``No other press anywhere in the nation of which I am
aware is so negative toward its own city.''
   Barrow said the endorsements show that ``even the establishment,
which has been supporting (Young) for 16 years, now is coming to
agreement with the neighborhoods and recognize it's time for a
change.''
