<HEAD>Fire Hits Home of Parents of Visitation Case Doctor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 3rd graf, Fire investigators, with cause still undetermined</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE RUMSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities say an arsonist may be responsible
for a fire that damaged the home of the missing parents of
Elizabeth Morgan, the physician who was jailed for hiding her
daughter in a child visitation battle.
   No one was in the house when the fire began early Sunday and
there were no injuries, but the fire caused $50,000 damage to the
suburban Fairfax County, Va., home, said county Fire Department
spokeswoman Pam Weiger.
   Ms. Weiger said today that investigators were trying to pin down
the cause.
   Robert Morgan, Elizabeth Morgan's brother, said he believed the
fire was set deliberately.
   ``The way (investigators) told it to us is that arson is the
only reason that makes sense, but they can't say it was arson
unless there's no doubt,'' Robert Morgan said.
   ``The report says that the point of origin was outside the
house. It was not the wiring or anything that did it and it was in
the middle of the night,'' he said.
   Ms. Weiger said she had no more information on the cause of the
fire.
   Robert Morgan said the home has not been occupied since
Elizabeth Morgan was sent to jail more than two years ago for
refusing to produce her daughter, Hilary, for court-ordered visits
with the girl's father.
   Ms. Morgan, 42, alleges her ex-husband, oral surgeon Eric
Foretich, sexually molested the girl. Foretich, 46, denies the
charge and a Washington judge has granted him visitation rights.
   Ms. Morgan spent more than two years in jail and was released
last month after widespread publicity led Congress to pass a bill
that ended her imprisonment.
   But the Morgan parents have not been seen since the summer of
1987 and the girl, who is 7 years old, remains missing.
   Asked in a telephone interview whether his parents knew of the
fire and where they were, Robert Morgan said, ``I prefer not to
say.''
   Ms. Morgan could not be reached for comment.
