<DOCNO> AP891030-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Ray     10-30 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Ray,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Assassin Loses Appeal to High Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Earl Ray, who is serving a 99-year
prison sentence for the assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther
King, lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that Ray's rights
were not violated when 20 years ago he pleaded guilty to
first-degree murder.
   Ray, 61, will not be eligible for parole until 1998 for the
April 4, 1968, killing of King in Memphis, Tenn. Ray is at Brushy
Mountain State Prison in Tennessee.
   Ray pleaded guilty on March 9, 1969, but retracted his story
three days later and has continued to claim his innocence.
   In his latest appeal, Ray said he received ineffective legal
assistance. A federal judge refused in 1988 to overturn Ray's
conviction, and the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the
judge's ruling last March.
   The case is Ray vs. Jones, 89-374.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
