<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-FaithHealing     10-30 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Faith Healing,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Bars Lawsuit Against Christian Science Church in Michigan Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today barred a lawsuit
against the Christian Science church in the death of a 15-month-old
Michigan boy who died of meningitis.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a suit
against the church and its members over faith healing would violate
their religious freedom.
   The case stems from the death of Matthew Swan on July 7, 1977,
from brain abscesses caused by meningitis.
   His parents, Douglas and Rita Swan of Grosse Pointe Park, Mich.,
were lifelong adherents of Christian Science at the time of their
son's death.
   They were advised by two Christian Science healers, Jeanne
Laitner and June Ahearn, to rely on religious faith when Matthew
developed a raging fever about three weeks before he died.
   After their son's death, the Swans sued the two healers and the
church, alleging negligence. The suit said, among other things,
that the healers made inaccurate diagnoses and coerced the parents
to forgo seeking medical help.
   The church was accused of negligence for failing to train the
healers properly.
   A Michigan state judge threw out the suit, and the dismissal was
upheld by a state appeals court in 1986.
   By that time, the Swans had withdrawn from the case and were
replaced as plaintiffs by a representative of their child's estate.
   The appeals court said constitutionally protected yreligious
freedom outweighs, in this case, the state's interest in protecting
children.
   ``Religious conduct is permissible and protected unless the
state can show a compelling state interest in interfering with the
conduct,'' the state court said. ``Even then, the state must act in
the least restrictive manner. We find no merit in (the) argument
that ...(a negligence suit) is the least restrictive means of
regulating spiritual healing practices.''
   Lawyers representing Matthew Swan's estate said the Michigan
ruling conflicts with others that have allowed churches and their
officials to be sued.
   For example, they cited a suit against the Rev. Sun Myung Moon's
Unification Church by two former California members who say they
were duped into joining it.
   The Supreme Court last May refused to block that suit, rejecting
an appeal by the Unification Church.
   The justices in the past have declined to review cases of
alleged clergy malpractice and those in which faith healing
practices are at issue.
   The case is Brown vs. Laitner, 89-354.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-KAL     10-30 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-KAL,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Turns Away Dispute Over Anti-Bias Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today turned away a dispute
over how to apply federal anti-bias laws to foreign-owned
businesses operating in the United States.
   The court, over one dissenting vote, let stand a ruling
challenged both by Korean Air Lines and a Philadelphia man replaced
in his KAL job by a Korean citizen.
   Justice Byron R. White voted to hear arguments in the case but
four votes are needed to grant such review.
   Thomas V. MacNamara was fired in 1982 as KAL's
Philadelphia-based district sales manager for Delaware,
Pennsylvania and southern New Jersey. He was replaced by Wan Gin
Chung, who is in this country on a visa.
   MacNamara said the airline violated that portion of the Civil
Rights Act of 1964 banning discrimination based on race or national
origin.
   MacNamara, 57 when he was fired, also said KAL violated a
federal law against age bias. Chung was 42 in 1982.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in its ruling last
December, gave partial victories to both MacNamara and KAL.
   The appeals court ordered that MacNamara's lawsuit go to trial,
but said he could prevail only if proving KAL intentionally
discriminated against him based on some illegal criterion.
   The appeals court said that to win, MacNamara must prove that
KAL would not have fired him but for his race, national origin or
age.
   MacNamara cannot succeed by showing, primarily with statistical
evidence, that his firing had the effect of discriminating against
older white Americans, the appeals court said.
   The 3rd Circuit court rejected KAL's argument that it should be
shielded from all bias suits because of a 1956 Treaty of
Friendship, Commerce and Navigation between the United States and
Korea.
   The treaty gives businesses of each nation broad discretion in
hiring on foreign soil.
   The appeals court said the treaty's ``limited purpose'' is to
assure foreign investors ``the freedom to place their own citizens
in key management positions, thus facilitating their operational
success in the host country.''
   The treaty does not authorize ``a broad exemption from laws that
prohibit discrimination on grounds unrelated to citizenship,'' the
appeals court said.
   KAL lawyers said the ruling will discourage foreign investment
in the United States and American investment abroad.
   MacNamara said the decision gives foreign corporations greater
rights than those of domestic U.S. corporations and exposes U.S.
workers to discrimination.
   The Bush administration urged the Supreme Court to reject the
competing appeals.
   The cases are KAL vs. MacNamara, 88-1449, and MacNamara vs. KAL,
88-1551.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Grayback     10-30 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Grayback,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Leaves Intact $4.25 Million Award to Navy Divers' Families</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today left intact a $4.25
million award to the families of five Navy divers killed in an
accident aboard the submarine USS Grayback in the Philippines seven
years ago.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by General
Dynamics Corp., designer of the diving chamber in which the men
died.
   The accident occurred near Subic Bay the night of Jan. 16, 1982,
when the divers were trapped inside the diving chamber without
adequate air.
   A ventilation valve that allows air to enter the flooded chamber
was not fully open, creating a vacuum as the water drained.
   The victims were William Robinson of Cassopolis, Mich., Richard
Bond of Bremerton, Wash., Charles Bloomer of Middleton, Ky., Rodney
Fitz of Hixson, Tenn., and Leslie Shelton of Goldsboro, N.C.
   The Grayback, originally a missile-carrying sub, was converted
in the late 1960s to dispatch divers underwater.
   General Dynamics designed the diving chamber, which then was
built by the Navy.
   Court records said the Navy was aware of a problem with the
ventilation valve. It was difficult to turn and there were no
warning devices to tell the divers it was not open completely.
   But the sub operated safely for 13 years as the Navy, rather
than redesigning the system, chose to compensate for the problem by
training divers to cope.
   A federal judge in Texas ordered General Dynamics to pay $4.25
million to the victims' families. The Navy was not ordered to pay
any money.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the damage judgment
in February.
   The appeals court, interpreting a key 1988 Supreme Court ruling,
refused to shield General Dynamics from the award.
   The high court last year ruled that a military contractor is
protected from being sued when the government approves equipment
conforming to ``reasonably precise'' Pentagon specifications and
the company warns the government about any potential dangers of
which it is aware.
   The 5th Circuit court said that ruling does not protect General
Dynamics because the Navy, in effect, rubber-stamped the
contractor's design plans. Thus, the appeals court said, it was the
company rather than the Navy that exercised discretion over the
chamber's design.
   ``The government does not exercise a discretionary function by
merely approving the contractor's work,'' the appeals court said.
``If the government delegates its design discretion to the
contractor and allows the contractor to develop the design, the
government contractor defense (against being sued) does not apply.''
   Major military contractors and business groups joined General
Dynamics in urging the Supreme Court to overturn the 5th Circuit
court ruling.
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce said the appeals court ruling
undermines the 1988 Supreme Court decision and could discourage
companies from competing for military contracts.
   The case is General Dynamics vs. Trevino, 89-376.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0060 </DOCNO>
