<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Secrist     10-30 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Secrist,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Won't Revive Libel Suit Against Iowa Senator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired Marine lieutenant colonel who worked
for former Sen. Roger Jepsen, R-Iowa, lost a Supreme Court bid
today to revive a libel lawsuit against Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa,
and two others.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that threw out
James Secrist's suit.
   Secrist, while still an active-duty Marine, was assigned to
Jepsen's Senate office staff in 1983.
   The arrangement was a controversial one, with Secrist continuing
to be paid his $45,000 annual salary by the Marine Corps.
   Harkin, a House member at the time who ran against and defeated
Jepsen a in a 1984 Senate race, criticized his Republican
opponent's appointment of Secrist.
   Harkin distributed a statement to the news media that said
Secrist helped raise funds for Jepsen's campaign. The statement
disputed Jepsen's claim that Secrist was hired to help procure
defense contracts for Iowa businesses.
   Secrist retired from the Marines in 1985 to become a Washington
lobbyist for defense contractor Rockwell International Corp. In
1986 he sued Harkin; Pam McKinney, the senator's press secretary;
and Harkin's campaign manager, John Frew.
   Secrist said the 1984 news release was libelous because it
implied he solicited funds for Jepsen in violation of federal law.
Secrist and Jepsen denied that the former Marine solicited campaign
funds.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last May upheld a federal
judge's decision to throw out Secrist's suit.
   The appeals court said Harkin's campaign press release was
opinion, not fact.
   ``A campaign press release is not a research monograph,'' the
appeals court said. ``Such a release is at least as likely to
signal political opinion as a newspaper editorial or political
cartoon.''
   Only factual statements, not opinions, may be the basis of a
libel suit, the appeals court said.
   Also, the appeals court said, Secrist failed to prove actual
malice _ that the statements in the news release were made with
knowledge or reckless disregard of their falsity.
   Secrist said Harkin and his staff aides failed to investigate
before alleging the officer Marine was raising funds for Jepsen.
   But the appeals court said such a lack of investigation is not
``evidence of reckless disregard for the truth.''
   The case is Secrist vs. Harkin, 89-220.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
