<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Magazines     10-30 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Magazines,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Let Stand Rulings on `Adult' Magazines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand rulings that
may allow Urbana, Ohio, officials to ban as obscene five ``adult''
magazines generally not considered hard-core pornography.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by store owners
who said their free-speech rights were violated by the ban.
   Store owners Charles Downing and Paul Veneroni said the
magazines are known in the publications industry as ``adult
sophisticate'' magazines, similar to Playboy and Penthouse.
   ``Magazines of this genre generally contain erotic photographs
of a woman or a man or couples in various poses, often fully nude,
but avoid explicit depictions of sexual activity,'' the store
owners said.
   The magazines are Nuggets, Velvet, Juggs, Oui and Big Boobs.
   Copies were puchased by Urbana Law Director John Newlin on Nov.
25, 1985, at the Main News and Smoke Shop run by Downing and
Veneroni.
   A municipal judge ruled that the magazines are obscene, opening
the way for city officials to ban their sale in Urbana.
   The Ohio Supreme Court, by a 5-2 vote, upheld the ruling in May.
   ``Courts are not bound by the magazine industry's determination
of what is explicit,'' the state court said. ``All five magazines
contain either in the text, photographs or their advertisements
numerous depictions or descriptions of ultimate sexual acts. (They)
are legally obscene under Urbana ordinances.''
   For example, the state court said, there are ads in the
magazines showing sexual activity in which small black dots were
used to obscure sexual organs. The dots would ``not preclude a jury
from finding'' the pictures are obscene, the state court said.
   The store owners said the ban violates a 1973 Supreme Court
ruling that says material is obscene if the average person using
contemporary community standards finds it appeals to prurient
interests and depicts sexual acts in a patently offensive manner.
That ruling said the work must be judged as a whole, and must be
found to lack serious literary, artistic, political or scientific
value.
   The case is Downing vs. Urbana, 89-298.
</TEXT>
