<SECOND>PM-Devil's Night, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Devil's Night Period Begins in Detroit; 169 Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with arrest figures; deleting reference
to mayor's office planning to release fire totals today. Picks up 5th graf
pvs, `There were...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 169 young curfew violators on the
first night of a three-day campaign against Devil's Night arson, a
spokesman said today.
   Tens of thousands of citizen volunteers helped patrol streets
Sunday in efforts to reduce the number of arson fires stemming from
the traditional Halloween-time spree. City officials did not
release information today on the number of fires reported Sunday
night and this morning.
   For three nights beginning Sunday, those under 18 face arrest if
they are out without an adult between 6 p.m. and 6 a.m. Those age
17 are being charged with misdemeanor curfew violation, while
younger people are being released to the custody of a parent or
guardian.
   Police Sgt. Christopher Buck, who released the arrest totals
this morning, said he did not know how many of the 169 arrested
were age 17.
   Devil's Night drew national attention in 1984 when 810 fires
were set in Detroit. Since then, the number of fires has declined
each Devil's Night period.
   There were 229 fires reported during the three-day period last
year, an average of 76 per night. About 65 fires are reported on a
normal night in Detroit, fire officials say.
   An estimated 30,000 citizen volunteers were helping patrol
streets on Sunday, authorities said.
   Several fires in garages were reported Sunday night in Detroit's
lower east side. One abandoned home was set on fire twice in a
90-minute period. The second time it burned down and the fire
spread to an occupied home, according to radio station WWJ-AM.
   No injuries were reported in any of the fires.
   Police said they found explosives in a vacant home's garage on
Detroit's northeast side Sunday night, but weren't sure if it was
connected with Devil's Night activity.
   Seven cases of dynamite, six blasting caps and 200 feet of time
fuse were found, said Detroit Police spokesman Officer John
Leavens. No arrests were made and it is unknown when the explosives
were placed in the garage.
   The police bomb squad successfully disposed of the dynamite,
Leavens said.
</TEXT>
