<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Pullman     10-30 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Pullman,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders Further Study in Alabama Racial Bias Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ordered further study
in a lawsuit that's been in federal court for 18 years, in which
black workers allege racial bias at a railroad freight car plant in
Alabama.
   The justices, in a brief order, said the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals should restudy the case in light of three of their
recent civil rights rulings.
   In one key decision last summer, the justices made it harder to
win on-the-job bias cases by using statistics to show racial
disparities in an employer's workforce.
   The Bessemer, Ala., plant was at one time the world's largest
for building railroad freight cars. It employed 2,000 in 28
departments before being shut down in 1981.
   The appeals acted on today stem from a 1971 lawsuit accusing
Pullman-Standard and the United Steelworkers union of agreeing to a
contract that discriminated against blacks in hiring, training,
temporary assignments, promotions and in the company's seniority
system.
   The Supreme Court in 1982 overturned a federal appeals court
ruling that the seniority system violated the federal Civil Rights
Act of 1964. The justices said the appeals court exceeded its
authority in determining the seniority system intentionally was
biased.
   But the dispute was far from over. The high court left many
questions unanswered, including whether blacks seeking damages
proved the seniority rules had the effect of discriminating against
them even if unintentional.
   After ensuing lower court hearings, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals last year handed down a lengthy ruling that in part
favored the blacks and in part favored the company and the union.
   The appeals court said the workers proved the company's
procedures for picking supervisors had a discriminatory impact
against blacks.
   The appeals court also said the seniority system was not created
or maintained with discriminatory intent and that any
discrimination in department assignments ended by February 1969.
   But the appeals court, overturning part of a trial judge's
decision, said Pullman-Standard may be forced to pay damages for
racially discriminatory department assignments before February 1969.
   Pullman-Standard asked the Supreme Court to dismiss the suit.
The company said the appeals court relied incorrectly on
statistical evidence to show discriminatory effects.
   The company's lawyers also said the class-action suit on behalf
of all black workers at the plant was defective because some
employees who served as representatives of the class were
ineligible to sue.
   The black workers asked the justices to revive their attack on
the seniority system, and to make it easier to prove their claims
and win damages.
   The cases are Pullman-Standard vs. Swint, 88-1601, and Swint vs.
Pullman-Standard, 88-1602.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0066 </DOCNO>
