<FIRST>u a PM-FreighterAground 1stLd-Writethru a0505 10-30 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Freighter Aground, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0505,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Cargo Ship Runs Aground in Florida Keys</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Coast Guard spotted ship and
saw no visible leaks, no injuries, other detail. Picks up 5th graf, pvs,
`The dry ...' ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yugoslavian freighter ran aground in the
westernmost Florida Keys early today, the U.S. Coast Guard
reported. It was the second such accident along the 200-mile
stretch of islands within a week.
   The 475-foot container ship Mavro Vetranic grounded itself in
the Dry Tortugas, a cluster of islands about 70 miles west of Key
West, at about 3:45 a.m. EST, said Lt. Cmdr. Jeff Karonis, a Coast
Guard spokesman in Miami.
   Another ship relayed a message on the grounding to the Coast
Guard at 7:50 a.m., said Petty Officer James Wentworth. A Coast
Guard helicopter wasn't expected to reach the ship until late
morning.
   The Coast Guard had very few details of the accident, but
Karonis said there was no report of any spillage from the vessel's
fuel tanks. It wasn't immediately known what type of cargo the
Mavro Vetranic was carrying, if any, nor where the ship was headed,
said Karonis.
   ``There is no visible pollution, there's no injuries at the
moment, and the ship is hard aground,'' Petty Officer Alastair
Worden said after a Coast Guard helicopter flew over the
16-year-old ship.
   The Dry Tortugas is the site of Fort Jefferson National Monument
and is marked by a tall lighthouse as well as the massive fort,
famed for its use as a Union prison during the Civil War.
   A boat from the monument was headed to the ship, which ran
aground on the western edge of the Tortugas, said National Park
Service spokesman Pat Tolle.
   ``The coral reefs will be the concern in this particular
issue,'' Ms. Tolle said.
   The grounding came five days after a much smaller cargo ship,
the 155-foot Alec Owen Maitland, ran aground in the Key Largo
National Marine Sanctuary, about 50 miles southeast of Miami in the
Upper Florida Keys.
   First mate Michael Anthony Bishop, 43, has been charged with
negligence, and ship's captain Duane Godwin, 37, has been charged
with allowing a person without the proper license to operate the
vessel.
   Bishop failed two breath-alcohol tests administered about five
hours after the grounding, but he told Coast Guard officials that
he began drinking only after the accident.
</TEXT>
