<FIRST>r a PM-GETrial     10-30 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GE Trial,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>GE Goes On Trial On Defense Fraud Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the second time in four years, General
Electric Co. went to court today to face charges of defrauding the
defense department.
   General Electric and two employees were accused of cheating the
Pentagon of $10 million. The company, the country's second-largest
defense contractor, faces a fine of $71.9 million if convicted.
   Since the 321-count indictment was returned in November, GE
consistently denied shortchanging the government in a $270 million
contract to make a battlefield computer system.
   The company has acknowledged, however, that an internal
investigation uncovered discrepancies totaling $3.69 million. GE
refunded that money before the indictment was handed up in U.S.
District Court.
   Clayton Undercoffler, GE attorney, said the trial is expected to
last at least two months.
   According to the Pentagon, officials at a GE subsidiary,
Management and Techinical Services Co., based in suburban King of
Prussia, padded costs and failed to notify the Pentagon of savings
negotiated with subcontractors.
   In May 1985, the company pleaded guilty to illegally claiming
$800,000 in cost overruns on Minuteman intercontinental ballistic
missiles and paid a $1.04 million fine.
   GE does approximately $6 billion annually in Defense Department
business that ranges from jet engines and electronic warfare
equipment to highly classified strategic work.
   Jury selection began this morning in the case, which will
scrutinize how GE handled its billing.
   Accused with GE were James Badolato, 41, of Springfield, the
former subcontracts manager for MATSCO, and Gerald A. Leo, 51, of
King of Prussia, MATSCO's materials manager.
   Badolato and Leo were charged with racketeering, five counts of
mail fraud, making false statements and concealing material facts
from a federal agency.
   Both men are now working for GE in other departments.
   GE, which was charged with five acts of mail fraud and with
making 312 false statements to the government, tried unsuccessfully
to settle the case out of court.
   Last week, at a pre-trial hearing before U.S. District Judge
Lowell Reed Jr., the government sought internal company papers GE
has declined to provide on grounds they are privileged
attorney-client communications. The judge reserved decision.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Nicholas Harbist, who is prosecuting
with David Harris, argued the government needed the documents to
rebut any GE efforts to show good corporate character.
</TEXT>
