<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Rodriguez     10-30 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Rodriguez,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Using Chicago Case to Consider Expanding Search Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to use a
Chicago drug prosecution to consider expanding police search powers.
   The justices said they will hear arguments that police, acting
without a warrant, should be allowed to use evidence seized after
they were allowed into a man's apartment by his girlfriend.
   The defendant, Edward Rodriguez, was arrested on July 26, 1985,
on charges he possessed cocaine and marijuana with intent to
distribute the drugs. Police said the drugs and drug paraphernalia
were in plain view at Rodriguez's apartment.
   Gale Fisher, who lived with Rodriguez part-time, summoned police
to her mother's home on July 26. She told them Rodriguez had beaten
her at the couple's apartment and she wanted to make a complaint.
   The police then accompanied her to Rodriguez's apartment and she
opened the door with a key. She later testified that she took the
key from Rodriguez's dresser after the two argued earlier that day.
   An Illinois appeals court said police violated the defendant's
rights because Ms. Fisher lacked authority to let the police into
the apartment.
   Police may not enter and search a home without a warrant ``if
the party who consented to the entry had apparent authority to do
so but lacked actual authority,'' the state appeals court said.
   The appeals court noted that Ms. Fisher's name was not on the
apartment lease and she did not help pay the rent. Also, the state
court said, she was an infrequent visitor and did not have access
to the apartment when Rodriguez was not there. She also had moved
her clothes and children to her mother's home, the state court
noted.
   ``All of these factors indicate that Fisher did not have the
common authority over the defendant's apartment that was necessary
to make her consent to enter valid,'' the state court added.
   The Illinois attorney general's office, in appealing to the
Supreme Court, said police acted in good faith when they relied on
Ms. Fisher's ``apparent authority to permit entry into the home.''
   The Supreme Court in 1974 ruled that when one occupant of a home
consents to a search of the premises, evidence police find may be
used against another occupant.
   The case is Illinois vs. Rodriguez, 88-2018.
</TEXT>
