<SECOND>PM-Costa Rica Notebook, 1st ld-writethru, a0449,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Baker `Blindsided' Opponents on the Tennis Courts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling to Deane sted Dean in 3rd graf, When Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Rodrigo Borja of Ecuador
might think twice the next time he's asked to play tennis with
President Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   The Ecuadoran ended up hobbling on crutches with a cast on his
foot after a morning on the court during the two-day ceremony
honoring Costa Rican democracy.
   When Bush and Baker spoke to a group of Americans at Ambassador
Deane Hinton's house on Saturday, they were gloating about their
6-1 doubles victory over Borja and Argentine President Carlos Menem
that morning.
   ``We blindsided those guys. It was great,'' Bush said, laughing.
``No, it was wonderful.''
   What he didn't say, but later told reporters on Air Force One,
was that Borja had fallen on the court and ``got badly hurt.''
   Borja's doctor was present, and after a brief consultation
allowed his patient to briefly go back to the game, said one
observer.
   But later Borja showed up on crutches at the dedication of San
Jose's Plaza of Democracy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Bush's visit to the ambassador's house wasn't all lightness.
About 20 American students staged a silent human rights protest at
the back of the crowd inside the embassy.
   A few hundred embassy workers and other Americans had come to
see Bush, and the students said they had only to show their U.S.
citizenship to get in.
   Dressed in black, they held up small signs, each bearing the
name of a person from El Salvador, Guatemala or Honduras, and the
word ``Disappeared,'' and ``U.S. $'' The students also held up
large sheet banners reading ``Shame,'' and ``Democracy: Social and
political equality and respect for the individual. Look it up,
George.''
   The students said they were protesting U.S. aid to countries
that still engage in human rights violations. It was not clear if
Bush noticed them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Local security for the multinational conference was so rigid
that even reporters, staying in hotels a few miles from the meeting
site and Bush's hotel, were kept under close guard.
   The press hotels were cleared of other guests and only those
wearing press or staff credentials were allowed in the door.
   Throughout San Jose was a show of armed force that was rare in
the small country, the only nation in the region with no army.
   Police troops were called in from around the country to help
provide security for Bush, Colombian President Virgilio Barco and
the other heads of state.
   Armed officers were stationed along the major highway and on
most of the bridges. The usually crowded four-lane highway was
closed Friday and Saturday to all traffic except vehicles on
official business.
   Helping to ease demands on the roads, President Oscar Arias
declared Friday a national holiday.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   When Bush arrived in Costa Rica, much of the attention was on
whether he would shake hands with Nicaraguan President Daniel
Ortega.
   They did that. But by the time he left town, Bush vented some
harsh feelings about the Nicaraguan he called a ``little man'' who
was ``always kind of sidling up to me for some photo op.''
   Ortega used the occasion on Friday to threaten to break the
cease-fire with the Contra rebels.
   The U.S. delegation gave him the cold shoulder that night during
a gala dinner. Asked if Bush and Ortega had talked at a cocktail
party before the dinner, Nicaraguan Ambassador to Costa Rica Saul
Arana said, ``Not even eye contact.''
   It was Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney whom Ortega
engaged at the dinner table.
   While Honduran President Jose Azcona sat quietly between them,
Ortega talked nonstop to Mulroney during the time a group of
photographers and reporters was in the room.
   Earlier, when Ortega was telling reporters on what he said to
Bush during their handshake meeting, Mulroney seemed eager to chime
in on behalf of his U.S. friend.
   Asked what he saw of the Bush-Ortega conversation, he said he
``didn't see them having a conversation. I saw them having a
courtesy chat.''
</TEXT>
