<FIRST>r a PM-BoyAbducted     10-30 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boy Abducted,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Guard Searchs For Abducted Boy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOSEPH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Guard troops resumed their
search this morning in the woods and fields near the spot where an
11-year-old boy was abducted by a masked gunman eight days ago.
   About 225 National Guard troops and 80 Minnesota Department of
Natural Resources workers searched unsuccessfully Sunday for clues
in the abduction of Jacob Wetterling, while supporters of the boy's
family released more than 1,000 white balloons after a church
service.
   ``There's a lot of power here, a lot of hope. I've got to feel
very hopeful,'' said the missing boy's mother, Patty Wetterling.
   A highway into St. Joseph, a town of about 3,000 some 80 miles
northwest of Minneapolis, was blocked Sunday night as authorities
stopped drivers to ask if they had been in the vicinity the evening
of Oct. 22, when the boy was kidnapped.
   Those who had were shown three composite sketches of possible
suspects. Authorities earlier had released one of the sketches, a
picture of a man wearing glasses who is believed to have tried to
kidnap a 10-year-old boy in Stearns County during the summer.
   The other two sketches will not be released to the public until
authorities follow leads from Sunday night's roadblock questioning,
an agent at the Stearns County Law Enforcement Center said.
   Jacob, described as a top student and hockey player, was
abducted at gunpoint by a masked man on a dark stretch of road less
than a mile from his home on the town's outskirts. The incident
occurred as Jacob, his 10-year-old brother, Trevor, and an
11-year-old friend were returning from a convenience store about
9:30 p.m.
   The abductor asked the boys how old they were then held onto
Jacob and threatened to shoot the other two unless they ran away.
   The release of the helium-filled balloons, each labeled with the
words ``Jacob's Hope,'' was another attempt by the town to sustain
the search's momentum.
   ``I think they (the balloons) are sending out all our love all
over the place and I don't think there is a place that is going to
be untouched by this,'' Mrs. Wetterling said.
   A white sweat sock found Saturday near the kidnapping site was
to be analyzed today at the state crime lab to determine if it is
linked to the abduction, sheriff's officials said.
   ``There's been no additional finding of clues,'' said State
National Guard Maj. Nate Thomas. The search stretched from dawn to
dark each day over the weekend.
   Oakland Athletics catcher Terry Steinbach, a Minnesota native,
wore a ``J'' on the back of his batting helmet during the fourth
game of the World Series in San Francisco on Saturday night to help
focus nationwide attention on the search for Jacob.
</TEXT>
