<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Pensions 1stLd-Writethru a0513 10-30 1080</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Pensions, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Will Review Pension Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 5-19, In other action, with other cases.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to review a
ruling government lawyers say threatens the federal program
protecting the pensions of 30 million American workers.
   The justices said they will decide what authority the Pension
Benefit Guaranty Corporation, a federal agency, has to order
employers to restore terminated pension plans.
   A federal appeals court limited such authority by setting aside
the agency's order that LTV Corp. and its subsidiary, LTV Steel
Co., restore three pension plans with unfunded liabilities of $2.3
billion.
   The appeal acted on today said the ruling, if not overturned,
could make the agency ``an open-ended source of industry bailouts''
and ``could lead to a financial crisis similar to that currently
facing'' the government's insurance program for the savings and
loan industry.
   In other action, the court:
   _ Turned away an appeal by a Nebraska state agency that wants to
test its employees for AIDS.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that blocked the
Eastern Nebraska Human Services Agency from imposing mandatory
blood testing of employees who come into direct contact with the
mentally retarded people the agency serves.
   _ Agreed to use a Chicago drug prosecution to consider expanding
police search powers.
   The justices said they will hear arguments that police, acting
without a warrant, should be allowed to use evidence seized after
they were allowed into a man's apartment by his girlfriend.
   _ Barred a lawsuit against the Christian Science church in the
death of a 15-month-old Michigan boy who died of meningitis.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that a suit
against the church and its members over faith healing would violate
their religious freedom.
   _ Rejected an appeal by an American Humanist Association member
who says he should have as much right as an ordained minister to
perform marriage ceremonies.
   The court, without comment, refused to hear arguments that a
Virginia law favoring ministers violates religious freedom and the
constitutionally required separation of church and state.
   _ Refused to hear appeals by three drug manufacturers fighting
lawsuits over the effects of DES, a drug once used by pregnant
women to prevent miscarriages.
   The court, without comment, left intact a New York ruling aimed
at forcing all manufacturers of the drug to share in paying damages
for injuries allegedly caused by DES.
   _ Turned away an appeal by a former Beech-Nut executiv e
fighting his conviction for selling adulterated apple juice.
   The court, without comment, left intact John F. Lavery's
sentence of a year and a day in prison and a $100,000 fine.
   _ Turned down an appeal by James Earl Ray, who is serving a
99-year prison sentence for the assassination of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that Ray's rights
were not violated 20 years ago when he pleaded guilty to
first-degree murder.
   The Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation, modeled after the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., is wholly owned by the federal government. Its
board of directors is comprised of the secretaries of labor,
treasury and commerce.
   The agency protects the pension benefits of the 30 million
Americans who participate in single-employer defined benefit
pension plans.
   When a pension plan is ended with insufficient money to satisfy
promised benefits, the federal agency becomes the pension plan's
trustee, taking over its assets and liabilities. The agency then
pays all benefits workers had earned as of the date the pension
plan ended.
   In fiscal year 1988, the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation
paid $324.7 million in insured benefits to 113,000 retirees who
participated in 1,476 terminated pension plans.
   The cost of the pension insurance is paid primarily by employers
with active pension plans, and by employers who terminate
underfunded pension plans.
   The agency has money problems of its own. In its most recent
annual report, the PBGC listed liabilities of $4 billion and assets
of $2.4 billion.
   The Dallas-based LTV Corp. and LTV Steel, after filing for
reorganization under federal bankruptcy law in 1986, advised the
PBGC that they could not and would not fund the three pension plans
they sponsored. The plans, which have about 100,000 participants,
were terminated in 1987.
   In a deal with the United Steelworkers of America union,
however, LTV Steel agreed to what government lawyers contend is a
``follow-on'' arrangement. Under it, LTV agreed to make up any
benefits lost to employees because of the pension plans'
termination _ those benefits not covered by the federal pension
insurance program.
   The result: employees continued to receive the same benefits
they did before the plans were terminated, and payment of unfunded
pension liabilities was shifted to the PBGC.
   LTV was responsible for $75 million in annual supplemental
retirement benefits, and the federal agency was making good on some
$400 million in annual obligations to LTV pensioners.
   The PBGC contends such arrangements are abusive, and the agency
ordered LTV to reassume responsibility for the three pension plans.
   When LTV refused, the agency sought to enforce its order in
federal court.
   A federal judge threw out the PBGC's order for restoration of
the pension plans, and the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld
that ruling last May 12.
   Federal law ``reveals no indication that Congress intended the
establishment of successive benefit plans to be a ground for
restoration,'' the appeals court ruled.
   It also said the PBGC's action was ``arbitrary and capricious''
because it failed to consider the goals of federal bankruptcy and
labor laws when issuing its restoration order.
   The PBGC then sought Supreme Court review, contending that the
2nd Circuit court's ruling ``places the pension insurance program
in serious financial jeopardy'' and ignores what Congress attempted
to achieve in passing the Employee Retirement Income Security Act
of 1974 (ERISA).
   ``Other companies will follow LTV's example and use pension
insurance as a subsidy to reduce costs and gain a competitive
edge,'' the appeal said.
   Justice Department lawyers sided with the PBGC, telling the high
court, ``The PBGC has reasonably concluded that restoration is an
appropriate response to the adoption of abusive follow-on plans.''
They said the appeals court ruling ``threatens to undermine ... a
program already seriously in debt.''
   But lawyers for LTV said Congress ``specifically rejected
proposed prohibitions on follow-on plans'' when substantially
amending ERISA in 1987.
   The case is PBGC vs. LTV, 89-390.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0529 10-30 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0529,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Sentenced to Life for Forcing Bus Off Cliff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CORRECT convict's name to Abdel Hadi Ghanem
sted Mahdi Abdel Ghanem, ADD comment from prosecutor; pickup 6th graf pvs,
`The victims...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city district court today sentenced a
Palestinian to 16 life terms for forcing a bus off a cliff, killing
16 people, Israel radio reported.
   The court gave Abdel Hadi Ghanem a life sentence for each of the
passengers who died in the crash and 20-year sentences for each of
the 24 passengers injured, said the state prosecutor, Uzi Hasson.
   Hasson said it was the stiffest sentence since the start of the
22-month Palestinian uprising against the Israeli occupation of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip. He said Ghanem is ineligible for parole
and can only be freed by a presidential pardon.
   ``It was a terrorist killing of 16 innocent people who were only
trying to travel home safely. They were young, they were old, men,
women. They found their deaths by the accused, but they did nothing
wrong,'' Hasson said in an interview.
   The bus was en route to Jerusalem from Tel Aviv on July 6 when
Ghanem grabbed the steering wheel and forced the bus into a deep
ravine.
   The victims included an American woman and two Canadian tourists.
   Ghanem, who also was injured in the incident, said he decided to
carry out a suicide attack after soldiers shot and wounded his best
friend in a clash near his home in the Gaza Strip's Nusseirat
refugee camp. His friend was paralyzed as a result of the incident.
   At least 607 Palestinians have been killed by Israelis in the
Palestinian revolt against the Israeli occupation. An addition 137
Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs, most as suspected
collaborators with Israel. Forty Israelis have died.
   The latest victim was a 24-year-old Palestinian who died today
of a gunshot wound suffered five days ago in the Farah refugee camp
in the West Bank, the army said.
   He was identified as Hussein Mohammad Hassani and the army said
he was about to throw a cement building block at soldiers when he
was hit.
   News of Hassani's death sparked demonstrations in the Farah
camp, and the army imposed a curfew on the area. Two Palestinians
were wounded, including a 17-year-old youth who was shot in the
chest, the army said.
   In a stone-throwing clash with soldiers in the Gaza Strip's
Shabura refugee camp, a 14-year-old Palestinian was critically
wounded when he was hit in the head with a plastic bullet, Arab
reports said.
   The youth, identified as Ashraf Kishda, was taken to Soroka
Hospital in Israel, the reports said.
   A Canadian television correspondent was hit in the leg by a
rubber-coated metal pellet fired by soldiers as he filmed the
clash. He was identified as Jean Francois Lepine of the Canadian
Broadcasting Corp.
   Israeli newspapers reported that the army soon will begin
deploying observation balloons equipped with cameras to pinpoint
rioting related to the uprising.
   The army spokesman's office declined comment on the reports,
which said the unmanned balloons will be floated over refugee camps
and other areas and transmit live photos to ground forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
