<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Soviet-Oil     10-30 0111</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet-Oil,0113</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets May Cut Oil Exports Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union on Monday said it might cut oil
exports by about 76,000 barrels a day in 1990 so the fuel could be
used domestically.
   The proposal, which amounts to a cut of roughly 2.8 percent of
estimated Soviet oil exports of 2.8 million barrels per day, came
in documents submitted to the Soviet legislature's discussion of
the 1990 budget.
   The Soviet Union suffers erratic domestic gasoline shortages,
and Soviet TV has shown farms unable to harvest grain for lack of
fuel. Officials have said recent coal strikes could result in power
shortages during the long winter.
</TEXT>
