<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Egypt-US     10-30 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Egypt-US,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint Military Exercises Next Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Egyptian military forces will hold
joint military exercises Nov. 11-17, the air force commander said
Monday.
   ``We benefit from these maneuvers by getting acquainted with the
most advanced weapons and through our direct contact with the U.S.
military,'' Lt. Gen. Alaa Barakat told a news conference marking
the 57th anniversary of the establishment of the Egyptian air force.
   The exercises will be the fifth in the series of ``Bright Star''
war games the two countries have held every two years since 1981.
The last maneuvers were staged in Egypt in August 1987, with more
than 9,000 troops from each side participating.
   Cairo receives $1.3 billion in military aid and $865 million in
economic assistance from the United States. Egypt is the
second-largest recipient of U.S. foreign aid after Israel.
   Barakat also said that in 1991, Egypt will receive 40 F-16
fighters, among the most advanced in the world. Egypt already has
taken delivery of 80 F-16s.
</TEXT>
