<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     10-30 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Scaling Down Martial Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed police will replace soldiers in Tiananmen
Square and troops have been withdrawn from intersections in a major
scaling down of the capital's 5-month-old martial law, officials
said Monday.
   The move appeared a test of Beijing's stability before martial
law is lifted completely, which a government spokesman recently
said will happen ``before very long.''
   Premier Li Peng ordered martial law in most of Beijing on May 20
as hundreds of thousands of students and citizens marched through
the streets daily to demand democratic reform. The army ended the
protests June 3-4 by shooting its way through the crowd to retake
Tiananmen Square, the demonstrators' base.
   ``Since achieving a decisive victory in the struggle to quell
the counterrevolutionary rebellion, the situation in the capital is
moving daily toward stability and social order is basically
normal,'' the city government and martial law command post said in
an announcement on the local TV news.
   ``Therefore ... effective upon announcement of this order,
martial law sentinels at overpasses and intersections will
completely withdraw.''
   As of Monday night, overpasses where soldiers had stood around
the clock under brightly colored umbrellas were unguarded except
for surveillance cameras on lampposts. The only soldiers in view in
the city center were around the perimeter of Tiananmen Square and
at nearby intersections.
   Few military trucks were on the streets Monday night. On recent
nights, convoys of hundreds of trucks of troops and supplies have
been seen moving through the city, their destination unclear.
   The order said soldiers in Tiananmen Square will be replaced
Tuesday by ordinary police and People's Armed Police, a special
security unit.
   It made clear, however, that martial law was not being lifted.
   ``Some soldiers stationed in the city and suburbs, together with
police and People's Armed Police, will continue in some districts
to carry out their martial law duties,'' it said.
   ``We hope that all city residents will voluntarily respect
martial law orders and regulations and actively uphold the
capital's normal work, production, education, scientific research
and social order.''
   Martial law orders forbid marches, strikes, class boycotts,
public speeches, distributing pamphlets, spreading rumors and other
``destructive activity.''
   Large-scale resistance to martial law was crushed in the week
after the June 3-4 army attack, and since then only isolated cases
of civilians attacking soldiers have been reported. The government
said many guns were stolen from army trucks during the troops'
sometimes-bumbling entry into Beijing, and that martial law was
necessary to protect social order.
   Gunshots still ring out at night without any official
explanation.
   The number of troops visible in the city has fallen sharply
since midsummer, when at least 150,000 were stationed along main
roads and in key facilities such as the television station and
Great Hall of the People.
   Only several dozen now guard the perimeter of Tiananmen Square,
restricting access to what used to be a favorite recreation spot.
They are armed with automatic rifles and wear helmets.
   Despite the reduction in troop presence, martial law has
discouraged many tourists from returning, and Western diplomats
have indicated that lifting martial law is a minimum requirement
for their governments to lift sanctions imposed in June. Most
Western governments have halted high-level contacts and military
sales, and have opposed new low-interest loans to China by
international institutions such as the World Bank.
   Government spokesman Yuan Mu said last week martial law was
``for a limited time and it seems that it will be lifted before
very long.'' He refused to disclose a date.
</TEXT>
