<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--China-Music     10-30 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Music,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Musicians Leaving China, Causing Talent Shortage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China is facing a musical talent shortage because
top artists are leaving for foreign countries, an official daily
said Monday.
   The China Youth News said 470 musicians, mostly highly skilled
professionals, have gone abroad at their own expense in the past
decade. The newspaper implied that few are likely to return.
   The daily said the exodus includes musicians from the Central
Conservatory of Music, the Central Ballet Ensemble, the Central
Philharmonic Society and the Central Opera Theater.
   Unlike writers, film directors and artists who have left China
for political reasons, most departing musicians are seeking to
escape the restrictive atmosphere of being locked into one group or
genre and live in a place where they have more freedom to express
their musical talents.
   The daily said the musicians have left for the United States,
France, Italy, Japan, West Germany, Australia, Canada, Austria,
Switzerland, Belgium and Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
