<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-PortAuthority     10-30 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Port Authority,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Will Decide Port Authority Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case likely to affect
other multi-state agencies, agreed today to decide whether a New
York-New Jersey transportation authority may be sued in federal
court.
   The justices said they would hear arguments by the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey seeking to kill lawsuits by
two employees.
   The authority was created in 1921 in a Congress-approved compact
between the two states. It operates airports, trains linking New
Jersey and New York City and other transportation facilities.
   The authority is run by 12 commissioners, six each appointed by
the governors of the respective states. The governors also have
veto power over actions by the commissioners.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals based in New York City
ruled in April that Port Authority employees Charles T. Foster and
Patrick Feeney may sue the agency in federal court. The appeals
court said the 11th Amendment to the Constitution shielding states
from federal court suits does not apply to the interstate agency.
   The 2nd Circuit court said the authority may be sued for money
damages largely because any judgment it would be forced to pay
would come from its revenues rather than the taxpayer-supported
treasuries of the two states.
   ``We believe that this insulation of state treasuries from the
liabilities of the Port Authority outweighs both the methods of
(commisioner) appointment and gubernatorial veto,'' the appeals
court said.
   The appeals court invited the Supreme Court to review the
ruling, noting that the Philadelphia-based 3rd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals has issued a conflicting ruling on the authority's
immunity from suit.
   The 2nd Circuit court said the 3rd Circuit was in error in
concluding that the taxpayers of New York and New Jersey could be
forced to pay damages if a suit depleted the agency's resources.
   Feeney is seeking $3 million for injuries he suffered while
working at a maintenance shop run by the authority in 1986.
   The case is Port Authority vs. Feeney, 89-386.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
