<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-EcclesiasticalTrial     10-30 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ecclesiastical Trial,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Recommends Two-Year Suspension of Embattled Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A socially active inner-city Episcopal
priest who sued his diocese and its bishop lied when he accused
them of conspiring to control his parish's money, a church panel
concluded today.
   In the first ecclesiastical trial ever held in the Newark
diocese, the five priests on the panel unanimously recommended that
the Rev. George Swanson be suspended for two years from ministerial
or administrative involvement in the church. Bishop John S. Spong
must still approve the recommendation, and Swanson's attorney said
he would appeal.
   Swanson, who filed the lawsuit in 1988 accusing Spong and the
diocese of engaging in a conspiracy against his tiny Jersey City
parish, did not show any emotion as the recommendation was read.
The lawsuit was dismissed from Superior Court on the grounds it was
a church matter, but Swanson is appealing that decision.
   About 20 Ascencion Church parishioners, who had gathered at
diocesean headquarters for the verdict, appeared stunned but
remained quiet.
   Swanson, 56, a San Francisco native, has headed the church in a
poverty-stricken Jersey City neighborhood for 12 years.
   Teresa Russell, a parishioner for eight years, said Sunday that
Swanson had drawn her back into the Episcopal church with social
activism and efforts to make religion relevant to current problems.
Swanson wore a button at today's announcement of the verdict urging
South Africa to free black activist Nelson Mandela.
   Swanson's attorney, Edwin Robertson, said the priest would
appeal to the church's provincial court of review.
   The panel decided that Swanson had known that the allegations he
made in the suit were false.
   ``The filing of the secular court action ... should never be
done lightly or unadvisedly and certainly not before exploring
other avenues,'' the panel said. The group ruled that Swanson
failed to make a good-faith effort to settle the dispute.
   Swanson, who has been banned from practicing his priestly duties
since March, was the first church official to face an
ecclesiastical trial since the Episcopal diocese was founded 113
years ago.
   In his lawsuit, Swanson charged that Spong, diocese vice
chancellor Michael Rehill and the diocese itself manipulated canon
law to try to take control of the parish's assets, including
$600,000 paid out by an insurance company after a fire all but
destroyed the church in 1986.
   At the end of the nine-day trial Thursday, diocese prosecutor
Richard B. McGlynn called Swanson a ``failed priest'' and a
``liar.''
   On Sunday, in the smoke-stained chapel of Ascencion Church, a
small cluster of faithful rallied on behalf of the priest. The
chapel is all that remains of the church. It has received only
makeshift repairs since the fire because the parish's funds became
embroiled in a legal battle with the diocese.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
