<FIRST>r w AM-US-China 550   10-30 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China, 550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engineers Back at Work on Arms Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A handful of Chinese engineers in the United
States to aid a $600 million arms sale to China have returned to
work on the program, but the State Department said Monday that
weapons deliveries suspended by President Bush in June have not
resumed.
   Officials, responding to a report in the Los Angeles Times,
stressed that Bush had suspended shipments _ not ended them _ after
the Beijing government cracked down on pro-democracy demonstrators.
   The Chinese engineers, who apparently did not leave the United
States over the summer, returned during the last few weeks to the
Grumman factory in Bethpage, N.Y., ``to provide technical support
which will enable U.S. work to continue during the suspension,'' a
State Department official said.
   The main parts of the deal with China are a program to improve
avionics on F-8 jets and the manufacture of torpedos, radar and
artillery ammunition.
   ``In view of the long-term interest of the United States, it has
always been the president's intention to suspend _ not terminate _
US-People's Republic of China FMS (foreign military sales)
programs, with the hope that circumstances would permit a
resumption of normal relations,'' said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Still, the official added: ``There are no deliveries. The
president's decision remains in effect.''
   The sanctions imposed by Bush were considered inadequate by
several members of Congress who called for harsher measures as an
expression of U.S. human rights convictions.
   The bloody June 4 crackdown on students in Tiananmen Square in
Beijing was seen by millions of Americans on television,
contributing to public criticism here of the Communist government
as it reversed a moderating trend.
   But Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III emphasized
then that maintaining strong ties with Beijing was in the strategic
interest of the United States.
   Two other sanctions, apart from a halt to weapons deliveries,
have been reversed or watered down since June.
   The president's ban on the visit of high-level U.S. officials to
China did not preclude Baker from meeting with Qian Qichen, the
Chinese foreign minister, at a conference on Cambodia in Paris at
the end of July.
   Also, dependents of American diplomats who were evacuated from
the U.S. Embassy in Beijing and U.S. consulates returned weeks
later.
   On Monday, former President Richard Nixon, the most prominent
American to visit China since the military crackdown, called on the
two nations to restore good relations and urged Chinese leaders to
shun the ``backwater of oppression and stagnation'' and respect the
yearnings of their people.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Nixon spoke with
Bush and National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft before he left
for China. However, Fitzwater said he did not know if Nixon was
carrying a letter from Bush to the Chinese leadership.
   Responding to Nixon's call for normalized relations between the
two countries, Fitzwater said:
   ``We have always said that we want to resume good relations with
China at some point. The question really is, when and under what
conditions? I would say that at this point we have not reached that
time and we have not seen the right conditions.''
</TEXT>
