<HEAD>Guerrillas Bomb Army Headquarters, Witnesses Say at Least One Person
Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with witness accounts and five injured;
ADDS byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas today
attacked the Defense Ministry and headquarters of the joint chiefs
of staff with homemade mortars, killing at least one person and
wounding five, witnesses said.
   The witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
rebels fired eight to 10 mortars from the beds of two trucks parked
300 yards from the heavily fortified military compound.
   Two of the mortars fell short and exploded at a gasoline
station, killing Ernesto Vasquez, 72, an attendant, as he was
filling up an automobile, the witnesses said. They said two other
attendants were wounded.
   The gas station was heavily damaged, but there was no fire.
   Another mortar exploded at a nearby fried chicken restaurant,
causing extensive damage and wounding one boy, the witnesses said.
   Two more mortars blew up at the entrance of the military
compound and three more exploded in a parking lot at a nearby
baseball stadium, wounding at least one soldier and one civilian,
the witnesses said.
   The military issued a statement that said one civilian was
killed and at least two injured in the attack.
   It said one of the injured was a civilian employee who worked in
the general staff headquarters of the Armed Forces high command.
   Maj. Mauricio Chavez Caceres, a military spokesman, said no
bombs fell inside the military compound. However, a soldier on duty
at the gate said two landed inside.
   The witnesses said they saw a wounded soldier, in combat dress,
being evacuated from the compound.
   The rebels staged a similar attack on the Defense Ministry
headquarters inside the compound Dec. 23, killing three people and
wounding 38.
</TEXT>
