<DOCNO> AP891030-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Katyn     10-30 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Katyn,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brzezinski: Soviets Should Take Responsibility for Katyn Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATYN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. National Security Adviser
Zbigniew Brzezinski visited the site where more than 4,300 Polish
officers were slain in World War II, and he called on the Soviet
Union to take responsibility for the massacre.
   At the same time of Brzezinski's visit to the memorial to the
officers in the Katyn Forest, 17 miles south of the Byelorussian
city of Smolensk, a group of more than 400 Polish relatives of the
dead arrived for a commemorative Mass.
   ``It's purely a coincidence,'' Brzezinski said when asked if he
knew the Polish group was coming. He was visiting Katyn while in
the Soviet Union to participate in an East-West conference.
   A monument at the site pays tribute to the ``victims of Fascism
_ Polish officers shot by the Nazis in 1941.'' However, most Poles
and Western historians believe the officers, the cream of the
Polish intelligentsia, were killed by the NKVD, Stalin's secret
police, in 1940 after they were deported to Soviet Union following
the outbreak of World War II.
   The Nazis discovered the graves in 1943 and blamed the Soviet
Union, but the Soviets said the Nazis had murdered the men in 1941,
during the German army's march on Moscow.
   ``We owe it to the families of the victims to say that this was
done by Stalin and the NKVD,'' Brzezinski said.
   ``These victims represented a community of suffering shared by
the Polish and Soviet people ... the truth of what happened should
be a point of reconciliation for both countries,'' he said.
   A Soviet-Polish historical commission set up by President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski to
clear up historical ``blank spots'' has yet to deliver a final
verdict on the controversy, which for Poles remains their most
painful wartime memory.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said in Warsaw
last week that the Soviet Union was still conducting investigations
and searching for documents, but that it was interested in finding
``the truth.''
   Many Poles hope the matter will be cleared up by the time Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki makes his first visit to Moscow in
November.
   The Polish side pre-empted a joint declaration on responsibility
in August when the Polish head of the commission, Jarema
Macizewski, said that documents show the Soviet Union was
responsible.
   Brzezinski, known for his staunch anti-communist views,
indicated he believed the Soviets would ultimately change their
version of the massacre.
   ``The fact that the Soviet government has enabled me to be here
_ and the Soviets know my views _ is symbolic of the breach with
Stalinism that perestroika represents,'' Brzezinski said, referring
to Gorbachev's political and economic reform program.
   Until the Solidarity trade union was born in 1980-81, Katyn was
officially a taboo subject in Poland.
   But a group calling itself the Families of Katyn Victims has
thousands of members throughout Poland. More than 400 arrived in
Smolensk on the first special train organized by the Polish and
Soviet tourist agencies.
   It was the largest group of Poles ever to visit Katyn since
Soviet authorities began allowing Poles to visit in groups about
one year ago.
   ``We never thought we would be able to come here,'' said
Agnieszka Stawowczyk, whose father was killed at Katyn.
   Three priests celebrated Mass in front of a wooden cross, which
was surrounded by wreaths and Solidarity banners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
