<SECOND>PM-Litmus Test, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Says No Ideological Tests For U.S. Scientific Jobs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to add quotes from speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aspirants to top scientific jobs in the
federal government will not have to pass an ideological test on
abortion and other political issues, Health and Human Services
Secretary Louis Sullivan says.
   Sullivan said in a speech Sunday at a meeting the Association of
American Medical Colleges that the so-called ``litmus test'' would
not be used to gauge applicants for jobs in his department.
   The secretary said the decision was meant to end the controversy
over such political tests and ``to clear the air and not have a
cloud hanging over these positions,'' according to The New York
Times.
   But Sullivan said it was ``necessary and proper'' for President
Bush to use the litmus test to fill top positions in the
administration, including those of HHS secretary and assistant
secretary for health, in order to select people who share his views.
   ``In the case of research administrators beneath that level,
however _ the leadership of the National Institutes of Health, the
Centers for Disease Control and other major federal agencies _ it
has been our policy that standards of scientific and administrative
excellence and leadership prevail in the selection process,''
Sullivan said.
