<FIRST>r w AM-ElSalvadorRefugees     10-30 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-El Salvador Refugees,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Refugees Want Legal Status, End to Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Salvadoran refugees met on the
steps of the Capitol on Monday to demand legal status in the United
States, an end to aid to the government of El Salvador and support
for negotiations to end the 10-year-old war.
   The meeting marked an end to a five-week caravan by 25
Salvadorans to 68 cities to explain the plight of the thousands of
refugees seeking to remain in the United States.
   ``We applaud the passage of the ... bill in the House of
Representatives, which would temporarily give Salvadorans the right
to live and work legally in the U.S.,'' the group, calling itself
the Salvadoran Refugee Caravan, said in a prepared statement. ``We
call on the Senate to likewise approve this bill, as a humanitarian
gesture that is in accordance with the democratic values of this
country.''
   The Salvadorans also called on the United States to stop backing
the government of Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani, whose
party they said has ``direct ties to death squads.''
   ``U.S. aid to the Cristiani government also continues in the
face of stepped-up violence against the civilian population and any
political opposition,'' the statement said.
   The United States during the past decade provided the Salvadoran
government with economic and military assistance of more than $3
billion. The aid began shortly after Marxist-led guerrillas began
their war to topple the government in 1979.
   The group also said it sought the support of the Bush
administration for negotiations between the guerrillas, known as
the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, and the Cristiani
government to end the war. Some 70,000 people, many of them
civilians, have been killed in the fighting.
</TEXT>
