<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Poll-Method     10-30 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poll-Method,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll on Hostages Based on Phone Interviews</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poll Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews Sept. 14-24 with 1,071 adults in the
continental United States. Phone numbers were selected randomly and
interviews were conducted with the adult who had the most recent
birthday, a random phenomenon.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning that 19 of
20 times its findings should be within 3 points of the result if
every adult American were asked the same questions. The error
margin is larger for subgroups.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions in this
poll; because of rounding, sums may not total 100:
   1. Do you think of Iran as an enemy of the United States, or as
unfriendly but not an enemy, or as something else? Enemy: 47.
Unfriendly: 37. Other: 8. Don't know or no answer: 9.
   2. Do you think Iran supports terrorism around the world, or
not? Yes: 79. No: 9. DK-NA: 12.
   3. Do you think Iran has control over the people who are holding
American hostages in Lebanon, or not? Yes: 72. No: 15. DK-NA: 13.
   4. Should the United States offer to resume normal relations
with Iran if Iran gets the American hostages in Lebanon freed? Yes:
61. No: 29. DK-NA: 10.
   5. The United States has frozen $2 billion in Iranian assets in
U.S. banks. Should the United States release this money to Iran if
Iran gets the American hostages in Lebanon freed? Yes: 50. No: 37.
DK-NA: 13.
   6a. Some people say the United States should negotiate with the
people who are holding American hostages in Lebanon in order to win
their freedom. Others say negotiating would encourage more
hostage-taking. Do you think the United States should negotiate
with the people who are holding American hostages in Lebanon, or
not? Yes: 47. No: 45. DK-NA: 8.
   b. (If no) How about if negotiations were held through a third
party, such as the Red Cross _ would you support or oppose that?
Support: 55. Oppose: 37. DK-NA: 8.
   7. Do you think the United States should pay money to the
hostage-takers to free the American hostages in Lebanon? Yes: 10.
No: 85. DK-NA: 5.
   8a. Would you support or oppose the use of U.S. military force
in Lebanon in an effort to free the American hostages in Lebanon?
Support: 62. Oppose: 28. DK-NA: 9.
   b. (If support) If the hostages might be killed in such an
action _ would you still support it, or not? Yes: 70. No: 24.
DK-NA: 6.
   9. Do you think the United States government has done enough to
try to free the U.S. hostages in Lebanon, or not? Yes: 25. No: 54.
DK-NA: 21.
   10. Do you think the U.S. hostages in Lebanon eventually will be
released, or not? Yes: 42. No: 37. DK-NA: 21.
</TEXT>
