<FIRST>u a PM-BridgeCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0484 10-30 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Collapse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0484,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness: People `Were Just Running in the Air'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE county wants to rebuild bridge;
picks up 9th graf pvs: `If we ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES JEFFERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEBER SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local official said today he is
considering rebuilding a bridge that collapsed, plunging five
people to their deaths, even though he has not obtained a
professional opinion about the tragedy's cause.
   The dead were among more than 30 people who witnesses said were
rocking the bridge back and forth just before it collapsed,
spilling the group into the Little Red River. Officials have
speculated that the swinging motion put tension on the cables
supporting the 77-year-old wood-decked structure and contributed to
the collapse.
   People ``were just running in the air,'' said Jennifer Johnson,
who was driving to her nearby home when she saw the accident.
   Of the 18 people injured, seven remained hospitalized today,
with conditions ranging from satisfactory to serious, authorities
said.
   The dead, who had gathered in a nearby town for a church
meeting, included three children.
   County officials as yet have not had an expert test the debris
to determine what happened.
   County Judge Harvey Adcock said today that he would seek a
historic preservation grant or some other funds to aid in
rebuilding the bridge, which has been on the National Register of
Historic Places since 1986. In Arkansas, the county judge has no
judicial power, but is chief administrator of county government.
   ``Everybody feels a great sense of loss now that it's gone,''
Adcock said.
   He said a state police investigator had looked at the site with
county officers, but Adcock didn't know whether the officer was an
engineer. The judge said he ``had the name and address of a private
engineer that will probably look at it.''
   A state Highway and Transportation Department engineer and an
engineer from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers said their agencies
had no plans to get involved in the investigation, unless they were
asked.
   ``No one has contacted us. It's out of our jurisdiction,'' said
David Lambert, heavy bridge and maintenance engineer for the
highway department. ``I guess that's up to the Cleburne County
authorites on how they want to handle it. If we had a request to
look at it, it would be considered.''
   There were no signs at either end of the bridge setting capacity
limits or warning visitors against swinging the bridge, which was a
popular pastime among young people. Officials did not believe any
warnings were needed, Adcock said.
   ``If we would have had any inkling that it wasn't safe, we would
have had it shut down,'' Adcock said.
   Those on the bridge were attending an annual meeting of the Full
Holiness church movement at nearby Prim.
   Ms. Johnson said she saw the upstream side buckle. ``It just
turned upside down and fell into the river,'' she said.
   ``One girl said it felt like a dream until she hit the water,''
said Cindy Watkins, who had traveled from Oklahoma with her sister,
Vicki, for the church outing. ``Everybody was up there laughing and
then all of a sudden it screeches and pops. It was real scary.''
   Another member of the church group, Daniel Rafferty of Seymour,
Mo., said he saw the bridge being rocked as he arrived.
   ``We thought it was kind of fun and it scared some people,''
Rafferty said.
   It ``just happened so quickly that no one had a chance to cry
for help,'' he said. ``They didn't know what happened. It was pure
terror. Arms were flailing. People were panicking. Everyone was
trying to save themselves.''
   As crews worked with cranes and bulldozers to remove the debris,
residents brought flowers to lay at the foot of the bridge to
remember the victims.
   Among the dead was Gayla Carlton, the 34-year-old daughter of
the host pastor, the Rev. Vernon Carlton of Prim.
   Her uncle, Tony Carlton, had two teen-age daughters on the
bridge. Both survived.
   ``At bedtime last night I told my daughters, `Let's thank the
Lord that y'all made it one more time.' We knelt at the bedside and
prayed,'' Carlton said. ``I have feelings for the others. There's
no way I can explain it.''
   The others killed were Jason Williams, 16, of Muldrow, Okla.;
Dana Waltman, 11, of Vancleave, Miss.; David Shane Warren, 13, of
Mayfield, Ky.; and Catrina Cotrell, in her early 20s, of Stratford,
Okla.
</TEXT>
