<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     10-30 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Countdown Test Successful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A launch team and five astronauts
successfully concluded a practice countdown Monday for a November
launch of the space shuttle Discovery, which will carry a secret
military payload.
   The exercise, which began Sunday, covered the final 24 hours of
an actual count and provided training for both ground controllers
and the astronauts, who were in the shuttle cockpit for the final
two hours.
   NASA spokesman George Diller said the exercise went well.
   In honor of Halloween, the astronauts wore costume hats and
carried artificial jack-o'-lanterns as they arrived at the launch
pad in their bulky orange pressure suits. Some pad workers wore
masks for the occasion.
   Discovery is scheduled to be launched Nov. 20 on the fifth of 32
shuttle flights assigned entirely to the Defense Department.
   For security reasons, officials will not disclose the nature of
the cargo or what experiments the space crew plans. Earlier
military missions have deployed reconnaissance and
intelligence-gathering satellites.
   Discovery's crew members are Air Force Col. Frederick C.
Gregory, the first black astronaut named to command a space shuttle
mission; Air Force Col. John Blaha, the pilot; and three mission
specialists, Navy Capt. Manley L. Carter Jr.; F. Story Musgrave;
and Kathryn C. Thornton. Blaha replaced Navy Rear Adm. S. David
Griggs, who was killed June 17 in the crash of a private plane he
was piloting.
</TEXT>
