<FIRST>r w PM-CapitolFlagBurning 1stLd-Writethru a0569 10-30 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capitol Flag Burning, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0569,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four People Burn American Flats at Capitol</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs last graf pvs with 3 new grafs to give police identifications,
charges.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four people shouting ``burn, baby, burn,''
torched three American flags on the central steps of the U.S.
Capitol today in a bid to test the new federal law protecting the
national symbol from desecration.
   All four demonstrators were arrested by Capitol police.
   ``We defy your law,'' said Nancy Kent, a spokeswoman for the
flag burners, reading from a prepared statement.``We challenge you.
Arrest us. Test your statute. Take it back to the Supreme Court and
try once again to claim it is all consistent with your
constitutional standards of free speech.''
   The law, which President Bush allowed to take force without his
signature, went into effect at midnight on Friday.
   The flag-burning demonstration had been scheduled for noon on
the marble plaza of the Supreme Court. Organizers announced it had
been moved and led photographers and television cameras to the
Capitol steps.
   One demonstrator produced a flag and ripped it.
   Two policemen tore the pieces of the flag from his hands.
   Behind them another man produced a flag and set it afire.
   Two other flags also were set ablaze as the four demonstrators
chanted, ``Burn, baby, burn.''
   ``Another shouted: ``Stop the fascist flag law. Oppose it.''
   Policemen first attempted to extinguish the flames by stamping
on the flags, them aimed fire extinguishers at the burning
remnants, dousing them in a chemical stream and shrouding the scene
in white smoke.
   Police spokesman Dan Nichols said the four were identified as
Shawn Eichner, 24, of New York City; Gregory Johnson, 33, of
Richmond, Ind.; David Blalock, 39, of Johnstown, Pa., and Scott
Tyler, 24, of Chicago.
   The four were charged with violating the Flag Protection Act of
1989, demonstrating without a permit and diorderly conduct, Nichols
said.
   Violation of the flag statute provides a maximum penalty of one
year in jail and a $1,000 fine. The other two charges are
misdemeanors and carry respective maximum penalties of $300 and 90
days in jail and $250 and 90 days in jail.
</TEXT>
