<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HalloweenTips     10-30 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Halloween Tips,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Safety Council Offers Halloween Safety Tips</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tampered Treats, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Safety Council has issued the
following guidelines for parents and children at Halloween:
   _ Children's costumes should be large enough so that warm
clothing can be worn underneath, yet short enough so that a child
won't trip. Avoid shoes that make walking difficult.
   _ For visibility, use light colors in costumes and attach
reflective tape to them. Have children use reflective treat bags.
   _ Attach a small child's name, address and phone number inside
his sleeve in case he gets lost. But don't openly display the
personal information on the child's costume.
   _ Masks can obscure a child's vision. Use non-toxic makeup
instead.
   _ Be sure children travel only in familiar neighborhoods and
that they don't enter strangers' homes. They should follow a
designated travel route with a definite return time and not
trick-or-treat past dark. Give them coins to call home if any
problems arise.
   _ Remind children not to eat any treat before it's been
inspected by a parent.
   _ Teach children pedestrian safety.
   _ Motorists should slow down in residential areas and watch for
children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
