<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-AbortionVeto     10-30 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Abortion Veto,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Again Defends Bush Veto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House on Monday defended anew
President Bush's abortion-related veto of the District of
Columbia's appropriations bill, which critics say has tied up funds
to battle drugs in the nation's capital.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush would
sign the funding measure ``in a nanosecond'' if Congress would
strip language liberalizing funding for abortions in the district.
   Bush on Friday vetoed the district budget bill, including the
annual $435 million federal contribution to the city's $3.4 billion
budget.
   The bill would provide the city with an extra $32 million to
hire more police, build prison space, launch a drug treatment
initiative for pregnant women and other anti-drug activities.
   The 1989 murder rate in the city reached 369 over the weekend,
tying the 1988 record. Authorities say many of the slayings are
drug related.
   The measure would also lift a year-old restriction that bars the
district from spending locally raised tax dollars to provide
unrestricted abortions for poor women.
   Bush said Saturday in San Jose, Costa Rica, that abortion-rights
supporters were playing ``political games'' with the bill, and he
vowed to stand like ``a brick wall'' against efforts to lift
restrictions on abortion funding.
   ``The fact is the president vetoed it because of his beliefs on
abortion. That's the way it stands,'' Fitzwater said. ``All they've
got to do is strip that out, change the language back to the way it
was and we'll sign that bill in a nanosecond.''
   Fitzwater rejected the argument that the district should be free
to do as it pleases with its own tax dollars. Under the law
governing home rule for the district, Congress must approve the
entire D.C. budget, not just the federal contribution.
   ``It's all out of the federal money. It's federally
appropriated. Everybody tries to use that argument it's local
money. It's not,'' Fitzwater said.
   The National Abortion Rights Action League says 30 states and
the district pay for abortions through Medicaid only to save the
mother's life; eight states pay for abortions in cases of rape or
incest or certain other circumstances; and 12 states pay for
abortions deemed ``medically necessary.''
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, the former two-time Democratic
presidential contender who has moved to the district from Chicago,
said Sunday that the veto demonstrates ``the colonial status of the
District of Columbia,'' and accused Bush of ``tyranny.''
</TEXT>
