<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Beech-Nut     10-30 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Beech-Nut,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Executive Loses Appeal of Apple Juice Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Beech-Nut executive fighting his
conviction for selling adulterated apple juice lost a Supreme Court
appeal today.
   The court, without comment, left intact John F. Lavery's
sentence of a year and a day in prison and a $100,000 fine.
   Lavery, former vice president in charge of operations for
Beech-Nut, was convicted last year in New York City of conspiracy
and mail fraud for selling as pure apple juice what essentially was
corn syrup.
   Government prosecutors said Lavery first was warned by a
Beech-Nut research director in 1977 that juice from its supplier,
Universal Juice Co., was adulterated. The prosecutors said many
similar warnings followed.
   Lavery did not fire Universal Juice Co. as supplier until 1982,
after a detective from the Processed Apple Institute told him
Beech-Nut was going to be hit with a lawsuit, the prosecutors said.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last March rejected
Lavery's arguments that he improperly was convicted of conspiracy
and fraud.
   But the appeals court said, ``The evidence was ample to permit
the jury to infer that Lavery conspired with the suppliers to
perpetrate a fraud on the public through the distribution of the
adulterated juice.''
   Beech-Nut President Niels L. Hoyvald also was convicted. He
received the same sentence as Lavery but was not involved in the
appeal acted on today.
   Beech-Nut was fined $2 million after pleading guilty to selling
adulterated and misbranded apple juice.
   The case is Lavery vs. U.S., 89-216.
</TEXT>
