<FIRST>r i AM-Sharansky     10-30 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sharansky,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Human Rights Activist Considers Visiting Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights activist Natan Sharansky, who
spent nine years in Soviet prisons, is considering visiting Moscow,
a spokeswoman said Monday.
   Sharansky was considering the offer from the Jewish
Confederation of the Soviet Union, a newly formed umbrella group
for Soviet Jewish organizations, to visit Moscow in December, said
the spokeswoman, who insisted on anonymity.
   She was speaking from the Jerusalem-based Soviet Jewry Zionist
Forum headed by Sharansky.
   Sharansky told the Maariv newspaper that he was interested in
visiting Moscow to encourage Jewish emigration to Israel, but was
concerned that publicity from his trip might benefit President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``I have no special nostalgia for the Soviet Union,'' Sharansky
said. ``My consideration to return and visit there will be if such
a visit would help our struggle to encourage the Jewish awakening.''
   ``I know that Gorbachev can benefit from a visit like that and I
have to consider who would gain more, Soviet Jews or Gorbachev,''
he said.
   In the early 1970s, Sharansky was a member of the Helsinki
Committee, a human rights watchdog group headed by Nobel Prize
laureate Andrei Sakharov.
   Sharansky made contacts with foreign journalists in Moscow and
gained prominence as a spokesman for organization. He also
championed the Soviet Jewry emigration movement.
   He was denied an exit visa to join his wife, who left for Israel
a day after their wedding in 1974. In March 1977, he was arrested
and in 1978 convicted of espionage and sentenced to 13 years in
prison.
   He spent nine years in Soviet prisons and labor camps, becoming
a symbol of the Soviet Jewry's plight thanks to the efforts of his
wife, Avital, who tirelessly campaigned on his behalf in the West.
   Sharansky was freed on Feb. 11, 1986, when he came West on
Berlin's Glienicke Bridge. Included in the swap were Wolf Georg
Frohn of East Germany, Jaroslave Jaworski of Czechoslovakia and
Dietrich Nistroy of West Germany, who were released by the East,
and Jerzy Kaczmarek of Poland, Yevgeni Semliakov of Soviet Union,
Detlef Scharfenorth of East Germany and Karl F. Koecher of
Czechoslovakia and his wife, Hana, who were released by the West.
   At first, Sharansky kept a low profile in Israel. But he emerged
last year to found the Soviet Jewry Zionist Forum, a lobby group
seeking to improve conditions for immigrants from the Soviet Union.
   He also heads the Council of New Immigrants' Organizations,
which represents 18 groups uniting immigrants from 40 countries.
   Sharansky told Maariv he believed the Soviets would issue him a
visa.
   ``The Russians are making efforts to cut themselves off from the
past. Yuri Orlov, also an activist of the Helsinki Committee ...
has recently visited the Soviet Union despite once being convicted
as an enemy of the state, and faced no problems,'' Sharansky said.
``This is not what may prevent my visit.''
</TEXT>
