<HEAD>US Deplores Czech Crackdown on Dissidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department criticized on Monday the
crackdown by Czech authorities on protesters who staged a
pro-democracy demonstration over the weekend.
   Police arrested about 350 demonstrators, who participated in a
march commemorating the 71st anniversary of the founding of the
first independent Czech republic.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the United
States deplores the actions of the Czech government, which
``seriously call into question its stated interest in improving
U.S.-Czechoslovakian relations.''
   She said that ``the people of Czechoslovakia know what democracy
is and they want it now.''
   ``The U.S. calls on the government of Czechoslovakia to respect
the rights of its citizens and to institute the basic freedoms
desired by the Czechoslovakian people,'' she said.
   Asked about indications of reform in Bulgaria, Ms. Tutwiler said
the administration welcomes them but added that Bulgaria still lags
behind the leaders of reform in Eastern Europe.
   Among other measures, Bulgaria has indicated it will lift some
restrictions on the activities of independent environmental
activists and is liberalizing passport laws.
   Ms. Tutwiler, asked about signs of increased public debate on
government policy in East Germany, expressed hope that this is
another indication that the government is sincere about taking
steps to meet the wishes of the people for reform.
   ``We will continue to watch developments in East Germany very
closely, particularly overtures made by the regime to the
opposition,'' she said.
