<FIRST>r w AM-US-WestGermany     10-30 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-West Germany,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>United States, West Germany Reach Military Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and West Germany have
reached an agreement that commits the German civil sector to
support the U.S. Armed Forces in the event of war or other crisis,
the Pentagon announced on Monday.
   The West German support covers such things as the transport of
personnel and supplies, telephone and teletype equipment,
construction equipment, maintenance and repair services, and
civilian labor, among other things, a Pentagon statement said.
   The latest agreement, reached in Bonn, West Germany, on Oct. 24,
is the culmination of a series of so-called ``host nation'' support
arrangments to improve the defense capabilities of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Under the agreements that date back to 1982, the United States
promised to reinforce the military units stationed in West Germany
with combat divisions and air squadrons, while the West German
government agreed to create military units to support U.S. forces
and to provide the additional support from the German civilian
sector, the statement said.
   The statement called the U.S.-West German series of agreements
the most extensive such commitment within the NATO alliance.
</TEXT>
