<FIRST>r w AM-Military-Society     10-30 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military-Society,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Percentage of Blacks in Military High, But Declining</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The percentage of blacks among the nation's
military recruits has dropped since 1980 but minorities continue to
be overrepresented in America's armed forces, said a congressional
report released Monday.
   Other changes found by the Congressional Budget Office, which
conducted the study of the nation's all-volunteer armed services,
included an improvement in standard military test scores and
educational background of the current recruits.
   ``These results, like those for race, represent a considerable
change from the beginning of the decade, when testing problems and
recruiting difficulties resulted in large numbers of low scorers
and non-graduates being accepted for military service,'' said the
study.
   ``The Army achieved particularly impressive gains,'' said the
report, ``Social Representation in the U.S. Military.''
   In 1980, less than 70 percent of active-duty recruits for the
four services _ Air Force, Army, Navy and Marine Corps _ had high
school diplomas. Only 55 percent of Army recruits could lay claim
to a secondary school degree.
   But seven years later, 94 percent of active-duty recruits for
the four services had high school diplomas, as did about 91 percent
of Army recruits.
   About two-thirds of the recruits scored above average in
comparison to the general youth population on the standard military
entrance exams, the study said.
   On the issue of minorities among the recruits, the study found
that between 1980 and 1987, the percentage of blacks among recruits
with no prior military service fell by nearly 3 points _ 22.3
percent to 19.7 percent. In comparison, there was an increase of
almost 1 percentage point in enlistment-age youths who are black.
   Contributing to the decline was the Army, where the share of
black recruits fell by more than 6 percentage points.
   The study also found that black recruits come disproportionately
from sections of the country with above-average black incomes and
better-educated black adults. In 1987, only 44 percent of the black
male active-duty recruits came from areas in the bottom half of the
income distribution for black families.
   Women accounted for less than 13 percent of active-duty recruits
in 1987, a slight drop from the 14.2 percent in 1980. The CBO
attributed the somewhat steady total to the limited number of
military jobs for women.
   The CBO said the purpose of the study was to provide an
objective analysis and not reach any conclusions about current
patterns of representation and ways to change them.
   However, the study did say that instituting a draft would not
change the social composition of the military unless enlisted
strengths were significantly increased.
   ``The all-volunteer force is doing a good job of attracting a
broad cross-section of American youth,'' said Sen. John Glenn,
D-Ohio, the chairman of the Senate Armed Services subcommittee on
manpower and personnel and the lawmaker who requested the study.
   The study, Glenn said, ``fills a major gap in our knowledge
about who is attracted to the volunteer military.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     10-30 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Passes Laws on Amnesty, Creates State Auditor's Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Monday approved
legislation granting amnesty to many people convicted of crimes
punishable by less than three years in prison, and it created an
office to control government and party finances.
   The laws, to take effect in November, were among several items
on the agenda on the opening day of the legislature's first session
since it rewrote the communist constitution to reflect democratic
ideals.
   Hungary's rapidly evolving reform course has put it in the
vanguard of democratic change within the Soviet bloc, along with
Poland, the first Warsaw Pact nation with a government not
dominated by the communists.
   At its last sitting, which ended Oct. 20, Hungary's Parliament
adopted a series of laws and constitutional amendements
establishing the legal framework for the first multiparty elections
since the now defunct Communist party consolidated power in 1948.
   The Communist Party _ formally known as the Hungarian Socialist
Workers' Party _ dissolved itself Oct. 7 at a historic congress
that gave birth to its successor, the Socialist Party. The new
party, which professes democratic ideals, retains political
control, but its leaders have promised to hand over power if
defeated at the polls next year.
   In another major move to break with the Communist past, acting
President Matyas Szueroes proclaimed the existence of the Republic
of Hungary Oct. 23, the 33rd anniversary of the 1956 anti-Stalinist
revolt.
   The proclamation, which formally terminated the
Communist-created People's Republic of Hungary, was cheered by more
than 100,000 Hungarians.
   The amnesty law applies to those serving terms of three years or
less who are in the following categories: pregnant women, women
with children under 14 living with them, women over 55 and men over
60, and those suffering from terminal illness. The terms are halved
for those in these categories serving sentences exceding three
years.
   The amnesty does not apply to those facing or serving sentences
for violent or sexual crimes.
   Creation of an auditor's office was meant to re-establish
impartial control over government and party spending which was
effectively abolished after the communists took over. The office,
which also has jurisdiction over the finances of state enterprises,
is responsible to Parliament.
   The number of legislators present to vote on the two bills
differed, accounting for the different totals.
   Tuesday's agenda included a decision on when and how to chose a
president, whose responsibilities include command of the armed
forces and other major tasks.
   The newly created post was originally to be filled Nov. 26 by
popular vote, but two opposition groups have collected more than
100,000 opposing signatures, enough to force a plebiscite on the
issue.
   The groups _ the League of Free Democrats and the League of
Young Democrats _ say the early date favors Socialist Party
candidate Imre Pozsgay because it doesn't give the opposition
enough time to organize and make their candidates well known.
   In addition, legislators planned Tuesday to discuss and vote on
government proposals on a suspended Danube River hydroelectric
project with Czechoslovakia, a Warsaw Pact ally increasingly at
odds with Hungary over its reforms.
   In declaring a moratorium in May on the Gabcikovo-Nagymaros dam
project, Hungary expressed concern about potential enviromental
damage. Czechoslovakia has said it will continue construction and
will demand compensation if work is permanently suspended by the
Hungarians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
