<FIRST>r a AM-People Sub a0621 10-30 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People, Sub, a0621,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs Denver-dated third item to CORRECT to Vasiliev sted Valiliev
in 6th graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Bolshoi Ballet stars who had a hankering for a
handgun got a Navajo peace pipe instead, according to a gun shop
owner who said he opened his store after-hours to accommodate the
Soviet sharpshooters.
   Dancer Vladimir Vasiliev beamed and thanked shop owner Scottie
Jewell after he presented him with the pipe during an hour-long
shopping trip.
   ``Beautiful,'' Vasiliev said.
   Vasiliev headlines a touring company of the Bolshoi Ballet that
performed in Denver over the weekend. The troupe's Denver
appearance was sponsored by the Colorado Ballet, and the Soviets
practiced last week at the local company's rehearsal hall near
Jewell's store.
   Several of the dancers are avid hunters and Jewell and his
13-year-old daughter, Alexandra, are big ballet fans. Alexandra
also dances with the Colorado Ballet.
   One of the dancers wandered into the gun store last week, then
met Jewell again after Saturday night's Bolshoi performance and
asked if he could bring friends to the store. Jewell agreed to open
the shop on his day off for Vasiliev and dancer Alexandr Bogatyriev.
   The Soviets were unable to by a gun because Jewell can only sell
rifles and guns to U.S. citizens who are Colorado residents.
   Jewell said an Indian artist from Farmington, N.M., made the
peace pipe and had given it to him to sell. When the Soviets came,
however, ``I thought it would be even better to give it away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
