<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Poland     10-30 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Poland,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Sending Three Cabinet Members to Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Monday he will send three
Cabinet members and his chief economic adviser to Poland to help
its non-communist government develop a strategy for overhauling the
country's battered economy.
   ``Poland's struggle has always been America's struggle,'' Bush
said. ``Maybe that's why it seems that Polish hearts and American
hearts beat as one.''
   The delegation named by Bush will include government, business,
labor and academic officials. It will be led by Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter, Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher,
Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole and Michael Boskin, chairman of the
Council of Economic Advisers.
   They will depart Washington on Nov. 29 and return on Dec. 2.
   Bush announced their selection in a Rose Garden ceremony marking
the end of October as Polish American heritage month.
   Saluting Poland for forming a non-communist government, the
first in Eastern Europe in more than 40 years, Bush said, ``Poland
herself has moved toward a new beginning.''
   Bush said that in Poland and elsewhere, ``the tide toward
oppression is running out. The tide toward liberty is running in.
   ``The voice of freedom is the voice of Poland, and the voice of
Poland is the voice of tomorrow.''
   Bush has proposed a $400 million, multiyear aid program for
Poland, but congressional Democrats are pushing for a package of
more than $1 billion.
   Discussing the mission with reporters following the president's
announcement, Mosbacher said that the travel group would be working
to speed up the process of getting assistance to Poland.
   ``They obviously have some serious fiscal and financial
problems. We just want to get as much in place as quickly as
possible,'' Mosbacher said, noting that winter is approaching.
   Among those accompanying the Cabinet officials will be AFL-CIO
President Lane Kirkland and various chief operating officers from
American companies, Mosbacher said. The business executives would
be exploring the possibility of starting joint ventures in Poland,
he said.
   ``We need a combination of people who have the expertise, people
who have the equipment, people who have the money and the
know-how,'' said Mosbacher.
</TEXT>
