<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Moslem     10-30 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Moslem,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Says Boycott of Moslem Autonomy Referendum a Mistake</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAMBOANGA CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino on
Monday urged people to vote in next month's plebiscite for
self-rule in the southern Philippines, saying a boycott would be a
mistake.
   It was the second time in three days that Mrs. Aquino has gone
to Mindanao, the second largest Philippine island, to campaign for
the ratification of a plan to grant limited self-rule in 13
southern provinces.
   On Saturday, Mrs. Aquino visited Cotabato to start the campaign,
but made no categorical appeal for voters to ratify the autonomy
act, which was passed by Congress.
   Voters in Mindanao and other southern islands go to the polls
Nov. 19 to decide whether their provinces will join an autonomous
regional government.
   The move is aimed at satisfying demands for self-rule for the 4
million-member Moslem minority. Christians form the majority in the
provinces of Mindanao and other southern islands.
   The bill, which Mrs. Aquino signed in August, has been facing
public opposition even from Moslem secessionist groups.
   ``I understand that some groups are organizing a boycott of the
plebiscite, Mrs. Aquino told hundreds of people at a rally. ``I
think this would be a serious mistake. A boycott position is
meaningless.''
   She refused to say whether she was for ratification or rejection
of the bill, adding that she was adopting a position of ``active
neutrality.''
   ``I have refused to dictate how people should vote for the
plebiscite,'' she said.
   She said she had been accused by her foes as being indecisive,
but she defended her stand, saying she upheld the principle of
``popular consultation.''
</TEXT>
