<FIRST>r a AM-OptometristHearing     10-30 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Optometrist Hearing,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Panel Under the Gun Over Topless Eye Exams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state board is caught in a political
ruckus over its decision to clear an optometrist who had some women
patients strip to the waist during eye exams.
   The Iowa Board of Optometry Examiners once voted to exonerate
optometrist Gary Fisher of Monticello but is reconsidering that
decision in the face of intense public pressure.
   The case has angered some women, pitted health professionals
against each other and raised questions about closed meetings of
medical regulators.
   The seven-member board scheduled a telephone conference call
Tuesday morning to decide if it wants to review Fisher's case. The
board met privately for more than five hours Saturday.
   Fisher was hauled before the state licensing board on ethics
charges after some women patients complained that he had them
partially disrobe.
   Fisher argued he did so for legitimate reasons, to check for
curvature of the spine associated with some eye disorders. Because
much of the professional discipline review is private, the issue
first came to light last month when the board cleared him.
   In its ruling, the panel said Fisher was ``honestly attempting
to provide the best care.''
   That decision prompted an uproar from lawmakers and others.
   ``It was kind of like a foot doctor looking at the brain,'' said
state Sen. Jack Nystrom, ranking member of the State Government
Committee.
   The issue heated up when the attorney general's office joined
with the board that regulates physicians in urging a new hearing.
The medical board threatened a lawsuit, saying Fisher strayed into
the practice of medicine, for which he isn't licensed.
   Fisher complained about being hounded by reporters; then he and
everyone else involved in the matter stopped commenting on the
advice of lawyers, who expect the issue eventually will land in
court.
   Fisher did say he no longer performs topless eye exams.
</TEXT>
