<FIRST>r i AM-UNESCO     10-30 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UNESCO,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Urges U.S., Britain, Singapore to Rejoin UNESCO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar on Monday urged the United States, Britain and Singapore to
rejoin the U.N. Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
   The United States left UNESCO in 1984, followed by Britain and
Singapore, on the grounds that the Paris-based U.N. agency was
politicized, anti-Western, mismanaged and too expensive.
   ``Science, education, culture, and communications are not
confined by national boundaries,'' the U.N. chief said.
``International organizations which deal with questions of global
concern such as these should be truly universal.''
   UNESCO is holding its General Conference meeting in Paris,
considering a reform program by its director-general, Federico
Mayor Zaragoza, and a more Third-World oriented agenda proposed by
the agency's Executive Board.
   One of the key factors that drove the United States out of
UNESCO was its consideration of a ``New World Information Order.''
   Third World nations saw the adoption of the policy as a way of
reducing the dominance of news agencies from the developed world in
international communications.
   The United States and Britain, however, feared Third World
nations would use the mandate to license journalists, enforce an
ethics code among them, and urge reporters to adopt ideological
goals, such as opposing racism and war.
   U.S. and British publishers and communications companies were
outraged at the suggestions, and supported President Ronald
Reagan's and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's decision to quit
the agency.
   Mayor has criticized plans for censorship or government control
of journalism and says the free flow of information should not
restricted.
</TEXT>
