<FIRST>r a AM-ShipAground     10-30 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Aground,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ship Hauling Phosphates Runs Aground off Key West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 475-foot ship hauling fertilizer phosphate ran
aground Monday in the westernmost Florida Keys, but the Coast Guard
said it appeared no cargo or fuel had spilled.
   The grounding was the second in five days by a ship sailing
along the 200-mile chain of islands at the southernmost tip of
Florida.
   Gov. Bob Martinez, who flew over to inspect the
Yugoslavian-registered Mavro Vetranic, said the ship apparently
``was well embedded on a coral reef.''
   ``It appears it has hit a crown jewel,'' he said. ``The reefs of
Florida are crown jewels in the underwater environment.''
   The ship was carrying 14,300 tons of phosphate for use in
fertilizer, 120,000 gallons of heavy fuel oil and 23,000 gallons of
diesel fuel, the Coast Guard said.
   ``There is no visible pollution, there's no injuries at the
moment, and the ship is hard aground,'' Petty Officer Alastair
Worden said after a Coast Guard helicopter flew over the
16-year-old ship.
   An owner's representative was arranging for tugs, barges to
lighten the ship's load and a salvage surveyor to determine what
can be done to move the ship, stranded about 7{ miles northeast of
Garden Key in the Dry Tortugas.
   The island cluster 70 miles west of Key West is the site of Fort
Jefferson National Monument and is marked by a tall lighthouse as
well as the massive fort.
   The governor earlier proposed a 10-mile buffer zone for shipping
off Florida to reduce the danger of groundings and spills, but
international agreement would be required for any such change. No
formal shipping lanes exist off the Florida Keys.
   ``We've had two of these (groundings) in less than a week,''
Martinez said. ``This will clearly show that we were not crying
wolf when we first brought this up.''
   The cargo ship ran aground at 1:45 a.m., but the Coast Guard
wasn't informed until it received a message from another vessel at
7:50 a.m., said Petty Officer James Wentworth.
   A Coast Guard marine inspector, a representative of Lloyd's of
London, the ship's insurer, and federal and state divers were among
those sent to inspect the grounded ship.
   The ship, built in 1973, is owned by Atlanska Plovidba of
Dubrovnik, Yugoslavia, a port on the Adriatic Sea.
   The grounding came five days after a much smaller cargo ship,
the 155-foot Alec Owen Maitland, tore a 200-yard swath through
coral in Key Largo National Marine Sanctuary, about 50 miles
southeast of Miami.
   A Coast Guard inquiry into that grounding resumed Monday in
Miami with one crew member saying the ship's owner had a
non-alcoholic policy but beer was in the ship's refrigerator.
   The first mate, who was at the helm, failed two breath tests
after the grounding, but both he and the captain said he didn't
start drinking until after the accident.
   The unlicensed first mate, Michael Anthony Bishop, 43, has been
charged with negligence, and the ship's captain Duane Godwin, 37,
with allowing an improperly licensed sailor to operate the ship.
   Ship repairs should be completed by Wednesday, said Coast Guard
Petty Officer Luis Diaz.
</TEXT>
