<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-DetroitJOA     10-30 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Detroit JOA,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Hears Arguments on Detroit Papers' Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A critic of the proposed partial merger of
Detroit's two daily newspapers told the Supreme Court Monday that
permitting the move would be ``a terrific incentive for monopoly''
conduct.
   But a lawyer for the Bush administration, defending former
Attorney General Edwin Meese's approval of the joint operating
agreement, said such mergers are needed to protect the dwindling
number of two-newspaper cities in America.
   Elsewhere, an investor group offered to buy the Detroit Free
Press for $68 million from Knight-Ridder Inc., which has said it
will sell or shut down the paper if the joint operating agreement
with the Gannett-owned Detroit News is overturned.
   The high court heard 60 minutes of arguments over the partial
merger and is expected to announce a decision by July. Justice
Byron R. White has removed himself from consideration of the case,
creating the possibility of a 4-4 tie that would uphold the joint
operating agreement.
   William B. Schultz, representing a group of Michigan readers and
advertisers who oppose the joint agreement, said both newspapers
are ``competitive equals'' and could survive if they raised
newstand prices and advertising rates.
   But, he said, the papers have been engaged in a price-cutting
war for years designed to drive each other out of business or force
a partial merger highly profitable to both.
   ``Their prices are too low and their advertisement rates are the
lowest in the country,'' he said.
   If the Supreme Court permits the Detroit papers to operate
jointly, ``It will result in artificial generation'' of other such
arrangements, Schultz said. ``The profit possibilities are
enormous.''
   But Thomas W. Merrill of the Justice Department said the partial
mergers are aimed at ``preserving two or more editorial voices'' in
cities that otherwise might become one-newspaper towns. There are
competing newspapers now in only 25 cities.
   Merrill said there are enough potential readers in Detroit to
support two newspapers if there were ``a pricing czar'' to prevent
price-cutting. ``Unfortunately there is no czar,'' he said.
   The federal Newspaper Preservation Act of 1970 authorizes the
attorney general to give financially failing newspapers an
exemption from federal antitrust laws.
   The Free Press and News have agreed to combine their business,
advertising and production departments but maintain separate news
and editorial staffs.
   They put off the partial merger pending the high court's ruling
on whether Meese improperly approved the deal in August 1988.
   The Free Press lost $10 million a year between 1981 and 1986.
The News lost $50 million in the same period.
   Gannett Co. is the nation's largest newspaper publishing group
and Knight-Ridder is second.
   Schultz stressed that the two companies essentially have agreed
to split profits down the middle if the joint agreement takes
effect. That suggests they regard the newspapers as competitive
equals and casts doubt on claims the Free Press is failing, he said.
   Justice John Paul Stevens aggressively questioned Merrill's
arguments that approving the joint operating agreement will not
sanction predatory pricing forbidden by antitrust law.
   Is this ``lawful or unlawful pricing?'' Stevens asked Merrill.
``I'd like an answer.''
   Merrill said, ``The record in this case does not suggest
predatory pricing.'' He said it would be unfair to overturn the
agreement and order further examination of that issue.
   The investor group that wants to buy the Free Press for $68
million is headed by William D. McMaster. He said he wanted to
convert the newspaper's format to a ``statewide community
newspaper''
   The case is Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press vs.
Thornburgh, 88-1640.
</TEXT>
