<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1911EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Asteroids     10-30 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asteroids,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amateur Astronomer Discovers Asteroids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JESSICA BALDWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An amateur astronomer using a homemade telescope
said Monday he has discovered three new asteroids, and the editor
of Astronomer magazine said he's the first Briton to make such a
find in 80 years.
   Brian Manning said he spotted the asteroids between the orbits
of Jupiter and Mars using a 10-inch reflector telescope set up in
his back yard in Kidderminster, 95 miles northwest of London.
   Editor Guy Hurst, who keeps track of all European astronomical
discoveries, said Manning's sightings were run through the
International Astronomical Union computer in Cambridge, Mass., and
found to be previously unknown.
   ``To go for 80 years with no discovery, it is very important for
British astronomy,'' Hurst said. ``Manning's work, although he is
an amateur, is rated as high as professional.''
   Manning, 63, said astronomy has been his hobby since he was a
boy.
   ``I'm delighted and did not expect it really,'' he said. ``You
always hope you might find something ... but it's a surprise since
the chance of discovery is rather remote.''
   Manning's discovery was his first attempt to identify an
asteroid, and was sparked by the September issue of Astronomer,
which challenged British amateurs to find an asteroid, Hurst said.
   Manning, a retired technician from Birmingham University's
Department of Metrology, which is the science of accurate
measurements, said he made a 20-minute photographic exposure of the
sky on Oct. 4.
   He didn't discover the asteroids until Oct. 5 when he developed
the telescopic image and scanned it with a binocular microscope.
   ``My garden is not a very good spot. It's down in a hollow with
trees all around,'' he said. ``The night of the fourth was quite
good, despite the millions of street lamps everywhere, which are a
big problem to amateur astronomers.''
   Although Manning discovered the asteroids they will be named by
the International Astronomical Union. The international society
voted last year to name asteroid 3,698, discovered by another
scientist, after Manning ``for his contribution to astronomy,''
Hurst said.
   Asteroids are thought to be the remnants of planets that were
partly formed or destroyed in the early days of the solar system.
   The first asteroid, named Ceres, was discovered in 1801. At 621
miles in diameter, it is still the largest ever found.
   Manning said he believes his asteroids are about 10 miles wide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PollutionSuit     10-30 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pollution Suit,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Cited in Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit filed Monday alleges that the
Environmental Protection Agency has failed to develop national
standards for discharging toxic pollution into public waterways as
required by law.
   As a result, according to the lawsuit filed in U.S. District
Court by the Natural Resources Defense Council and Public Citizen,
millions of pounds of toxic wastes are unregulated.
   The lawsuit asks the federal courts to direct the EPA to develop
a plan for limiting a broader range of toxic pollution than is
covered by federal regulations.
   ``Over two-thirds of the industrial facilities that release
toxics into our waterways are not covered by nationwide EPA
regulations, but by a weak system of site-specific permits,'' said
Robert Adler, an attorney for the NRDC, a Washington-based
environmental organization.
   EPA spokeswoman Alicia Tenuta said the agency had no immediate
comment on the lawsuit because officials have not seen it.
   The suit, using data filed by industry to the EPA on 1987 toxic
emissions, said an estimated 70 million pounds of unregulated toxic
wastes are released annually into surface waters and sewers from a
variety of industries ranging from parmaceutical companies to
mining, iron and steel and texile operations.
   Eric Glitzenstein, an attorney for Public Citizen, said many of
those toxic releases come from companies that are in business to
treat hazardous wastes.
   ``The hazardous waste treatment industry is perhaps the most
astonishing example of an industry that escapes nationwide toxic
pollution controls,'' Giltzenstein said.
   ``Ironically, these facilities are cleaning up polluted land and
groundwater at hazardous waste sites, only to release equally
dangerous wastes into our waters.''
   The lawsuit alleges that the EPA has failed to live up to
requirements under the Clean Water Act and the Resource
Conservation and Recovery Act to establish in a timely fashion a
regulatory plan for controlling the discharge of hazardous waste
into public waterways.
</TEXT>
