<DOCNO> AP891030-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     10-30 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban Troops Reach Halfway Point in Withdrawal from Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Half of Cuba's 50,000 soldiers in Angola
have left for home, slightly ahead of a schedule set in peace
agreements signed last year by Angola, Cuba and South Africa,
officials said Monday.
   In a ceremony at the capital's airport, the last 150 of the
first 25,000 Cubans to leave the southwest African nation paraded
past Angolan, Cuban and U.N. officials to board Soviet-built
transport planes.
   According to the accords signed Dec. 22, 1988, in New York,
3,000 Cubans were to have left Angola by April 1 and 25,000 by Nov.
1. All 50,000 are to be out by July 1, 1991.
   Brazilian Gen. Pericles Ferreria Gomes said he thought the
actual number of repatriated Cubans could be even higher than
25,000 due to differences in U.N. and Cuban counting methods.
   A U.N. monitoring force will leave Luanda on Wednesday to
inspect former Cuban bases below the 13th parallel that runs along
Angola's central highlands close to the Benguela railroad, Gomes
said.
   Gomes, as leader of the force, said he would also travel south
of the parallel Friday to check the bases.
   Following the New York accords, the pullout began in January
when the first 3,000 troops left Luanda.
   U.S. officials repeatedly have reported the Cuban withdrawal
proceeding on, or slightly ahead of, schedule. They verified the
Cubans pulled back to north of the 15th parallel Aug. 1.
   Cuba and Angola agreed to the pullout in exchange for South
Africa's pledge to cease aid to the rebels of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola and allow Namibia to gain
independence.
   South African aid to UNITA, as the rebels are known, was
replaced by a boost in U.S. assistance to $40 million a year.
   UNITA has been fighting to force the Marxist Angolan government,
backed by Cuba, to share power since shortly after Angola gained
independence from Portugal in 1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
