<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Farm-Aid     10-30 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Farm-Aid,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Farmer Relief Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Monday signed legislation
that gives a break to farmers who are growing substitute crops on
land where drought destroyed or damaged earlier plantings.
   The measure eases restrictions that were part of a previous
federal farm-disaster aid package.
   The revision protects winter wheat and cotton farmers who
otherwise might have been denied disaster payments for their lost
crops under an Agriculture Department plan _ even though the
producers expect to earn little or no profit on replacement crops
such as grain sorghum or soybeans.
   The Agriculture Department, trying to prevent farmers from
reaping double benefits, has been planning to deduct 75 percent of
the gross value of any replacement crop from the disaster payment a
farmer would have otherwise received for losses on his first crop.
   Under the bill, approved by Congress last week, that system
would be modified.
   Farmers would have no payment deductions if the replacement
crops failed to produce more than 50 percent of the county average
yield for the second crop.
   But if the yield exceeded 50 percent of average yield, the
Agriculture Department's formula for deductions would kick in and
be applied only to the portion of the crop that exceeded the 50
percent mark.
   Under the Agriculture Department's initial plan, even farmers
who had replanted only a few acres would have to wait until
harvesting their second crop before obtaining disaster benefits for
damage to the first crop.
   That provision was canceled by the new legislation.
</TEXT>
