<HEAD>Officials: X-Rays Not Effective in Detecting Tampered Treats</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, `While the...' to restore first reference to
Harvit.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID WILKISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the nation's hospitals have pulled the plug on offers to
X-ray Halloween goodies, saying the once popular way to detect pins
and needles is too costly and is ineffective in preventing
poisoning.
   ``It cost a fortune,'' said Rose Ann Soloway, of the National
Capital Poison Center at Georgetown University Hospital in
Washington, D.C.
   ``Someone calculated the cost in health care dollars, and it's
an enormous amount of money nationwide,'' Ms. Soloway said. ``It's
money that's probably not well spent.
   ``If candy is going to be tampered with, there's any number of
ways of doing it,'' she said. ``X-rays can only detect foreign
objects, especially metallic objects. X-rays can't detect chemicals
or anything that could be put on or into foods.''
   Donna Siegfried, technical safety specialist for the National
Safety Council in Chicago, said hospitals began using X-ray
machines to examine Halloween treats in the mid-1970s, when reports
of glass and pins lodged in goods became more frequent.
   But some officials said hospitals are just providing parents
with a false sense of security.
   ``We were concerned that parents who brought candy in to the
emergency room to have it X-rayed and were told that there was
nothing in it were led to believe it was safe,'' said Janet
Ferguson, Cabell Huntington Hospital spokeswoman in Huntington,
W.Va.
   Not all hospitals are taking the advice of the nation's poison
centers. Bob Blackburn, chief technician for Logan General Hospital
in Logan, W.Va., said the hospital has X-rayed candy for the past
several years and will do so again this year.
   ``There is no way to detect poisons, but we try to detect a
metallic foreign body. At least we're giving the child a chance,''
Blackburn said.
   ``In the past, we have found different things, pins stuck into
fruit and candy,'' he said. ``We caution the people when we do the
candy for the kids. We caution them that we can't detect any
poison.''
   Cabell Huntington Hospital examined youngsters' treats until two
years ago, when the American Association of Poison Control Centers
suggested hospitals no longer X-ray candy.
   John Baldwin, head nurse of Cabell Huntington's emergency
department, said experts can detect foreign bodies by X-rays only
14 percent of the time, ``which means most of the time they
couldn't detect it even if it were there.''
   Ms. Soloway said it's important that parents inspect each piece
of candy themselves rather than depending on X-rays at hospitals.
   While the X-raying process often disrupted hospital routines, it
was offered with good intentions and an eye on public relations,
said West Virginia Poison Control Center spokeswoman Pam Harvit.
But by last year, concerns about liability outstripped the
benefits, she said.
   ``The problem we saw is that parents would take the candy to get
it X-rayed and then give the kids the candy and assume it was
safe,'' she said.
   While parents still have concerns about tampered candy, the
National Safety Council's Siegfried said the number of reported
incidents is low.
   ``It's not a big problem. Rumors start and the media gets hold
of it, and it's usually just some individual that wanted
attention,'' she said.
   ``Falls are the number one cause of injury because of masks,
running up and down stairs ... tripping over their costumes,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
