<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FCCBudget     10-30 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FCC Budget,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves $231 Million For FCC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Monday authorized $231.3 million
for the Federal Communications Commission over the next two years,
while ordering the agency to adopt a global perspective in
regulating the telecommunications industry.
   On a voice vote, the chamber gave the FCC $109.8 million in
spending authority for fiscal 1990, which began Oct. 1, and $121.5
million for fiscal 1991. That was an increase from $99.6 million in
1989.
   The Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee
earlier this month authorized $109.8 million for the FCC in 1990,
but only $119.8 million for 1991.
   The House on Friday approved a fiscal 1990 appropriations
measure containing the $109.8 million, which is the amount the
White House had sought. The Senate was expected to act on a
companion appropriation Tuesday.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., said the FCC needed the extra
money to cover costs of moving and consolidating agency offices in
1991 and to hire more people and facilities.
   Rep. Carlos J. Moorhead, R-Calif., said ``It is money the agency
sorely needs.''
   The House on Monday also authorized $29.3 million for the
Commerce Department's National Telecommunications and Information
Administration for 1990 and 1991.
   The FCC authorization was amended last week by the House Energy
and Commerce Committee to require the agency to consider what
impacts its rulings may have on U.S. trade.
   The amendment by Rep. Bill Richardson, D-N.M., was spurred by a
European Common Market decision last month to urge its 12 member
nations to broadcast television programs made in the market at
least 51 percent of the time, ``where practicable.''
   Richardson said that without giving the FCC increased authority
in matters of international trade, the amendment was a ``strong
signal'' that until foreign telecommunications markets are
completely open to U.S. companies, the United States will be
watching its own interests carefully.
   Markey said the measure gives the FCC no new authority in trade
matters, but it will tell ``the agency and the rest of the world
that we're serious about this international telecommunications
competition.''
</TEXT>
