<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru a0584 10-30 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Disperse Demonstrators at Trial in Kosovo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS wiht 11 grafs to UPDATE with details on clashes in Podujevo
and Pristina. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `At the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TITOVA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police using tear gas and
clubs dispersed 1,000 ethnic Albanians Monday who were protesting
the trial of the former Communist Party chief of Kosovo, a southern
province wracked by ethnic violence.
   Azem Vlasi, the ex-party leader, and 14 other ethnic Albanians
are accused of ``counterrevolutionary activities'' and opposing
constitutional changes that limited the province's autonomy.
   Death is the maximum penalty on conviction of the charges, which
include inciting ethnic Albanians to riot and strike. Vlasi's
co-defendants are officials and workers at a zinc and lead mine
where a strike occurred in March.
   Kosovo, with a predominantly ethnic Albanian population, is a
province in the republic of Serbia. For generations the Serbs and
ethnic Albanians have accused each other of discrimination.
   The trial was adjourned soon after it opened Monday as defense
lawyers asked for a change of venue. The lawyers said a fair trial
is impossible in Serbia because none of its courts could be
considered impartial.
   Police fired tear gas from armored vehicles and wielded
truncheons to disperse stone-throwing demonstrators in Podujevo, 20
miles from Pristina, the provincial capital of Kosovo. There also
were anti-Serb protests in Pristina.
   Before the confrontation in Podujevo, demonstrators marched
through the town chanting ``We Want Freedom'' and ``Azem! Azem!''
and trying to break through police lines. Azem is former party
leader Vlasi's first name.
   Many demonstrators were students and some wore scarves over
their faces to hide their identities.
   Small groups of protesters continued to roam the streets
following the main clash with police, hurling stones, breaking shop
windows and driving away Yugoslav and foreign journalists. Some
used cars and trash cans to erect street barricades.
   There were no reports of injuries but police were seen taking
away several people.
   In Pristina, police battled groups of protesters throughout the
city, including hundreds of students gathered around their school
dormitories. Police used tear gas in the pedestrian zone in the
downtown area, driving people screaming in panic down side streets.
   At the start of Monday's session in the Titova Mitrovica
courthouse, defense lawyers demanded that presiding Judge Ismet
Emra and prosecutor Spasone Zamfirovic be removed on grounds of
bias.
   Vlasi, 42, described the proceedings as a ``show trial staged
with clear political goals'' and claimed he was the victim of a
plot by archrival Slobodan Milosevic, president of Serbia.
   Until his arrest in March, Vlasi publicly opposed Milosevic's
efforts to increase control over Kosovo, an autonomous province in
which 85 percent of the 1.9 million people are ethnic Albanians. At
least 24 people were killed in the March violence.
   Milosevic and the Serbian leadership argued the changes were
necessary because of alleged harassment of the Serbian minority in
Kosovo, the heartland of ancient Serbia.
   Some analysts call the Vlasi case Yugoslaviaq's most important
political trial since that of Milovan Djilas in the 1950s. Djilas,
once heir apparent to the late President Tito, spent nine years in
jail for publicly criticizing the communist system and Tito's rule.
   Vlasi declared to the court Monday: ``The campaign to liquidate
me has lasted a long time ... and was conducted by Milosevic and
Rahman Morina,'' the current Kosovo party chief.
   Police cordoned off the courthouse and only 80 people, most of
them journalists or relatives of the accused, were allowed inside.
Several Western diplomats acting as human rights monitors were
among those denied access.
   The trial has been denounced in the liberal Yugoslav republics
of Slovenia and in Croatia as a Serbian bid to intimidate ethnic
Albanian dissent in Kosovo.
   Slovenian and Croatian members of the national collective
presidency and the Communist Party's ruling Presidium have urged
both bodies to demand the charges be dropped.
</TEXT>
