<FIRST>u w AM-Skinner-Buyouts     10-30 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinner-Buyouts,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Secretary Says Bill Would Give Him Too Much Authority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said
Monday he doesn't want the power over airline takeovers that a bill
pending in Congress would give him.
   ``This is a piece of expansive legislation that no person like
myself who favors deregulation could support,'' Skinner said in an
interview.
   The House has scheduled to take up Tuesday the Air Carrier
Securities Act, which would require the Transportation Department
to block purchase of 15 percent or more of an airline if the sale
threatened to hinder safety, reduce competition, break up the
carrier or put it under foreign control.
   On a related matter, Skinner said he and financial experts had
serious reservations about the proposed takeover of United
Airlines' parent company, UAL Corp., before the deal fell through.
But he denied any role in collapse of the buyout plan, which Wall
Street analysts say triggered the Oct. 13 drop in the stock market.
   ``The United Airlines transaction fell for one reason and one
reason only _ it was not sound financially,'' Skinner said.
   Collapse of the UAL takeover bid by its unions and management,
with backing from several banks and British Airways, followed
announcement of an agreement Skinner reached with Alfred Checchi to
scale down foreign participation in Checchi's takeover of Northwest
Airlines' parent company, NWA Inc. The department concluded that
the original deal put KLM Royal Dutch Airlines in a position to
control Northwest.
   Skinner said his decision to modify the NWA takeover was
``thoroughly coordinated with senior officials of the White House.''
   Responding to reports that he had been criticized for the NWA
action by others in the administration, Skinner said, ``Anybody who
says that I did not keep the White House informed fully as to what
was going on prior to making those decisions just isn't informed.''
   Skinner declined, however, to describe any conversations he had
with other administration officials over his NWA action.
   The airline takeover bill pending in the House has had strong
bipartisan support, passing the Public Works and Transportation
Committee 23-5. A similar measure passed the Senate Commerce,
Science and Transportation Committee but has not yet come up on the
Senate floor.
   The bills were prompted by a series of takeover moves in the
airline industry, including the United and Northwest deals and the
aborted attempt by developer Donald Trump to buy AMR Corp., parent
company of American Airlines. The decline in the stock market led
Trump to withdraw his $7.5 billion plan, which was opposed by AMR
management.
   Skinner and his deputy, Elaine Chao, both have sent letters to
Congress opposing the takeover bill, although Skinner had indicated
in earlier committee testimony that there may be advantages to
giving him power to approve takeovers rather than merely review
them after they are consummated.
   ``A preapproval process of existing law might be cleaner than
trying to unwrap a transaction; one can argue that,'' Skinner said
Monday, adding that when he made a similar statement before
Congress he may have been misinterpreted as supporting takeover
legislation.
   But he said the bills before Congress go too far.
   ``It goes far beyond the factors that under existing law I'm to
take into consideration,'' he said. Current law requires the
department to review airline aquisitions after they take place to
ensure that carriers are financially fit to operate safely and that
a foreign entity does not control them.
   Skinner said the proposed legislation would require him to
assess the impact of the deal on competition and to look at labor
provisions.
   ``That smacks of reregulation. It probably is reregulation and
is inappropriate in a deregulated environment,'' he said.
   ``The point is, I dont think I need it,'' Skinner said. ``I
think there are other ways I can do it.''
</TEXT>
