<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Charlotte     10-30 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Charlotte,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charlotte Begins Citywide Cleanup of Hugo Debris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army of workers assembled Monday for
the first citywide cleanup since the remnants of Hurricane Hugo
struck this inland city more than a month ago.
   Officials said the crews were prepared to stay on the job seven
days a week for at least five weeks to clean up the tons of debris
left behind by Hugo.
   ``They'll work until we get out from under the emergency,'' said
Fred Rogers, operations supervisor for street maintainence for the
city of Charlotte.
   Employees will have to be released for vacations, he said. ``But
we're going to keep it running until it's all finished,'' Rogers
said. The only day off for employees in the next several weeks will
be Thanksgiving Day, he said.
   Hurricane Hugo hit the U.S. mainland on Sept. 22, dealing its
strongest blow to Charleston, S.C. By the time it reached
Charlotte, its winds had slowed from 135 mph to a steady 70 mph and
it had been downgraded from a hurricane to a tropical storm.
   Still, it was powerful enough to uproot thousands of trees,
knock down power lines and flood low-lying areas. Three people died
in the Charlotte area and preliminary estimates put the damage at
$300 million.
   A thorough, citywide cleanup was delayed while local officials
waited for federal damage estimates to be made, and for bids to
come in from various contractors who would do the cleanup.
   The workers who assembled to begin the job Monday came from 80
of the state's 100 counties and found a city still choked with
storm debris. Rogers said there was enough debris left to fill
about 160,000 dump trucks, each carrying 10 cubic yards of trash.
   ``It's going real well,'' he said. ``This morning it was kind of
chaotic. But we've got them all together now and from now on, it
should be a routine type thing and we should have no more trouble.''
   About 300 state workers in about 200 Transportation Department
trucks arrived Sunday. They'll help about 250 city workers and
employees of 16 private companies.
   Storm debris is still causing problems in Charleston as well.
Parents there have been urged not to send their youngsters
trick-or-treating on Halloween, for fear that debris on curbsides
might create a safety hazard.
   ``We don't think it's safe for children to go trick-or-treating
with all the debris on city streets. It's safer for parents to have
Halloween parties,'' police Sgt. Ronald Hamilton said.
</TEXT>
