<FIRST>r w AM-LitmusTest 1stLd-Writethru   10-30 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Litmus Test, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0633,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>No `Litmus Test' for Top Medical Jobs, HHS Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs `But medical ...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with right-to-life comment. Picks up 8th graf pvs `William Danforth ...'
^By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush administration officials said Monday that
candidates for top medical jobs will not be rejected because of
their views on abortion or other political issues.
   Medical and scientific experts have been concerned recently that
an ideological ``litmus test'' centering on abortion and related
issues was prompting qualified candidates to withdraw from
consideration for top federal jobs, including the directorship of
the National Institutes of Health.
   In a speech Sunday, Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan said he took these concerns to the White House last week.
The administration has agreed, he said, that people being
considered for jobs below the level of assistant secretary do not
have to pass an ideological test.
   ``It has been our policy that standards of scientific and
administrative excellence and leadership prevail in the selection
process'' for scientific jobs, including heads of NIH and the
Centers for Disease Control, he said.
   However, he said, it was ``necessary and proper'' for Bush to
use the litmus test to fill positions at the level of assistant
secretary and above to select people who share his views.
   Conservative right-to-life groups have pressed the Bush
administration to appoint to positions at HHS people who share the
president's opposition to abortion.
   Douglas Johnson of the National Right to Life Committee said it
was particularly important that the head of NIH back the
president's abortion stance because ``a director who is inclined to
do so can undermine (the administration's) policy'' on such things
as research using fetal tissue.
   ``If the White House doesn't look into this, I'm sure some
senators will at the appropriate time,'' he said, referring to
Senate confirmation hearings on a nominee for NIH director.
   Medical and scientific experts have been concerned over reports
that at least one candidate for the NIH post withdrew after he got
a call from White House officials asking his position on abortion
and fetal tissue research.
   William Danforth, chancellor of Washington University in St.
Louis, reportedly told the caller that if that was all they wanted
to know about him, he was not interested in the job.
   Danforth has declined to answer questions on the subject. In a
statement, he has said he is not interested in leaving Washington
University and ``any conjecture about my candidacy, possible
conversations with White House representatives and others ... are
simply irrelevant.''
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush will
continue exploring the political views of candidates for
policy-making jobs in the health field.
   ``We'll still certainly ask them for their position on abortion,
fetal tissue research, AIDS, the whole range of issues that they
would have to be directing federal policy on,'' he said. ``But for
those jobs that essentially technical, below the assistant
secretary level, the answer is no.''
   He said the surgeon general's job ``would be a policy-making
job. We certainly would want to know that they support the
president's position.''
   Bush's candidate for surgeon general, Antonia Novello, deputy
director of the National Institute of Child Health and Human
Development, was asked her views on abortion before being selected
by the president, officials have said.
   Earlier this month, when the reports about Danforth surfaced and
it became clear that Novello was in line to be nominated,
administration officials said the abortion question was being asked
of candidates for most jobs at HHS, though that was not necessarily
the deciding factor.
   Scientists and medical experts said they feared that the
volatile issue would further politicize top government medical jobs
like the NIH post, which remains unfilled.
</TEXT>
