<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Pierce'sBills     10-30 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pierce's Bills,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce's Lawyer Complains Government Won't Pay Legal Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former HUD Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr.'s
lawyer accused the Justice Department Monday of giving an
``off-the-wall'' reason for not paying Pierce's legal expenses from
a congressional investigation.
   A Justice Department spokesman said it was just an
interpretation of law.
   Pierce twice refused to answer questions when he appeared before
the House Employment and Housing Subcommittee, which has been
investigating allegations of political favoritism at the Department
of Housing and Urban Development, which he headed during the Reagan
administration.
   He contended that because the hearings related to his tenure at
the department, HUD should pay his fees.
   The department forwarded Pierce's request to the Justice
Department for a ruling on whether the former secretary qualified
for reimbursement under the regulations.
   Two weeks later, the Justice Department replied that it had no
responsibility to represent Pierce and therefore would not rule on
whether he qualified for reimbursement. The department said it was
up to HUD whether to represent Pierce or pay his fees.
   ``It's a hot potato,'' said Pierce attorney Robert Plotkin.
``HUD hands off to Justice, Justice hands off back to HUD.''
   Plotkin said the Justice Department defied a plain reading of
government regulations when it determined it wasn't responsible for
expenses Pierce incurred during the subcommittee investigation.
   ``I couldn't believe that of several potential grounds that
perhaps they might have used to justify not paying it, the one they
used seemed so off-the-wall,'' Plotkin said.
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said ``our decision
was based on the civil division's interpretation of the law. The
lawyers took a look at it and that's their decision.''
   Plotkin said the Justice Department stretched hard to formulate
an interpretation of the regulations that allowed it to avoid
making a politically difficult decision on Pierce's request.
   The regulation states that current and former federal officials
``may be provided representation in civil and congressional
proceedings and in state criminal proceedings ... when the actions
for which representation is requested reasonably appear to have
been performed within the scope of the employee's employment and
providing representation would otherwise be in the interest of the
United States.''
   ``One would think that clearly, on it's face we are eligible,''
Plotkin said. ``And then they have to exercise their discretion as
to whether or not they want to pay it.''
   But in an Oct. 25 letter to HUD, Deputy Assistant Attorney
General Stephen C. Bransdorfer said that legal representation by
the Justice Department ``is available only in situations where the
employee is subject to civil or state criminal proceedings as a
result of actions taken within the normal scope of that employee's
authority.
   ``If there are no such underlying proceedings then
representation is not available,'' Bransdorfer said.
   There are no civil or state criminal proceedings against Pierce.
   According to Bransdorfer's determination, HUD said it was
recommending that Pierce's request be denied.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
