<SECOND>AM-Final Days-TV,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Nixon Drama Second in Overnight Ratings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's ``The Final Days,'' a movie about
President Nixon's last weeks in office during the Watergate
scandal, was second to CBS on Sunday in overnight ratings for 21
cities, ABC estimates showed Monday.
   The television drama, the making of which had drawn criticism
from Nixon through his lawyers, averaged a 12.6 rating and 20
percent share of the audience in its three-hour time period.
   The film, a dramatization of the 1976 best seller by Carl
Bernstein and Robert Woodward, did better in Washington, D.C.
Although it also was second to CBS there, it averaged a 15.3 rating
and a 24 per cent share.
   In the 21-city overnight ratings, CBS won the night with ``60
Minutes,'' ``Murder, She Wrote'' and a TV movie, ``The Lady
Forgets.'' CBS averaged an 18.5 rating and a 29 percent share.
   NBC was third, averaging a 10.1 rating and 16 percent share for
its 8-to-11 p.m. roster of ``Sister Kate,'' ``My Two Dads'' and a
TV movie, ``Double Your Pleasure.''
   Ratings represent the number of homes tuned in and shares the
percentage of audience tuned to a given program. National audience
estimates for Sunday night won't be available until Tuesday, a
spokeswoman for A.C. Nielsen Co. said.
</TEXT>
