<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1813EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MinimumWage     10-30 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Status Quo as Republicans Search for Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republicans frustrated by a lack of
guidance from the White House searched Monday for a compromise on
raising the minimum wage in the hope of avoiding a partisan fight
as an election year looms.
   The White House didn't publicly rule out a compromise, but said
that for now it stood by its offer to raise the hourly minimum wage
from $3.35 to $4.25 by January 1992 _ a year later than the
Democratic proposal due for a vote Wednesday.
   ``We are not changing our position at this point,'' White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said. Chief of Staff John Sununu is
discussing the issue with congressional leaders, Fitzwater said.
   But even Republicans said the White House was doing little more
than listening, and it appeared the administration was losing the
support of some conservative Democrats and moderate Republicans who
helped Bush win a veto battle on the issue earlier this year.
   One of those conservative Democrats, Rep. Timothy Penny of
Minnesota, said it appeared the White House had abandoned thoughts
of striking a deal.
   ``It sounds like they're digging in their heals again,'' he
said. ``Picking another fight like this is causing a lot of us to
question their sincerity because a deal is within reach.''
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said the discussions
were continuing, but added: ``I don't know how fruitful they are.''
   Even an administration official close to the negotations
complained of ``a lack of focus'' from the White House that had
``left dangling'' the GOP leadership. The Republicans had hoped to
strike a compromise to avoid another veto fight, a potential issue
in 1990 congressional elections.
   Because of the White House position, the Republican leadership
was mulling a number of proposals of its own, with a whip count
planned for Tuesday likely to determine the final shape of the
measure it will offer as an alternative to the Democrats' plan.
   The Democrats also planned a head count, and were mulling
changes designed to win back enough conservative Democrats to
override a second Bush veto.
   Even the administration official said the Democratic leadership
was within reach of winning a veto-proof majority in the House.
   ``Some of the votes we got last time we got with the message
very clear that it was `this time and this time only,''' said the
official, speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``Right now it's
probably five or six votes either way.''
   The current bill would increase the minimum wage to $3.80 on
Jan. 1 and to $4.25 on Jan. 1, 1991. It also would allow workers
with fewer than two months job experience to be paid a subminimum
wage.
   Penny and other conservative Democrats want the two 45-cent
increases pushed back to April 1, 1990, and April 1, 1991, and the
``subminimum'' period extended to three or four months.
   ``That would make a big difference to several members,'' he said.
   Bush has insisted that to get his signature a minimum wage bill
also would have to allow employers to pay all new workers a
subminimum for up to six months regardless or prior job experience.
Democrats have said they would never accept such language.
   In addition to next year's elections, two other factors have
strengthened the Democrats' hand.
   The $4.25-an-hour target is more acceptable to many conservative
Democrats than the $4.55 level in the measure Bush vetoed. Also,
the fight over Bush's attempt to cut the capital gains tax has
allowed the Democratic leadership to shape the issue as one of rich
vs. poor.
</TEXT>
