<HEAD>Cason Nomination Held Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senator put the nomination of James Cason as
assistant secretary of agriculture on hold Monday, calling Cason
``a James Watt clone.''
   ``I think he would be a disaster,'' Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev.,
said of the man President Bush wants to head forest and
conservation programs at the Agriculture Department.
   Reid's request that the nomination be put on hold prevents full
Senate debate until Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine,
removes the hold.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter has urged the Senate to
confirm Cason as quickly as possible and has said that he expects
Cason to follow the environmental agenda he sets.
   ``He feels confident that Jim Cason is the person to do the
job,'' said Yeutter spokeswoman Kelly Shipp.
   Reid said he disapproved of decisions Cason has made as a
high-ranking Interior Department official, such as liberalizing
strip mining in national parks.
   ``I think he (Cason) is a James Watt clone,'' Reid said.
   Watt was the controversial Reagan administration official who
resigned under public pressure.
   Cason was hired at the Interior Department while Watt was
secretary, but he said during confirmation hearings that he barely
knew Watt.
   Agriculture Chairman Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., also opposes
Cason, though his committee voted 12-7 to send the nomination to
the full Senate.
   Cason, 35, has held a variety of high-ranking posts at the
Interior Department since the early days of the Reagan
administration. Leahy accused him of consistently putting private
interests ahead of public ones.
