<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Balfour     10-30 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Balfour,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earl Of Balfour Says Israel Must Keep Present Boundaries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAIFA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Earl of Balfour, whose granduncle wrote
a declaration supporting establishment of a Jewish national home in
Palestine, said Monday that Israel must keep its present
``protectable'' boundaries.
   Balfour is in this northern port for a symposium on the 1917
Balfour Declaration, which opens Tuesday. The declaration is a
major document in the history of the Zionist movement and in the
history of Israel's establishment.
   ``Lawrence of Arabia promised to the Arabs that every country
will keep what she fought for but I did not find any evidence that
there was any Arab country that fought on the Jordan valley,'' he
told a reporter.
   ``Therefore when it comes to the present boundaries of Israel,
including what's inside, Israel has to keep and protect and develop
her boundaries ... because these boundaries are protectable,''
Balfour said.
   ``You fought for this country and it belongs to you.''
   His reference was to T.E. Lawrence, who rallied Arabs to fight
on the side of Britain in World War I.
   Israel's former prime minister, Menachem Begin, was invited to
attend the symposium but instead sent a letter, saying Israel would
remember the Balfour Declaration as ``a turning point in the
history of the Jewish people.''
   However, he accused Britain of changing the document's meaning
over the years, focusing on ``the Land of Israel instead of the
Land of Israel as home for the Jewish people ... when millions of
Jews cried for a homeland.''
   Israel was created in 1948 after more than a half-century of
efforts by Zionist leaders to establish a sovereign nation as a
homeland for Jews.
   Begin, 76, referred to the Zionist draft of the document that
called for reconstituting Palestine ``as the National Home of the
Jewish people.''
   The Nov. 2, 1917, declaration written in the form of a letter to
the president of the British Zionist Federation stated that ``His
Majesty's Government view with favour the establishment in
Palestine of a national home for the Jewish people.''
   Begin became prime minister in 1977 and resigned abruptly in
August 1983. Aides said then that he was depressed over the death
of his wife and over Israel's protracted involvement in Lebanon
following its June 1982 invasion.
   He has lived mostly in seclusion since then.
</TEXT>
