<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Ortega     10-30 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Ortega,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Asked Argentine Help in Demobilizing Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR J. SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua's leader Daniel Ortega
asked President Carlos Menem to organize political support to
demobilize the Nicaraguan rebels, Foreign Minister Domingo Cavallo
said Monday.
   Menem ``responded that he is going to do everything possible to
help achieve peace in that region,'' Cavallo added. ``Right away,
I'm going to begin talks with (hemispheric) foreign ministers to
see what we can do.''
   But Menem, speaking with reporters about his talks Sunday with
the Nicaraguan leader in Managua said Argentina would not mediate
the dispute.
   ``We just talked. Don't take this as a kind of mediation or
anything like that. It was simply a gesture of good faith'' he said.
   Menem and Cavallo made their comments in separate meetings with
reporters and it was unclear what role Argentina might play in the
Nicaraguan conflict.
   Both returned Monday from San Jose, Costa Rica, where they and
leaders from more than a dozen nations, including President Bush,
attended Costa Rica's weekend celebration of its 100th anniversary
of independence.
   The Argentine delegation made a stopover in Nicaragua and Menem
spoke for 90 minutes with President Ortega.
   In Managua, Menem indicated he might intervene on Ortega's
behalf with Central American governments and President Bush to seek
a U.S. commitment to demobilize the Nicaraguan rebels, known as
Contras.
   Menem was quoted as saying, ``I have taken upon myself the task
of making those gestures.
   ``We have appealed to the good will of the Nicaraguan
government, but we are going to work so that the presidential
accords of Tela, Honduras, are fulfilled by the demobilization of
the Contras and by this arrive at peace in Central America.''
   Ortega was quoted as saying Menem's offer ``is the first
concrete action to save the critical situation in which Nicaragua
is living. We are going to take very much into account the decision
of President Menem.''
   Back in Buenos Aires, Menem was asked if his comments meant he
would try to mediate the Nicaraguan dispute.
   ``I don't see that because it should be the U.S. government
directly'' he said, referring to Washington's support of the rebels.
   Ortega stunned the other leaders at the Costa Rican celebrations
when he announced his Sandinista government may end a unilateral
cease-fire in the war with the Contras. He accused the rebels of
violating the accord signed in Tela, Honduras, on Aug. 7 by himself
and four other Central American presidents.
   The accords call for free elections in Nicaragua, which Ortega's
government says will be held in February, and demobilization of the
Contras by Dec. 5.
   Most of the estimated 11,000 rebels operate out of bases in
Honduras near the border with Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
