<DOCNO> AP891030-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Ivory     10-30 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Ivory,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Joins International Ban on Ivory Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan, which buys more ivory than any other
country, said Monday it would join a ban on the ivory trade that is
intended to protect African elephants.
   The ban was adopted Oct. 17 at a meeting of the 91-nation
Convention on Trade in Endangered Species and is to remain in
effect at least until 1992.
   Japan had until Jan. 18 to decide whether to file an appeal,
which would allow it to continue trading ivory with other countries
that did the same or with the more than 60 nations outside the
accord.
   Hajime Tsujimoto of the Foreign Ministry's U.N. office
acknowledged that international attention on Japan as the world's
main ivory consumer had played a role in the decision.
   He also told reporters the decision did not necessarily mean
Japan was out of the market permanently, and that it ``may import
if the circumstances in the world change.''
   If the elephant is removed from the endangered species list, he
said, ``the story will be different.''
   Zimbabwe, Botswana, Malawi and Mozambique have objected to the
ban on grounds their elephant herds are not endangered and they
depend on ivory sales to finance successful conservation. By filing
for exemptions, they may continue trade in ivory with other
countries that do not accept the ban.
   A recent census estimated Africa now has about 600,000
elephants, fewer than half the total of a decade ago.
   About 30,000 people in Japan are employed in the ivory industry,
which carves elephant tusks into ornaments, jewelry and personal
signature seals.
   Tsujimoto said some might have to find other jobs eventually,
but Japan has enough ivory in stock to last about two years.
   Japan regularly has taken about 40 percent of the world's ivory
exports. Imports totaled 106 tons in 1988 and 143 tons in 1987.
   It is to be host of the next meeting of the convention, in April
1992.
   Tsujimoto said Japan would like to study aid to African
countries for better management of elephant populations.
   ``We are deeply concerned about the rapid decline in the number
of elephants over the last 10 years,'' he said. ``We believe
drastic measures should be taken to prevent further decline in the
number and seek proper protection of the animals.''
   In Hong Kong, up to 400 ivory traders and carvers marched
through downtown streets Monday to protest the ban. Adeline Li of
the Hong Kong and Kowloon Ivory Manufacturers' Association said
about 4,000 people worked in the industry in Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1852EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Pravda 1stLd-Writethru a0683 10-30 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pravda, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda Editor Meets the Press, With Himself the Target</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One graf SUBS for 14th graf, ``After Politburo ... DELETING
extraneous quotation mark. Picks up 15th graf, It would ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Gorbachev confidant who is now Pravda's editor
met the foreign press Monday and made himself the target, a
definite change at a paper that has bashed imperialists mercilessly
for generations.
   Asked how he will stop a sharp decline in readership in
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's era of glasnost, or openness, Ivan
Frolov said: ``We shall not seek to increase circulation at all
costs.''
   Although he offered some ideas for enlivening the gray columns _
interviews with members of the ruling Politburo, for instance _ the
60-year-old editor seemed to hold weak commitment by today's
Communists as responsible as the party daily's content for its
flagging fortunes.
   ``I can ask the question even more directly: Do we need more
genuine Communists, members of the CPSU, than the already known
number of Pravda subscribers?'' Frolov said, implying that the real
Communist today is one who dutifully reads the paper.
   Only one week into his new job, the white-haired former
Gorbachev adviser already has done something that would have been a
surprise coming from his remote predecessor Viktor Afanasyev, who
ran the paper for 13 years.
   Frolov opened Pravda's 8th floor conference room to foreign
correspondents and sought their questions.
   It was a unique opportunity to hear the views of a member of the
policy-making party Central Committee now in charge of the most
authoritative, if no longer most widely read, Soviet newspaper.
   As is the custom in such confrontations, Frolov occasionally
avoided straight answers _ on Pravda's circulation, for example.
   ``We don't have definitive information; the circulation was once
10,700,000; it will probably be less,'' he said from the head of a
rectangle of wooden tables pushed together to make room for more
than 100 journalists, all but a few of them foreigners.
   Pravda, officially the organ of the party Central Committee, now
has tough competition from other dailies that have taken advantage
of glasnost to publish more daring or spicier stories.
   Also, Soviet citizens no longer are required to take Pravda to
get another publication they really want, such as a literary
monthly or a magazine about movies.
   A Pravda official told a Westerner who visited the paper last
month that only 3 million to 4 million people had subscribed for
next year.
   Frolov said research would be used to determine why Pravda's
readership has dropped. He said there would be ``some innovations''
to tempt readers, among them exclusive publication of some Central
Committee documents.
   ``After Politburo meetings, we shall publish interviews with the
leaders of the party on what they personally think of the subjects
raised there,'' he said.
   It would be a departure if Politburo members were persuaded to
give their personal views on its decisions, customarily made in
secret and always presented as unanimous.
   Frolov made clear Pravda will not become the pugnacious,
Western-style newspaper some Soviets say is needed to safeguard the
public interest.
   ``I must say, the decision about coverage of Central Committee
or Politburo events is made by the appropriate bodies, and you will
agree that it is quite proper and that they ought to have the
authority to do it,'' he said, defending the party's right to do
business behind closed doors.
   That was his response when asked why Pravda and other papers had
not printed an account of the meeting earlier this month with
ranking editors, in which Gorbachev was said to have accused some
of excesses or ideological errors.
   Western reporters found that many Soviet journalists who
attended the technically secret meeting were ready to talk about it.
   How does Frolov see the future of the newspaper founded by Lenin
in 1912 as a tool to whip up hostility to the czar among workers?
   ``We shall not become a non-serious, light paper,'' he said.
``We shall not chase hot news, publish non-verified facts or poorly
analyzed materials. We shall not seek to increase circulation at
all costs.''
   Pravda, he said, will try to ``express the very essence of
present-day party policies.''
   That does not mean Frolov shuns making the paper more attractive.
   ``As far as I am concerned, there can be nothing more attractive
than good analysis,'' said the editor, a graduate in philosopy from
Moscow State University.
