<FIRST>r a AM-ElderlySlayings     10-30 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elderly Slayings,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slayings of Two Women Stun Small Community</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALD KNOB, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said they had some leads Monday
in the deaths of two elderly women whose blood-drenched bodies were
found in homes 500 yards apart, 12 hours after they returned from
the same church service.
   The two women were beaten, stabbed and apparently robbed over
the weekend, authorities said.
   ``We've got leads and we hope to make an arrest or arrests,''
said Cpl. R.A. Miller of the Boone County Sheriff's Department.
   The slayings stunned people in the small community, about 25
miles south of Madison.
   ``This has tore everybody all to pieces,'' said Beth Kinder of
Charleston, who was in Bald Knob on Monday visiting her mother.
``Now people are panicking. We've never had anything like this
happen.''
   The body of Faye Jarrell, 83, was found Sunday morning after a
neighbor knocked on her door and got no answer. A short time later,
another person spotted an open door next door and notified police,
who found the body of Dorothy Daniels, 68.
   Both had last been seen Saturday night at the Bald Knob
Methodist Church, where they attended a wake for a neighbor.
   Both victims' homes had been ransacked and were missing small
items, Miller said. But he said more valuable items usually taken
during a robbery, such as televisions and prescription drugs, had
not been touched.
   ``The motive we're looking at right now is robbery,'' Miller
said. ``We can't substantiate any other motive at this time.''
   Miller said an autopsy showed that both victims had been stabbed
repeatedly and beaten.
   ``There is no evidence of gunshot wounds,'' Miller said. ``...
There was a considerable amount of blood.
   The victims apparently lived modestly, and there was no
indication of what prompted the attack, Miller said.
   ``They didn't appear wealthy,'' he said. ``They were elderly and
lived alone. Nothing extravagant. They were neat in their houses.
It looked like one lady had done some quilting.''
   Rose Belcher, who lives a half-mile from the two houses, said
she had known the victims all her life.
   ``They were well thought-of in the community,'' she said. ``It's
a big shock to all of us. My only thought is someone must have
thought they had some money. It's so sick.''
</TEXT>
