<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia     10-30 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report 149 People Arrested During Demonstration to be Charged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government news media said
Monday that 149 of the 355 demonstrators arrested during an
anti-government protest will be charged with violating public order.
   The Communist Party daily Rude Pravo said the 149 were detained
for 48 hours and all of the others arrested during the
demonstration Saturday in Prague were released soon after they had
been seized.
   Rude Pravo did not say if the 149 were still in jail and an
Interior Ministry official said only that they had been held for 48
hours.
   At a regular news conference Monday, deputy goverment spokesman
Marcel Jansen quickly told reporters he had no official statement
on the demonstration and they should address questions to chief
government spokesman Miroslav Pavel, who is on vacation.
   The party newspaper said the 149 would be charged under
anti-demonstration laws passed earlier this year that impose fines
of up to $2,000.
   More than 10,000 people gathered Saturday in Prague's Wenceslas
Square to mark the 71st anniversary of Czechoslovak independence.
They chanted calls for free elections, a new government and the
removal of Communist Party leader Milos Jakes.
   Rude Pravo said five policemen and seven demonstrators were
injured in clashes during the rally but all had been treated and
none remained hospitalized.
   The state media provided no information about 17 foreigners
reported detained during the rally, other than repeat the report
and say the foreigners were from 11 different countries.
   Rude Pravo again accused the U.S.-funded Radio Free Europe and
Voice of America radio stations for the anti-government
demonstration.
   In Washington, the State Department criticized the crackdown on
the pro-democracy rally.
   Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said, ``The people of
Czechoslovakia know what democracy is and they want it now.''
   ``The U.S. calls on the government of Czechoslovakia to respect
the rights of its citizens and to institute the basic freedoms
desired by the Czechoslovakian people.''
   The newspaper Mlada Fronta, published for Communist youths, did
not take the hard line followed by Rude Pravo.
   Rude Pravo referred to the people surrounded and attacked by
riot police in Wenceslas Square as the ``aggressive'' core of the
demonstration.
   Mlada Fronta said about 300 demonstrators were involved and they
were peaceful. It noted the people chanted demands to police not to
use violence and shouted, ``We have bare hands!'' raising their
arms to show they were unarmed.
</TEXT>
