<FIRST>r a AM-StPaulFires     10-30 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-St Paul Fires,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>St. Paul Fire Chief To Step Aside While Allegations Investigated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE LAHAMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city fire chief is stepping aside
while officials look into allegations he had links to arsonists,
Mayor George Latimer announced Monday.
   Reports about Fire Chief Stephen Conroy are ``shocking and
disturbing,'' Latimer said.
   ``If there was wrongdoing, it will be prosecuted and
penalized,'' the mayor said in announcing Conroy would take paid
administrative leave.
   Latimer also said firefighters have been barred from
moonlighting for fire adjusting companies, a practice criticized by
fire experts quoted in Sunday's report in the Star Tribune of
Minneapolis.
   The Star Tribune reported that properties owned by Conroy or his
brother, Patrick, have had 11 fires in the past 25 years. It also
noted that two associates of Patrick Conroy were convicted of arson
in 1986.
   Stephen Conroy told the newspaper that he has no connections
with any ``fire industry'' in St. Paul, and said his department
``is looked on as one of the better fire departments in the
country.'' His brother denied any involvement in arson.
   ``We are confident that after a thorough investigation, we will
be totally exonerated from any wrongdoing of any nature,'' said
Earl P. Gray, an attorney representing Stephen Conroy.
   Latimer said Conroy requested an examination by outside
investigators so he could clear his name. He added that the chief
agreed to cooperate fully with the investigators, and volunteered
to take the administrative leave.
   ``I did not have to urge him. He made the offer,'' the mayor
said. ``He obviously is in a lot of pain and is very sad today.''
   Latimer said Ramsey County Attorney Tom Foley has agreed that
the investigation into the allegations should be handled by an
outside agency,
   The newspaper report said the fire chief has allowed
firefighters to moonlight for an adjusting company that has
represented alleged arsonists in fire insurance claims. It also
said shoddy investigations by the department have helped arson
thrive.
   The newspaper said its report focused on more than 200 fires in
St. Paul over the past 25 years that in some way involved Stephen
or Patrick Conroy, public adjuster William Whelan, or their friends
and associates.
   The newspaper said Stephen Conroy gave $10,000 to set Whelan up
in business as a public adjuster before becoming chief. It also
said that Whelan's most frequent contractor has been Patrick
Conroy, and that companies owned by Whelan and Patrick Conroy have
received millions of dollars in insurance money from St. Paul fires.
   Asked why many of his cases involved arson fires, Whelan said,
``I have no idea.'' He said arsonists who have worked on his staff
were not known arsonists at the time.
   The Star Tribune said its reporters examined more than 10,000
pages of documents and interviewed hundreds of people.
   City police and the state Bureau of Criminal Apprehension raised
questions about Stephen Conroy 10 years ago, but their
investigation died amid political squabbles, the newspaper said.
   Latimer said Deputy Fire Chief John Colonna, 43, who has been
with the department for 18{ years, will serve as acting chief while
Conroy is on leave.
   Colonna said he hopes the latest allegations can be cleared up
quickly.
   ``It's easy for anyone to see that these kinds of articles would
affect the morale of the Fire Department,'' he said. ``That's why
it's so important that this be brought to a public conclusion.''
   Latimer, who has served as mayor since 1976, is not seeking
re-election in next Tuesday's general election.
</TEXT>
