<FIRST>r i AM-Amnesty-Turkey     10-30 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amnesty-Turkey,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty Reports Unabated Use of Torture in Turkey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International said Tuesday that anyone
detained in Turkey for suspected political offenses is in danger of
being tortured.
   The worldwide human rights organization said use of torture to
obtain information or confessions from political prisoners
continued unabated on a wide scale in violation of international
treaties signed and ratified by Turkey last year.
   London-based Amnesty said in a new report that more than 500
political prisoners alleged they were tortured in Turkey so far
this year and 10 such prisoners were said to have died in custody
as a result of being tortured.
   Amnesty said most of the allegations relate to initial
interrogations in police custody while detainees were routinely
denied access to lawyers or relatives.
   It said that while its report does not discuss torture of
criminal prisoners, ``they, too, are frequently reported to have
been ill-treated and tortured.''
   Amnesty reported ``the government ... has consistently denied
that torture is systematic in Turkey and has described those
instances of torture which it admits as the isolated actions of
individuals.''
   The organization welcomed as a step in the right direction draft
amendments to the Turkish Criminal Procedure Code announced in
September. But it said they fall short of international standards
that require all detainees be brought before a judge soon after
detention and have prompt access to lawyers, doctors and relatives.
   The proposals, which still must be approved by the Turkish Grand
National Assembly, would shorten the maximum detention period to
four to 10 days and grant lawyers access to detainees. The maximum
detention period permitted before a detainee is either formally
charged or released now is 24 hours. In political cases it may be
extended to 15 days, however, and under emergency legislation up to
30 days.
   Specific cases cited by Amnesty include 21 students held
incommunicado at Ankara police headquarters on the day the
government announced the draft amendments. The students later said
they were tortured while being interrogated.
   One, 20-year-old Yusuf Ali Yildiz, said that during six days in
custody he was stripped naked, hosed down with pressurized cold
water, beaten and given electric shocks.
   The report also cited the death of Seyhmus Orhan from Yoncali
village in southeastern Turkey. It said he died on July 18 after 24
hours of interrogation at the Command of the 118th Gendarmerie
Regiment. Officials said he was shot trying to escape. Other
detainees and relatives said he was killed under torture and shot
afterward.
   Amnesty, winner of the 1977 Nobel Peace Prize, said statements
extracted under torture are used as evidence against political
prisoners.
   It said the Maltaya State Security Court convicted four people
in September of belonging to the illegal organization Devrimci Yol
(Revolutionary Path) without investigating their allegations that
their confessions were extracted under torture.
   The defendants told the court they were stripped, hosed with
ice-cold water, beaten and given electric shocks, Amnesty said. One
said he confessed when police threatened to torture his wife.
   Amnesty said it repeatedly urged the Turkish government to take
effective steps to prevent torture and to meet its obligations
under European and United Nations conventions for the prevention of
torture.
   It said it also asked Turkey to establish independent and
impartial procedures to investigate allegations of torture and to
ensure that statements extracted under torture are not used as
evidence against defendants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
