<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Glance     10-30 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Glance,620</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a clance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court on Monday
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PENSIONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court agreed to consider how much authority the federal
government has in holding a company responsible for its pension
plans. The case arose from a federal agency's order that LTV Corp.
restore three terminated pension plans that had an unfunded
liability of $2.3 billion. A federal appeals court set aside that
order, and the Supreme Court agreed to consider whether the lower
court's order was correct.
   The case is PBGC vs. LTV, 89-390.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AIDS TESTING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal from the Eastern
Nebraska Human Services Agency, which wanted to require AIDS
testing for all employees who come in direct contact with mentally
retarded people served by the agency. Lower court rulings blocked
the required AIDS testing, and the Supreme Court decision lest
those rulings stand.
   The case is Eastern Nebraska Community Office of Retardation vs.
Glover, 88-1805.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MARRIAGE &amp; MINISTERS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court turned down the appeal of Roy Torcaso, a member of the
American Humanist Association, who argued that a Virginia law was
unconstitutional because it favors ordained ministers in
officiating at weddings.
   The case is Torcaso vs. Virginia, 89-375.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NAVY DIVERS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court today left intact a $4.25 million award to the
families of five Navy divers killed in a 1982 accident aboard the
submarine USS Grayback in the Philippines. The justices, without
comment, rejected an appeal by General Dynamics Corp., designer of
the diving chamber in which the men died.
   The case is General Dynamics vs. Trevino, 89-376.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DES DAMAGES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court refused to hear appeals by E.R. Squibb &amp; Sons, Eli
Lilly and Co. and Rexall Drug Co. from a ruling by the New York
Court of Appeals aimed at forcing all manufacturers to share in
paying damages for injuries allegedly caused by diethylstilbestrol,
a synthetic female hormone made by 300 companies from 1947 to 1971
to prevent miscarriages.
   The cases were Rexall Drug Co. vs. Tigue, 89-168; E.R. Squibb &amp;
Sons vs. Hymowitz, 89-204; Eli Lilly vs. Hymowitz, 89-397.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HERBICIDE DAMAGES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court let stand a $1.5 million award won by the family of
James Greenhill, a U.S. Forest Service employee who died of cancer
in 1979 after his exposure to a Dow Chemical Co. herbicide, 2,4-D,
in 1976-1978, refusing a Dow appeal aimed at winning a new trial in
the product-liability case. a0530
   The case was Dow Chemical vs. Greenhill, 89-395.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WARRANTLESS SEARCH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court agreed to use a Chicago drug prosecution to hear
arguments that police without a warrant should be allowed to use
drug evidence seized after they were allowed into a man's apartment
by his girlfriend who did not live there.
   The case is Illinois vs. Rodriguez, 88-2018.
</TEXT>
