<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Prices     10-30 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Prices,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Raised up to 150 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government imposed steep increases on
energy prices, effective Wednesday, in conjunction with a revised
budget passed by Parliament that slashes coal subsidies.
   The price increases and spending cuts were the latest exercise
in fiscal toughness from the 2-month-old government led by Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki of Solidarity in its effort to control
the economic crisis.
   A Finance Ministry statement Monday said electricity would go up
150 percent, natural gas 100 percent and bills for heat and hot
water 50 percent.
   ``Low retail prices of electricity, heat and gas fuels in
relation to the cost of production and to other fuels make it
necessary to increase retail prices,'' it said. ``This increase is
a logical result of the recent increase in the price of coal.''
   Similar price increases have brought down Communist governments
and led to the birth of Solidarity in 1980s as the Soviet bloc's
first independent trade union, but public forbearance toward
Mazowiecki continues.
   An official announcement Monday said donations to help support
his government had reached $138,000, most of it from individuals.
   Foreign governments also have offered tens of millions of
dollars' help in Poland's move toward democracy and a market
economy.
   The first grain shipment donated by the United States arrived
off the Baltic port of Gdynia on Monday. Washington said three
Cabinet members would lead a delegation arriving in late November
to determine how U.S. aid can be used most effectively.
   Parliament approved the amended budget Monday by a vote of
301-4, with 35 abstentions. It reduces the projected deficit from
9.2 trillion zlotys ($3.8 billion) to 4.7 trillion ($1.96 billion)
and trims subsidies for the coal industry by 1.2 trillion zlotys
($500 million).
   It puts expenditures at 34.4 trillion zlotys ($14.3 billion) in
1989 and income at 29.7 trillion zlotys ($12.4 billion).
   The government hopes partially closing the budget gap will
reduce the amount of money in circulation and slow inflation, now
at about 600 percent annually.
   Many food subsidies also have been trimmed, along with
government-financed projects and spending on social services.
   On Oct. 16, Parliament restricted an indexation plan that
provides automatic pay increases to counteract inflation.
</TEXT>
