<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0718 10-30 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockies Freeze While East Basks in Record Warmth</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Winds gusted ...,' to CORRECT name of city to
Junction, sted Junction City.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures dipped below zero in Colorado on Monday, the East
Coast basked in record warmth, and rain was scattered across the
nation's midsection.
   The rain marked the eastern edge of a cold front that reached
from the Great Lakes south to Texas. Temperatures were unusually
cold west of the front, but balmy to the east.
   The low temperature for the nation overnight was 2 degrees below
zero at Alamosa, Colo. Klamath Falls, Ore., set a record for the
date with a low of 19 degrees overnight.
   In contrast, high-temperature records fell in Alpena, Mich.,
where it was 73 degrees, and Concord, N.H., where it was 75.
Burlington, Vt., tied its old record of 70, and Portland, Maine,
matched its old record for the date of 71.
   Rain and thunderstorms from the cold front extended from the
upper and middle Texas coast to northeast and central Texas,
western Louisiana and Arkansas. Rain also reached from Missouri to
Iowa, southeast Minnesota, Wisconsin and northwestern Illinois.
   Rain also fell over the Carolinas, and snow showers were
scattered across southeast Nebraska.
   No measurable snowfall was reported during the 6 hours ending at
1 p.m. EST. Heavier rainfall during the same period included 1.4
inches at Killeen, Texas.
   Winds gusted to near 40 mph at Junction, Texas, and the
temperature dropped 17 degrees in less than an hour as the cold
front moved through the area.
   In North Dakota, advisories were posted for a cold, windy
Halloween night. The cold north winds are expected to bring snow
showers, temperatures into the teens and wind chills to 20 below
zero over western and central portions of the state.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 22
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 88 at Corpus Christi
and Harlingen, Texas.
</TEXT>
