<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 2d Ld-Writethru, a0678,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Guerrillas Bomb Defense Ministry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cristiani says Nicaragua involved in attack, new info changes
to conform grafs 1-12. Pickup 10th graf: Two shells exploded...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels fired at least
16 shells from homemade mortars at the Defense Ministry Monday but
most exploded in nearby streets, killing a gas station attendant
and wounding 15 other people.
   President Alfredo Cristiani accused Nicaragua's Sandinistas of
either supplying the weapons or parts and technical skill for their
construction to the rebels.
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front (FMLN), an
umbrella organization of guerrilla groups, had announced in
February it was suspending the use of homemade mortars in populated
areas because their inaccuracy caused civilian casualties.
   Cristiani told a news conference the attack was ``an attempt by
the FMLN to give the impression it is strong.
   ``But they (the rebels) have only the capacity to stage
terrorist actions.''
   Col. Rene Emilio Ponce, head of the Joint Chiefs of Staff said
eight shells struck the grounds of the Armed Forces Social Club
adjacent to the ministry compound but no one was wounded there.
   Authorities said the other shells exploded in adjoining civilian
neighborhoods.
   Ponce reported 30 unfired shells were found on two trucks from
which the other shells had been launched. The trucks were in a
shopping mall about 300 yards from the military compound.
   The shells on one truck were covered with garlands of paper
flowers, the kind used in ceremonies marking the Day of the Dead
holiday on Nov. 2. Those on the other truck were covered with boxes
painted as speakers for a musical band.
   Ponce called the shelling ``indiscriminate terrorism,'' and also
accused Nicaragua's leftist government of providing the weapons for
the rebels.
   ``The FMLN lies when it talks about peace while at the same time
waging war,'' Ponce said, referring to recent efforts to negotiate
an end to the decade-old civil war.
   Representatives of Cristiani's rightist government and the FMLN
have met twice since September, but they are far apart on terms for
a cease-fire and have only agreed to continue the talks.
   Two shells exploded at a gasoline station about 800 yards away,
killing Ernesto Vasquez, 72, as he pumped gas. The blasts wounded
two attendants.
   ``I felt I was on a battlefield,'' said Francisco Morales, 27, a
mechanic, about 15 minutes after the attack.
   ``This is very bad,'' said Morales, who was shaken by the
deafening blasts and the carnage. ``They (the guerrillas) don't let
the humble people work, and we have to work.''
   The gas station was heavily damaged, but there was no fire.
   Another bomb fell at a nearby fried chicken restaurant, slightly
wounding a boy and causing extensive damage.
   Two mortar shells fell at the entrance to the military compound,
and three landed beyond the compound, on a sidewalk bordering a
parking lot next to the National Baseball Stadium. At least one
soldier and one civilian were wounded by those blasts, witnesses
said.
   Maj. Mauricio Chavez Caceres, chief of the armed forces press
committee, said no bombs fell inside the ministry compound.
   A soldier on duty at the gate said two bombs fell inside the
compound, but this could not be confirmed. Witnesses said they saw
one injured soldier being evacuated from the compound.
   The rebels staged a similar attack on Dec. 23, killing three
people and wounding 38. Only one of those casualties was a soldier.
   The rebels issued a communique Feb. 28 announcing they would
suspend such attacks because of ``faults and deficiencies'' that
were causing ``high risk to the civilian population, without us at
any time having intended to harm innocent civilians.''
   According to human rights organizations, most of the more than
70,000 people killed in El Salvador's civil war have been civilians.
</TEXT>
