<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 2029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-NukeTest     10-30 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuke Test,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ninth Nuclear Test of Year Set For Tuesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear weapon is scheduled to be detonated
Tuesday morning deep beneath the Nevada Test Site in a major test
that may be felt as far away Las Vegas, the Energy Department said
Monday.
   If weather conditions are favorable, the Energy Department plans
to set off the weapon at 7 a.m. PST.
   Scientists had planned to conduct the test Saturday, but it was
postponed because of winds blowing toward populated areas.
   The blast is to range from 20 to 150 kilotons, and may be felt
up to 105 miles away, according to DOE spokesman Jim Boyer. Las
Vegas is 105 miles southeast of the test site.
   Managers of high-rise buildings in the city were warned not to
have workers in precarious positions at the time of the detonation.
   The test will be the ninth of the year at the nation's nuclear
proving grounds, and the 696th announced blast since nuclear
testing began at the site in January 1951.
   The test is a weapons-related detonation to be conducted at the
bottom of a shaft 1,850 feet beneath the surface of Pahute Mesa.
Scientists from Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory are
conducting the test.
   It is the first test since Sept. 14, when a smaller nuclear
weapon was detonated at the site.
   The DOE does not specify the expected yield of each detonation,
classifying them as either under 20 kilotons or between 20 and 150
kilotons.
   Only tests in the upper limits that are expected to produce
ground motion away from the site are announced in advance.
</TEXT>
