<FIRST>u w AM-Rahall-Lebanon     10-30 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rahall-Lebanon,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Lebanon Trip Showed America Cares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Virginia Rep. Nick Rahall, who defied the
State Department by going to Beirut, said Monday he showed people
there America cares and gave a prominent Lebanese leader some
down-home political advice.
   Rahall and Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, who are of Lebanese descent,
returned Sunday from unsanctioned meetings with Christian leader
Gen. Michel Aoun, whose forces control east Beirut, and acting
Prime Minister Salim Hoss in Moslem west Beirut.
   Both U.S. lawmakers described the two meetings as friendly and
respectful.
   Conversations with Aoun, who's pivotal in determining whether
Lebanon ratifies a new peace plan, also were frank, Rahall said in
an interview.
   ``We advised him that he ought to cool his anti-American
rhetoric,'' said Rahall, who predicted Aoun would become ``I think
more toned-down.''
   Rahall, who's been in Congress for 13 years, said he also passed
along to the military leader this political advice: ``Bite your
tongue and just hope that the follies of your enemies will catch up
with them.''
   In response, ``He said, `I hear you,''' Rahall recounted.
   The two Democrats' private diplomatic mission was not approved
by the State Department, which blocked an August attempt by Oakar
and Rahall to go to Beirut.
   Rahall defended the trip, saying the legislators did not engage
in amateur diplomacy or hostage negotiation.
   ``We weren't there as administration spokesmen,'' he said.
``There's never any good time, according to the State Department,
to visit that country.''
   Rahall said he and Oakar accomplished their primary goal. ``I
think we showed that despite the withdrawal of our ambassador the
U.S. is still committed to achieving peace in Lebanon,'' he said.
``That had, I think a very positive impact on the Lebanese people.''
   In an interview Sunday night and again Monday at a news
conference in her Cleveland district, Oakar said the trip was
within her rights and duties as a congresswoman.
   Oakar and Rahall visited Lebanon in 1982 at the height of the
fighting between Israeli, Syrian and Lebanese troops to condemn the
Israeli invasion of Lebanon. Rahall returned a year later and said
he intends to go back.
</TEXT>
