<FIRST>r a AM-Devil'sNight     10-30 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Devil's Night,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>All Quiet on the Arson Front So Far, Detroit Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 169 youths on the first night of
a special curfew for a three-day campaign against Devil's Night
arson, a police spokesman said Monday.
   About 30,000 volunteers have pledged to help police patrol city
streets and ease the burden on firefighters, who in 1984 battled
808 fires during the three-day period before and including
Halloween.
   The number of fires has declined steadily every year since 1984.
Last year, there were 229 fires.
   Mayor Coleman A. Young's office refused to release the number of
arson fires until Wednesday, spokesman Robert Berg said Monday.
   Berg wouldn't say if any fires were set since Sunday night. But
he did say no arson-related arrests or fire-related injuries were
reported overnight.
   The special dusk-to-dawn curfew took effect at 6 p.m. Sunday and
ends at 6 a.m. Wednesday. The curfew allows police to arrest youths
17 and under who are not accompanied by an adult while outdoors.
   The 17-year-olds faced hearings Monday on the misdemeanor
charge, while those 16 and under were released either to the
custody of a parent or guardian or were held in the Wayne County
Youth Home, said police Sgt. Christopher Buck.
   Police arrested 302 curfew violators on the first night of the
1988 Devil's Night period, which was a Saturday. Buck said the
number declined this year because outdoor activity generally is
slower on a Sunday.
