<HEAD>Five Injured When Airplane Hits Turbulance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines 727 with 105 people
aboard made an emergency landing at Nashville International Airport
on Monday night after air turbulence injured five people, officials
said.
   The non-stop flight from San Juan, Puerto Rico, to Detroit
landed safely around 6:30 p.m., American spokesman Al Becker said
from the airline's Dallas headquarters.
   ``Apparently, it experienced turbulance about 90 miles north of
Nassau in the Bahamas, at about 31,000 feet,'' he said.
   Four of the five injuries were minor, Becker said. A flight
attendant was hospitalized for observation.
   The Boeing 727 was carrying 98 passengers and a seven-member
crew, Becker said.
   Althought there were no reports of damage to the plane, Becker
said inspectors would check the aircraft.
