<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Sentenced to 16 Life Terms For Bus Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Arab reporter's office searched,
more casualties. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-year-old Palestinian was sentenced Monday
to 16 life terms in prison for killing 16 people, including an
American and two Canadians, when he forced a crowded passenger bus
off the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem highway.
   The attack July 6 was the bloodiest in the 22-month-old
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and
the sentence imposed on Abdel Hadi Ghanem was one of the stiffest
in Israel's history.
   Also Monday, newspapers said the army will soon begin using
observation balloons equipped with cameras to keep track of
protests and disturbances related to the uprising.
   A Canadian TV correspondent was slightly wounded and a
14-year-old Palestinian boy was critically injured when soldiers
opened fire on stone throwers in a Gaza Strip refugee camp.
   Also in Gaza, soldiers searched the office of Arab journalist
Taher Sharita, said to do work for The New York Times and Reuters
news agency, and removed documents they deemed suspicious, military
officials said.
   They said the documents would be returned if found to be
non-inflammatory.
   A Palestinian refugee died Monday of a gunshot wound suffered
five days earlier in the Farah refugee camp in the West Bank, the
army said.
   He was identified as Hussein Mohammad Hassani, 24, and the army
said he was about to throw a cement block at soldiers when shot.
   Thirteen Palestinians were wounded in clashes with soldiers in
the occupied lands on Monday, including the boy shot in Gaza and
two Arabs shot in the Farah camp in protests that broke out after
Hassani's death was reported, Arab hospital officials said.
   Hassani's death raised to 607 the number of Palestinians killed
by Israelis in the Palestinian revolt, which began in December 1987.
   An additional 137 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs,
most as suspected collaborators with Israel. Forty Israelis have
died.
   Ghanem was sentenced to life in prison for each of the deaths in
the bus attack. He also received 20 years for each of the 24
passengers wounded in the attack.
   The sentences are to be served concurrently.
   Chief Prosecutor Uzi Hasson said there was no parole for murder
sentences and Ghanem could be freed only if the president
intervened on his behalf.
   The victims included the only American to be killed in the
uprising, lawyer Rita Levine, 39, of Philadelphia. Two victims were
Canadian tourists, Fern Rykiss, 17, of Winnepeg, and Shelley
Halpenny, 32, of Vancouver.
   Ghanem, who was injured in the incident, said he carried out the
attack to avenge a friend wounded by soldiers and paralyzed in a
clash near his home in the Gaza Strip's Nusseirat refugee camp.
   The attack prompted several days of revenge attacks by Jews on
Arabs in Jerusalem and other cities.
   The Canadian correspondent wounded in Shabura refugee camp in
Gaza was identified as Jean Francois Lepine of the Canadian
Broadcasting Corp. He was hit with a rubber bullet in the leg,
colleagues and the army command said.
   An army spokesman said an officer fired at the legs of
Palestinian rioters, hitting Lepine.
   ``The journalist was standing among the rioters ... and was not
identified by the officer before the shooting was carried out. He
was bandaged by troops and taken to a U.N. clinic,'' the spokesman
said.
   Lepine received stitches at a United Nations clinic and was
taken to a local hospital for X-rays ``as a precaution,'' said a
CBC producer who asked that his name not be used.
   Lepine was at least the third journalist wounded since the
uprising began.
   In the same incident, a Palestinian boy was hit in the head with
a plastic bullet fired by the troops, Arab reports said. Ashraf
Kishda was taken to Soroka Hospital in Israel, the reports said.
</TEXT>
