<SECOND>AM-Times Dealers,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Times Settles Case Brought By Home Delivery Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Times will pay about $3.6 million
over six years to settle lawsuits brought by independent
home-delivery dealers who wanted to block a delivery service
offered by the newspaper, the Times announced Monday.
   Under the settlement, the Times will continue to run its own
delivery service in exchange for the $3.6 million paid to the
dealers, along with other payments in the form of subsidies over
three years, the newspaper said in a statement.
   The dealers first sued in 1982 when the Times began its own
competing direct delivery service.
   Two antitrust lawsuits were dismissed in U.S. District Court,
and the decisions were affirmed by the U.S. Court of Appeals.
   The remaining lawsuits, including various contract claims, were
dismissed as part of Monday's settlement, the Times said.
