<SECOND>AM-NIreland-Trains,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs Warnings Cut Cross-Border Trains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three railway lines in Northern
Ireland were closed Monday night by bomb warnings, one day after
Protestants and Roman Catholics traveled together to defy IRA
disruption of cross-border trains.
   Anonymous telephoned warnings of bombs on the lines closed the
cross-border service between Newry in the north and Dundalk in the
Irish Republic. Separate warnings shut down services in the north
between Belfast and Bangor and Belfast and Larne.
   Police said they would not inspect the tracks until daylight
because they fered possible ambushes and booby traps.
   The closures meant disruption Tuesday morning for thousands of
Belfast-bound commuters.
   Hundreds of people traveled on ``peace trains'' last weekend to
protest bombings and bomb threats by the outlawed Irish Republican
Army, which has halted the cross-border route more than 60 times
this year in its fight to end British rule in Northern Ireland.
