<FIRST>u a AM-KansasExplosion     10-30 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kansas Explosion,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosions at Oil Company Damage 25 Mobile Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREAT BEND, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven explosions ripped through an
oil-field service company Monday, injuring two workers, damaging 25
mobile homes and forcing the evacuation of about 200 people,
authorities said.
   ``It was just like mortar rounds shot out in all directions,''
Police Chief Dean Akings said in this city of about 17,000 people
112 miles northwest of Wichita.
   The explosions and fire at Wire Tech Service Inc. on the eastern
edge of the city began at 7:50 a.m., and were caused by shaped
charges, which are explosives used in the oil industry, officials
said.
   A search for live charges and blasting caps was under way Monday
night.
   ``There was over 1,000 of those projectiles inside the
business,'' Akings said. ``They all went somewhere. We've had some
of those projectiles located up to three-quarters of a mile away.''
   The city police and fire departments, the U.S. Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and an Army bomb squad from Fort
Riley took part in the search. Residents were warned to call
authorities if they spotted any charges, which can be set off by
high heat or pressure.
   The first explosion was followed by six more blasts and a fire
at the company. Firefighters standing outside the building put the
blaze out within about 20 minutes, said Fire Chief Dick Meisinger.
   ``I wasn't going to send people in,'' Meisinger said, citing the
danger of another explosion.
   About 200 residents within a quarter-mile of Wire Tech Service
were evacuated, Akings said. Everyone except the residents of the
25 mobile homes damaged by the explosions had returned to their
homes by late Monday.
   The two workers injured were inside the building when the
explosions erupted.
   Brent Curtis, 27, suffered cuts and was in stable condition at
the Central Kansas Medical Center, said Nursing Supervisor Mary
Doherty. George Reed, 35, was treated and released.
   At least four or five vehicles parked in front of a machine shop
across the street from Wire Tech were heavily damaged, said Joyce
Lindholm, who works at the shop.
   Wire Tech provides service to established oil wells, and does
not manufacture explosives.
   Dorothy Juergensen, who lives near the plant, said she was
leaving her house when the first blast occurred.
   ``I was heading out the door when it hit. We waited for
everything to quit flying around,'' she said. ``... It shook
everything and everybody.''
</TEXT>
