<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Czechoslovakia     10-30 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Czechoslovakia,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian TV Broadcasts Czech Dissident Havel's Critical Comments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State TV showed extensive film on
Monday of police beating demonstrators with clubs in Prague and
broadcast an interview with top dissident Vaclav Havel raking
Czechoslovakia's hard-line communist leadership.
   ``Society is slowly waking'' in protest against repression,
banned playwright Havel told the Panorama public affairs show.
   His comments were part of a 20-minute segment dealing with
demonstrations on the 71st anniversary of Czechoslovak
independence. More than 10,000 people defied a police ban and
rallied for democracy in Prague last Saturday, despite hundreds of
arrests and beatings by riot police.
   Havel was interviewed in a hospital on Friday. He has been there
for treatment of a bronchial inflammation since shortly after his
arrest Thursday, two days before mass protests broke out.
   Alluding to promises of change in East Germany, forced by mass
demonstrations, and to reforms in Hungary and Poland, Havel said,
``The (Czechoslovak) authorities are very nervous and are acting
accordingly.''
   ``The present Czechoslovak leadership is increasingly isolated
at home as well as abroad.''
   Formal alliance in the Warsaw Pact has been unable to paper over
increasing tensions between Czechoslovakia, one of the most
orthodox Soviet bloc countries, and Hungary, which is rapidly
evolving into a multiparty democracy.
   Political differences were heightened by Hungary's decision to
unilaterally declare a moratorium on its part of a Danube River dam
and canal project with Czechoslovakia. It says completion of the
project would cause irreversible ecological havoc.
   Czechoslovakia plans to finish construction of its part and
demands compensation from Hungary if it pulls out permanently.
   In a separate Panorama interview, movie director Jiri Menzel,
best-known abroad for his Oscar-winning film ``Closely Watched
Trains,'' described Czechoslovakia as split between ``those who
rule ... and those who obediently ... accept everything that
happens.''
   Panorama also showed an interview made months ago with
Czechoslovakia's former communist party leader, Alexander Dubcek,
whose 1968 political reforms were crushed by a Warsaw Pact invasion.
   ``You can write in the constitution that the (communist) party
is the leading power, but that doesn't mean anything by itself,''
Dubcek asserted.
   Dubcek, who has compared his attempts at reform with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policies, urged the Czechoslovak
leadership to follow Moscow's example.
   Months before it disbanded and was replaced by the newly created
Socialist Party on Oct. 7, Hungary's communist party directly
criticized the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion _ the only Soviet bloc
communist party to do so.
   That move, along with a spate of newspaper articles and radio
and television programs siding with the 1968 reformers on occasion
of the Aug. 21 anniversary of the invasion, drew a formal
Czechoslovak protest.
   The National Federation of Hungarian Journalists on Monday
assailed the detention of a Hungarian reporter by Czechoslovak
police over the weekend and the ousting of other Hungarian
journalists trying to cover the Aug. 21 anniversary in Prague.
   In a statement carried by the official MTI news agency, the
federation urged Czechoslovak authorities to observe international
norms on human rights and on freedom of information. It also
scolded East Germany for recently expelling some Hungarian
reporters.
</TEXT>
