<FIRST>u a AM-PrisonHostages 2ndLd-Writethru a0701 10-30 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Hostages, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0701,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Inmate Holds Hostages for Five Hours</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with convict surrendering, hostages
released unharmed, prisoner a transfer from Washington state, demand for
airplane, other details. Picks up 6th graf, `Last summer...' Nic in 3rd
graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convict armed with a homemade knife held a
doctor and three workers hostage for five hours at a state prison
Monday, and surrendered after talking with the head of Illinois'
penal system, authorities said.
   The prisoner had demanded to see Corrections Department Director
Michael Lane, who flew to the maximum-security Stateville
Correctional Center from the state capital of Springfield.
   The doctor and three dental clinic workers were taken hostage
about 2 p.m. in the prison medical unit, said Corrections
Department spokesman Nic Howell. The hostages were released
unharmed about five hours later.
   The inmate, Mark A. LaRue, 35, had been transferred to Illinois
from Washington state in an exchange of troublemaking inmates, Lane
said. LaRue had asked for an airplane to return him to Washington,
Lane said.
   ``He's given me a letter that's articulated a number of things,
but principally, he doesn't want to be in Illinois,'' Lane said.
``I think that he does not want to be locked up.''
   Howell said Lane agreed to transfer the inmate to another prison.
   The prison was immediately placed on a lockdown status, with
inmates confined to their cells, Howell said.
   LaRue had an extensive record in Washington, including arrests
for burglary, assault and posession of a weapon by an inmate,
according to records in the Corrections Department.
   He had been serving a 10-year sentence for assault, said a
Washington Corrections Department spokeswoman. While in prison,
Larue was sentenced to three years for possession of a weapon and
then was sentenced to 20 years on two assault charges, she said.
   Lane said LaRue was transferred from the Washington state system
to federal prison because he was a troublemaker. He was in six
federal prisons before being sent to Illinois.
   Last summer, a guard was beaten to death at Stateville, which
has been plagued by overcrowding.
   The guard, Lawrence ``Frank'' Kush, 24, was one of about 30
workers at the prison who were on a hit list circulated within the
penitentiary earlier in the year, signed ``the Executioner.'' Kush
was known as an aggressive guard who led raids to confiscate drugs,
weapons and other contraband from convicts.
   In March, an inmate was stabbed to death at the prison.
   Stateville, built in 1920 to house 1,506 prisoners, had 2,070 as
of Friday, Howell said.
   Joliet is 30 miles southwest of Chicago.
</TEXT>
