<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 2245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BoeingPayment     10-30 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing Payment,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Military Airplanes to Pay $11 Million to the Federal Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Boeing Co.'s military aircraft
division signed an agreement Monday requiring the company to pay
the federal government $11 million in connection with allegations
of overcharges on Air Force contracts, officials said.
   The signing by Boeing Military Airplanes President Robert L.
Dryden was announced by the U.S. attorney's office in Wichita and
the Justice Department in Washington.
   Boeing has denied any wrongdoing in the case, characterizing the
dispute as a good-faith disagreement over pricing procedures. In
the settlement, the company did not acknowledge the validity of the
government's claims.
   However, a document reportedly presented to federal grand jurors
contained a Boeing official's calculations of how much money would
be generated by the overcharges.
   Under the settlement, Boeing must pay the $11 million within
five days. The agreement says Boeing won't face civil or criminal
prosecution in the case, except possible Internal Revenue Service
claims.
   ``We're certainly pleased that an amicable settlement could be
reached,'' said company spokesman Richhard L. Ziegler.
   Ziegler refused to discuss the company's potential IRS liability
in the case or how the alleged overcharges occurred.
   The case involved contracts for new aluminum skins, or outer
coverings, on KC-135 refueling tankers and transports from 1974 to
1986. Government investigators alleged that Boeing overcharged for
aluminum raw materials by quoting supplier catalog prices instead
of their actual costs, which were 12 percent to 13 percent less.
During Air Force contract negotiations, Boeing is required to
certify the raw materials prices it quotes are current, accurate
and complete.
   An investigation into the case began in 1985.
   A federal grand jury in Wichita, where the division is based,
heard hundreds of hours of testimony, and inspected thousands of
documents for more than nine months before the case was withdrawn
by prosecutors late last month.
   In addition to the other terms of the settlement, the agreement
prohibits Boeing from charging any of its costs or legal fees in
the settlement to government accounts or on future government
contrcats.
   The divison's parent company is based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
