<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 2246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RiotTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0700 10-30 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riot Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0700,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Prospects Questioned About Past Riots, Potential for More</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 6th graf, `I assumed...', to UPDATE with
session ending for day with five people excused. Picks up 7th graf, `Attorneys
for...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospective jurors in the trial of a Miami police
officer who shot a black motorcyclist to death were asked Monday
whether the threat of racial violence would influence their verdict.
   People were called into the courtroom one at a time from a jury
pool created last week and questioned closely by attorneys about
their knowledge of the Jan. 16 shooting that sparked three days of
rioting.
   The trial of Colombian-born William Lozano, 30, has raised
concern among local officials about another violent reaction in the
community, which has seen several racial eruptions this decade
after the slayings of blacks by police and the acquittals of police
officers after trials.
   Lozano is charged with two counts of manslaughter in the deaths
of Clement Anthony Lloyd, 23, who was shot in the head while being
chased by police, and Allan Blanchard, 24, who suffered fatal
injuries when the bike crashed.
   As the trial's second week began Monday, lead prosecutor John
Hogan estimated that seating a six-member jury and four alternates
would take at least two weeks. But Monday's relatively brisk pace
could mean a jury will be seated more quickly.
   ``I assumed we'd have a lot more trouble than this,'' Hogan said.
   When the session ended for the day, nine people were retained as
prospective jurors and five were excused. Among those excused were
three people who said they had formed strong opinions on the case.
Most of the people questioned said they knew very little about the
case.
   Attorneys for both sides questioned prospective jurors on the
past riots and asked if they could remain impartial despite the
threat of violence looming over this trial.
   A white woman in her 50s, who said she followed the case in
newspapers and on television, said she couldn't put aside her fears
of possible violence.
   ``It's frightening,'' she said. ``You're afraid that if you were
on the jury and brought in a verdict the black community didn't
want to hear, there'd be rioting.''
   She was dismissed.
   A black woman, who works as a bus-maintenance clerk, said she
had not formed an opinion about the Lozano case. Asked about past
riots, she said, ``I don't believe in violence. We all suffer from
it.''
   But she indicated that the threat of violence would not affect
her verdict if she were on the jury.
   ``Whatever happens, happens,'' she said.
   She was told to remain as the jury-selection process continued.
   The shooting, which occurred on the birthday of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. during the week leading up to the Super Bowl, left
one person dead and caused millions in property damage.
   The defense says Lozano shot in self-defense.
   His attorney, Roy Black, won the acquittal of then-Miami officer
Luis Alvarez in the 1982 shooting of a young black man at a video
arcade in Overtown, just blocks from where Lloyd and Blanchard were
killed.
   That slaying and the innocent verdict in 1984 triggered racial
violence, as did the acquittal of five Metro-Dade officers tried in
1980 in the beating death of a black motorcyclist after a chase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
