<FIRST>u a AM-Plane-Turbulence 2ndLd-Writethru a0744 10-30 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane-Turbulence, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0744,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Injured When Airplane Hits Turbulence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: EDITS throughout to CORRECT that plane did not make emergency
landing, as Nashville was scheduled stop, CORRECT to seven injured, sted
five, 107 were aboard, sted 105, UPDATE with all but one treated and released,
plane flying to Detroit. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NS3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines 727 with 107 people
aboard landed safely Monday night after air turbulence that injured
three passengers and four flight attendants, officials said.
   Flight 860 from San Juan, Puerto Rico, to Detroit, with a
scheduled stop in Nashville, landed safely at Nashville
International Airport around 6:30 p.m., p.m., American spokesman Al
Becker said from the airline's Dallas headquarters.
   ``Apparently, it experienced turbulence about 90 miles north of
Nassau in the Bahamas, at about 31,000 feet,'' Becker said.
   The pilot radioed ahead to reqest that paramedics be on hand in
Nashville. The Boeing 727 was carrying 100 passengers and a
seven-member crew, officials said.
   The three passengers and four flight attendants injured were
taken to a hospital for examination, said Metro Nashville Airport
Authority spokesman Stephan Foust.
   ``Three of them walked off the plane and four others were
carried off on stretchers,'' Foust said.
   All but one of the injured were treated at HCA-Donelson hospital
and released, said Nursing Administrator Cathy Parrish. The seventh
was still being examined late Monday.
   The injuries included sore backs, shoulder pain and hip pain,
Mrs. Parrish said.
   The plane was checked for damage, then continued on to Detroit,
only slightly behind schedule, Foust said.
</TEXT>
