<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 0820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-GermanHomeless Adv03   10-30 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-German Homeless, Adv 03,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, Nov. 3, or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Severe Housing Shortage Afflicts Wealthy West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOGNE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Affluent young executives flocking
to West German cities like this scenic Rhine River metropolis have
a problem in common with the poor immigrants crowding in from the
East.
   Hundreds of thousands of them can find no place to live.
   West Germany, one of the world's wealthiest nations, has been
plunged into a housing crisis by its own prosperity.
   Demographic and economic warps have coincided to flood the
market with homeseekers at a time when the supply of new public and
private housing is virtually nil due to a construction lag five
years ago.
   ``Our postwar baby boom came along a little later than in the
United States, and we are now seeing hordes of young people with
good educations and good incomes flooding the housing market,''
said Stefan Kampmann, director of the German Tenants Association,
which monitors rental conditions nationwide.
   ``They can afford better housing, and they want it, but it just
isn't there.''
   The housing shortage loomed long before a wave of East European
refugees hit this year, but that influx expected to reach 500,000
by year's end has greatly aggravated the problem.
   The nation is now short about 800,000 homes. A million other
households are in need of major renovation.
   Thousands of recent arrivals from East Germany, the Soviet Union
and Poland sleep on cots in converted concert halls or in makeshift
metal housing erected on sports fields.
   The hundreds of thousands of upmarket homeless usually crowd in
with relatives or friends during the hunt for housing, which can
take years.
   West Berlin, Munich, Hamburg and Frankfurt suffer the most acute
shortages, but officials concede the problem has reached crisis
proportions in virtually every city.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl has declared housing the No. 1 budget
priority for next year and has promised special funds for new
construction this year and a review of tax and rent-control laws.
   Paradoxically, hundreds of thousands of potential apartments are
kept off the market by landlords in West Germany because of tax
consequences or building restrictions that prevent conversion of
attics and lofts.
   Pressure from all income brackets is mounting, and tales of
apartment-hunting woes abound.
   Desperate homeseekers advertise any way they can. A man in West
Berlin painted an appeal on the back of his leather jacket. Many
put up notices on trees and light standards.
   ``Desperate, well-paid two-income couple with small child will
pay 800 marks ($420) for information leading to obtaining a
three-room or larger apartment,'' said one of hundreds of such
notices posted in the Suedstadt neighborhood in Bonn, the capital.
   ``Non-smoking medical student seeks any room for 1989-90 study
year,'' a Heidelberg man, Rainer Schimpf, has likewise announced.
   Heike Schneider, a 29-year-old journalist in Bonn, said the
apartment shortage allows landlords to pick and choose tenants to
the point of discrimination.
   ``Landlords won't rent to students and single people because
they think you're going to wreck the place,'' said Ms. Schneider,
who shares an apartment with two roommates.
   While West Germans have more money to invest as their economy
booms, housing construction is a long-term investment with lots of
risks.
   Crowded with industry and covered with a spider's web of
freeways from the North Sea to the Bavarian Alps, little open land
is available for new suburban housing.
   Environmental codes strictly limit construction in urban areas,
and building and labor costs have risen so sharply that rents
double the going rate would have to be charged to recover
construction costs.
   A rent-control law has kept prices relatively stable at the
equivalent of about $600 to $725 a month for a 1,000 square feet of
living space.
   About 60 percent of West German households are renters.
   The German Home, Apartment and Land Owners Association in
Duesseldorf contends the government will have to loosen regulations
to encourage owners to rent second homes and spare rooms.
   Its president, Theodor Paul, says 225,000 more dwellings could
be brought into the market if owners could see a profit in it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday PMs, Nov. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
