<DOCNO> AP891030-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 0835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Peru-Soviets Adv07   10-30 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru-Soviets, Adv 07,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday PMs, Nov 7 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>In Peruvian Port, Shopkeepers Speak Russian</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW SCOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALLAO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dirty, decayed, haunted by hoodlums,
prostitutes and drug addicts, this fogbound seaport is not much
different from any other Latin American port of call _ except here,
the shopkeepers speak Russian.
   More than 200 ships of the Soviet fishing fleet operating in the
Pacific off Peru use Callao as a resupply point under a contract
signed by the two countries in 1971.
   For the Soviet Union, Callao represents an important but
controversial foothold in a region where Soviet influence has been
limited.
   About 30,000 Soviet crewmen a year, on six-month stints, shuttle
in and out on Aeroflot flights to nearby Lima, Peru's capital.
   The sailors, the most visible sign of the Soviet presence in
Peru, have become prominent targets for leftist terrorists, however.
   On July 5, a terrorist bomb tossed beneath a tour bus wounded 20
sailors from the fleet on a shopping and sightseeing trip. Many of
the wounded were badly maimed and burned.
   Six Soviet fishermen also were wounded in 1986 when a bomb
hidden under a pile of sweaters went off in a clothing shop
frequented by the sailors in Callao.
   Police attributed the attacks to the Shining Path, a leftist
insurgent group fighting since 1980 to topple Peru's government and
install a workers' and peasants' state patterned on the ideas of
the late Chairman Mao Tse-tung of China.
   The group also has attacked the Aeroflot office in downtown Lima
and a Peru-Soviet cultural center.
   On Oct. 25 rebels in a passing car hurled dynamite at the Soviet
Embassy, damaging a diplomat's car but causing no injuries.
   It was the second attack on the embassy in three years. In 1986
the Maoist guerrillas assaulted it with explosives and submachine
guns. One rebel penetrated the embassy compound but was blown up
when a bomb exploded in his hands.
   The Shining Path views the current Soviet and Chinese
governments as traitors to true Marxism and regards the Soviets as
enemies because they have been a major supplier of arms to the
Peruvian armed forces for the past two decades.
   Just before the July 5 bus bombing, the government announced it
had purchased four Soviet helicopter gunships for its fight against
the insurgents.
   Close relations between Peru and the Soviet Union go back to the
late 1960s, when the leftist military dictatorship of Gen. Juan
Velasco realigned Peruvian foreign relations toward the East bloc.
   Velasco outfitted his army and air force with Soviet arms and
aircraft, and despite subsequent changes in government Peru remains
dependant on the Soviets for training and spare parts.
   Today the country is the third largest purchaser of Soviet
military hardware in the Western Hemisphere, after Cuba and
Nicaragua.
   ``They are inhibited from turning away from the Soviet influence
because of decisions made 20 years ago,'' said a Western diplomat.
``They're hooked onto the chain.''
   Although staggered by a huge budget deficit and a $17 billion
foreign debt, the government is planning to buy 14 more helicopters
for use by its counterinsurgency forces.
   The government uses the fishing contract to help pay its debts
with the Soviets, almost all of which is for arms purchases.
   The agreement allows Soviet trawlers to harvest 400,000 tons of
fish a year inside Peru's 200-mile territorial-water limit. Peru
takes 17.5 percent of the catch.
   Critics complain the Soviets take as much as $1.5 billion worth
of fish each year without paying taxes and accuse the government of
doing little to control the take.
   ``They can fish where, when and as much as they want,'' said
Sen. Felipe Osterling, who submitted a formal complaint to the
government in April charging the fishing contract was
unconstitutional.
   The left-leaning government of President Alan Garcia has not
responded to the complaint.
   But businesses in blighted Callao welcome the tall blond
fishermen.
   ``Sweaters _ the cheapest; blue jeans, imported watches, and
they carry away lots of brown leather jackets,'' said Angelica
Casana, owner of a store that sells Peruvian handicrafts. ``They
take special sizes because they are very big.''
   The terrorist threat, however, has caused business to drop off
in Callao as the sailors try to maintain a low profile, she added.
   ``It's affected them, the fear,'' she said.
   ``They don't come like they used to, and some shops have closed
up and left.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tuesday PMs Nov. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
