<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1527EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-RememberChina? Adv05-2Takes   10-30 0901</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Remember China?, Adv 05-2 Takes,0934</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Nov. 5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>What Happened to the Outrage Over China?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HIRSH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Events in China, which roused the world to a
frenzy of outrage in June, seem more recently to have lulled it to
sleep.
   What was once high drama on television has dwindled to a daily
grind of repression and arrests since the bold ``democracy
movement'' in Beijing's Tiananmen Square was snuffed out in blood.
   But what happened to the horror that swept the world in June?
Where are the tens of thousands of expatriate Chinese students and
sympathizers who joined in strident protest? And beyond the mild
sanctions announced months ago, where are the threatened boycotts,
the embargoes?
   On Oct. 1, only about 3,500 people joined fugitives from the
Chinese democracy movement for a demonstration in Washington to
counter the regime's 40th anniversary celebration. Organizers had
hoped to draw nearly 10 times that many.
   Other disturbances of global impact _ such as the 1979 Soviet
invasion of Afghanistan or the '76 Soweto massacre in South Africa
_ provoked lasting reaction from the West, either by arousing Cold
War passions or prompting endless demonstrations on college
campuses.
   Yet the world seems to do little more than frown at China while
its hard-line Communist government zealously smothers human rights.
   ``All the great intentions about making China realize the cost
of oppression have faded,'' said Sidney Jones, executive director
of Asia Watch, a human rights committee in New York.
   ``The Western European governments, the U.S. and Japan ... none
has said China has to lift martial law in Beijing before we'll lift
the freeze on World Bank loans. No one has said anyone involved in
the violence must resign before we resume high level contacts.''
   China watchers point to several reasons for the muted response:
   _Foreign governments do not want to disturb China's tentative
orientation toward the West, so carefully nurtured since the Nixon
years.
   _The Cold War has faded, and with it fears of communist excesses.
   _China activists suffered a sharp emotional letdown after seeing
their hopes crushed so abruptly; they recognize, bleakly, the
current regime is just continuing that country's age-old habit of
dictatorial repression.
   _The number of Americans and other Westerners involved with
China, whether economically or politically, is still small. Only
since U.S. diplomatic relations were resumed in 1979 have firm ties
been established after years of alienation.
   But the simplest reason may be out of sight, out of mind. With
dozens of arrests and at least 12 executions over the summer, the
Chinese government apparently has succeeded in extinguishing the
democracy movement _ or at least driving it underground.
   ``There's no one to carry the torch,'' said Jonathan D. Spence,
a China scholar at Yale University. ``If there was some kind of
opposition in China like the unions or the church in Eastern
Europe, they could carry the story.''
   Foreign news media, getting scant information from frightened
Chinese sources, have largely dropped China to the back pages. In
its place are more exciting _ and visible _ developments in Eastern
Europe and Latin America.
   ``The Chinese government has really done a very good job of
managing the story,'' said Barry Naughton, a China expert at the
School of International Relations and Pacific Studies at the
University of California, San Diego.
   ``In particular they have carefully avoided any sensational
event that could be a rallying cry. There is an ambiguity about it.
   ``They have begun to carry out a policy of systematic limitation
on intellectual freedom. That's a major story but they do it in a
way that is incremental. They're nickle and diming it.''
   That strategy suffered a minor setback Oct. 5 when the 1989
Nobel Peace Prize was awarded to the Dalai Lama, the exiled leader
of Tibet, for his non-violent struggle to free his country from
China's occupation. It was a glancing commentary on Tiananmen
Square.
   But there may be deeper reasons why the emotions stirred by the
deaths of hundreds, perhaps thousands of Chinese on June 3-4 now
seem stilled.
   In some ways, the times are not ripe for outrage. The Cold War
has ebbed; some say ended. With it has gone the fear of communism
that aroused the right-wing ``China Lobby'' of the 1950s and
lingered long enough to prompt President Carter's grain embargo and
boycott of the 1980 Moscow Olympics.
   Instead, today's news is filled with smiling Soviet leaders and
widening gaps in the Iron Curtain. A poll published by Business
Week magazine in August found that, by a 3-to-1 margin, Americans
are more concerned by the economic threat from Japan than the
military threat from the Soviet Union.
   Economics, indeed, seems to be replacing ideology as the driving
force behind East-West relations, blurring distinctions. President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev of the Soviet Union has staked his future on
it. So apparently have China's leaders, despite the lurch back into
totalitarianism.
   ``The burden of China relations has to some extent fallen on
businessmen, who are not exactly altruists,'' commented Robert F.
Dernberger, a China specialist at the University of Michigan.
   For the record, Chinese Communist Party leader Jiang Zemin
opened celebrations marking the regime's 40th anniversary with a
blast of Cold War rhetoric. He condemned the West's ``rotten
lifestyles'' and predicted the triumph of socialism over capitalism.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
