<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--SeniorHackers Adv02   10-30 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Senior Hackers, Adv 02,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Nov. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nursing Home Residents Use Computers To Correspond With Pen Pals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF MEYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALLEY CITY, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Susanne Barstad didn't know a modem
from a disk drive, but she and other residents of Sheyenne Care
Center have learned that computers can be as easy to use as a horse
and buggy.
   ``I figured you're never too old to learn if you want to try,''
the cheery 90-year-old said. ``I've always had a curiosity about
trying new things.''
   Barstad is among 19 residents of the nursing home who use a
computer to write to pen pals around the country through a network
called SeniorNet.
   The nonprofit organization has trained more than 3,500 people on
personal computers at 30 sites in 13 states and Canada since 1986.
Sites include doctors offices, senior centers and colleges, but
Sheyenne Care Center is the only nursing home, said Cindy Schwehr,
the center's SeniorNet coordinator.
   Schwehr believes the program keeps the residents' minds alert
and helps ward off institutional depression. ``I think it boosts
their self-esteem, their confidence. And it's an easy way for them
to establish friendships with people in other parts of the
country.''
   While some of the residents balked at using the computer,
Barstad jumped at the chance. ``I knew computers are going to be
the wave of the future. ... I was happy when they asked me to come
down and try it.''
   Barstad, a retired nurse, corresponds with three other seniors,
including an author in Florida and a former journalist in Virginia.
   Barb Svenningsen, a volunteer who helps the residents operate
the computer, said some still hesitate to use it. ``Their first
question is, `How much is it going to cost?' But those that get on
it and realize they can do it _ they really seem to like it.''
   SeniorNet evolved from a computer class and user manual,
``Computers for Kids over 60,'' by Mary Furlong, an associate
professor of education at the University of San Francisco and now
executive director of SeniorNet.
   Furlong started it because she felt senior citizens had been
left out of the computer revolution of the '80s. ``What I've
learned in the past six years is that older adults have a great
deal of wisdom to share. If we give them access to these tools ...
we as a society stand to learn a great deal.''
   Recognizing a relatively untapped market for computers and
information services, industry has been eager to help SeniorNet get
off the ground.
   Apple Computer Corp. donated $200,000 worth of computers to
equip 11 training sites including Sheyenne Care Center, which
received a keyboard, disk drive, monitor and printer.
   Users are billed only for the time something is sent over
transmission lines, Furlong said. That averages about three or four
hours a month at $12.60 an hour for most users.
   Sheyenne Care Center's bills are paid for by the Markle
Foundation of New York, which has donated $700,000 to SeniorNet.
The center joined after former administrator Jim Tourville heard
about it at a national conference.
   Tourville and former marketing director Tim Hager contacted
Furlong, and in 1987 the nursing home was selected to join eight
other sites in the country.
   ``We had absolutely nothing to lose by doing this _ because
everything was donated _ and hundreds of things to gain,'' Schwehr
said.
   ``This has given them a link with some of their younger family
members because the children are learning about computers in
school,'' she said. ``It gives them something to talk about, and
that can mean so much to an elderly person.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 1151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Nepal-Jesuit Adv02   10-30 0825</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Nepal-Jesuit, Adv 02,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Nov. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Solitary Voice from the Himalayas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BINAYA GURUACHARYA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GODAVARI, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Marshall D. Moran has talked
with Mahatma Ghandi and drove India's first prime minister,
Jawaharlal Nehru, around in a jeep. But to most of those who know
him, he's simply ``Mickey Mouse.''
   ``I want to continue as long as I find people wanting to talk to
me,'' said the 83-year-old Chicago-born Jesuit, ham license 9N1MM,
the only private radio operator in this tiny Himalayan kingdom
sandwiched between China and India.
   Since he started out on the radio he built himself, Moran
estimates he's talked to more than 80,000 ham operators. ``I used
to talk to captains of ships at sea. They used to respond saying,
`Your signal is not good.'''
   In 1961, the Maritime Radio Club of Houston sent him the radio
he's used since.
   Moran learned to make receivers from a friend in school. ``When
I was 13, I used to sell them to my friends. The parts would cost
me $90 ... I would sell it for $100. In those days $10 was good
money.''
   Those were also the days when broadcasting was young and no one
had heard of television. ``I saw the development of radio and
television from the very beginning. I was lucky to see the
beginning.''
   Moran set sail from the United States in 1929, in search of a
new homeland in Asia. He settled first in India, and became
principal of St. Xavier's School in Patna in the eastern Indian
province of Bihar.
   It was there, in 1939, ``while I was in the middle of putting a
high school in Patna, I met Gandhi _ the great man... After a half
hour talk with him I agreed to work for him,'' Moran recalls.
   ``In 1946, just before the end of the Second World War, I was
going to shillong to give a retreat lecture before Christmas,'' he
said, and Jawaharlal Nehru, who a year later would become prime
minister, was on the train.
   ``Nehru was then president of the Congress (Party). Large crowds
would come to see and hear him when the train stopped at railway
stations, and when his microphone did not work his voice stopped
and I went up to the speakers and connected the wires,'' Moran
said. ``Nehru asked me, `What is the name of your company which
takes so good care of loudspeakers?'
   ``I said, `I am sorry I am a Jesuit priest and an American
missionary.'''
   Moran met Nehru again in 1947 and drove him around Bihar in his
jeep during Hindu-Muslim rioting before the partition of India.
   Two years later, as principal of St. Xavier's in Patna, Moran
made his first trip to Nepal, to conduct examinations for Patna
University. He moved to the mountain kingdom in 1951 so settle,
intent on starting a boarding school.
   At the time, there was no airport, so he took a train to Raxaul,
the last Indian township on the border, and made his way to
Bhimphedi at the base of the Himalayan foothills. ``There were
eight porters waiting for me with an ulinkath (an open palanquin).
Four of them carried me on it and four others followed, running
behind them, changing turns every 10 minutes,'' he said.
   ``This was the only means of transportation system in those days
to enter into the Nepalese capital. ... I saw even cars being
carried by men on their shoulder along the trail. At Bhimphedi,
people took off the wheels of a car and they put the car on top of
two long logs with nine planks strapped sideways and 36 people in
rows of four men carried it on the trail to Thankot.''
   When Moran brought his own car into Nepal that in 1951, however,
he did it by air. Even so, he said, it was a Herculean effort.
   ``The door of the DC-3 was so narrow that I had to take off the
back and front bumpers first. The car was pushed into the plane
with barely an inch to spare to fit it in.'' Some of the plane's
hinges had to be removed, and ``When I asked the pilot for his
permission he said, `I can't give permission to do so but if I go
and take a cup of tea, I might not see it. Hurry up.'''
   That year, Moran met Nehru a third time. The prime minister was
visiting as a state guest, ``saw me at a civic reception standing
among the huge crowd and told King Tribhuvan, pointing at me, `This
is my most favourite driver.'''
   It was also the year that Moran established St. Xavier's, in an
old maharaja's summer palace 5,000 feet up in the Himalayan
foothills, where he still teaches five days a week _ when he
doesn't have his ``ears on.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 2</NOTE>
