<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Gardening Adv02   10-30 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Gardening, Adv 02,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Nov. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Getting Pleasure out of Intrigue</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   James Walters worked for the AP as a reporter
and editor from 1947 until he retired in 1984.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JAMES E. WALTERS</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 40 years, when Bill Warriner saw a rose he
ticked off its development possibilities. Now he grows them mainly
for pleasure. In fact, Pleasure, his 1990 All-American, is the best
in mass plantings.
   ``One of the main reasons people don't grow roses is they don't
want to take care of them, so if you remove that reason you get
more customers,'' said Warriner, 67, who retired from Jackson &amp;
Perkins Co. ``I do think it's a shame more people, especially
retirees, don't enjoy the pleasure of gardening.''
   There are about 60 rose bushes growing in the 90-by-90-foot
landscape of his home in Tustin, Calif., a Los Angeles suburb where
he's lived the past 20 years. There's also a small vegetable garden
and a couple each of avocado, orange, lemon, lime and persimmon
trees. It's all pretty low-key.
   Of his roses, Warriner says, ``Now I just like to look at them,
smell them, enjoy them. What I'm looking for is beauty in the
landscape.''
   Pink-blooming Pleasure was propagated before his 1987 retirement
as vice president of research at Jackson &amp; Perkins, the
rose-selling giant. So were his 1989 All-Americans _ Tournament of
Roses and Class Act. It can be eight years from propagation to
possible designation by All-America Selection Inc., a non-profit
organization of most U.S. rose producers, so there may be more
Warriner winners. He has 15, more than anyone in the 50-year-old
competition.
   Announcements aren't made for two years after the selection to
give growers time to produce plants for sale. Pleasure will be
available this spring.
   I planted two test plants in March. The desert climate is a
severe test but Pleasure, a floribunda, produced numerous flowers
and good foliage. Compared to others, however, the flowers dropped
their petals quickly after being cut.
   ``Sometimes a rose that holds too long makes a poor landscape
subject because the flowers dry and stay on the bush,'' said
Warriner.
   Warriner, who grew up in Michigan, has never been sure why he's
always had a keen interest in flowers. He went to Michigan State
University because of its horticuture reputation. He also made the
boxing team as a middleweight, ``which probably cut off a lot of
joking about my love of flowers.'' He still can make the weight,
``although the pounds are distributed a lot differently.''
   As a hybridizer, he patented about 110 rose varieties. Jackson &amp;
Perkins estimates 41 million of his roses have been sold. Besides
the 1989 and 1990 All-Americans, they include such standbys as
Simplicity, Cherish, Love, Honor, Intrigue, Impatient, Sun Flare,
Medallion, French Lace and Color Magic.
   Warriner never developed a personal favorite and says it's a
thrill to see any of his growing somewhere ``because it means you
did something right.
   ``I look on each variety in a different way. The variety that
more people have grown than anything else is Simplicity. But it's
certainly not the most beautiful variety I've created. And so it's
hard to say what the favorite is. It would change every year,
depending on my goals in hybridizing at the time.''
   The most difficult part of hybridizing, he feels, is deciding
which roses to use for the crosses. One parent of Pleasure is
Intrigue, but Warriner said he never used it in hybridizing because
``it doesn't really bloom enough to be a good parent, although it's
a very clean plant and fragrant.''
   But when he saw a certain seedling he recalled Intrigue's strong
points and thought the combination had possibilities. He doesn't
recall now what it was that grabbed his attention. ``We rarely had
less than 150,000 seedlings.
   ``You go through them in the spring and summer on almost a daily
basis and pick out those that look like they might have potential,
and discard those with none. The first year we'd select perhaps
1,000 seedling varieties for further propagation. The next year
more would be eliminated. After going through the procedure about
three times, what's left are just a few varieties.''
   How possible is it that the ``perfect rose'' is growing
somewhere, but the owner doesn't realize it and no one else sees it?
   ``I certainly wouldn't go looking for it. Roses have to be
developed. I don't see how the natural process can produce a
winning specimen.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 2</NOTE>
