<HEAD>For release Thursday, Nov. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Consumer Information on Audiocassette for Visually Impaired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two dozen publications on consumer
issues now are available on audiocassette from regional libraries
for the blind.
   The cassettes are being made available without charge by the
American Association for Retired Persons and American Foundation
for the Blind.
   More than half the foundation's 170 regional and sub-regional
libraries are circulating tapes of AARP's most requested
publications, covering subjects such as medical care, consumer
issues, financial matters, health and nutrition and long-term care.
The project is designed to improve access to information for the
nearly 2 million older Americans with visual impairments, AARP said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's nursing homes need new ways to watch
over ``wanderers,'' the thousands of patients _ especially
Alzheimer's victims _ who are prone to walking around, says a
researcher seeking a high-tech solution.
   In three months of study at an Atlanta nursing home, David
Martino-Saltzman identified two patterns _ ``meandering,'' in which
patients wander aimlessly, and ``circuiting,'' in which they walk
laps around a defined area.
   The challenge for researchers is to find a way for nursing homes
to deal with the problem without physical restraints or drugs, said
Martino-Saltzman, a behavior specialist at the Veterans
Administration Medical Center here.
   His study involved pressure-sensitive floor mats that would
detect electronic tags worn by patients. The computerized system
allowed the patients to wander, but alerted workers when the
patients were where they shouldn't be.
   Such systems can be prohibitively expensive for small nursing
homes, he said. ``Small nursing homes can't afford a $100,000
system. It behooves us to come up with something that's
affordable.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 2</NOTE>
