<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Television-Casting Adv02   10-30 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Television-Casting, Adv 02,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, Nov. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Work Never Better For the Older Actor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-PRI--Television</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For proof that the tube is booming for older
actors, look no further than this year's Emmy Awards.
   Richard Mulligan, 56, won best actor in a comedy series, and
Carroll O'Connor, 65, won in a drama series. Other nominees
included Colleen Dewhurst, 63; Doris Roberts, 59; Eileen Brennan
and Diahann Carroll, both 54; all four ``Golden Girls''; Angela
Lansbury, 64; and Richard Dysart, 60ish.
   ``I think that's indicative of the effect older actors are
having on television,'' said Peter Golden, GTG Entertainment's vice
president for talent.
   ``We're finding that these days it seems to be hip to be
older,'' Golden said. ``The pilot movie for our series `Baywatch,'
which features mostly young actors, had a lifeguard in his 60s. He
died in the movie but tested so well we're going to add an older
lifeguard to the series.
   ``We're developing a comedy series that focuses on a man in his
70s.''
   Deborah Barylski, an independent talent agent who has cast many
comedy series, is placing more older performers than ever before.
``The scripts I'm getting are paying a lot more attention to that
kind of character.
   ``When I cast `Frank's Place' we used so many elderly people
that I really had to do a lot of digging to find new actors in that
age range.''
   NBC's ``The Golden Girls,'' starring Bea Arthur, 63; Betty
White, 67; Estelle Getty, 66; and Rue McClanahan, 53, set the stage
for shows focusing on older characters. Others include CBS'
``Murder, She Wrote'' (Lansbury) and ``Newhart'' (Bob Newhart, 60);
and NBC's ``In the Heat of the Night,'' (O'Connor) and ``Mancuso,
FBI'' (Robert Loggia, 59).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
