<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     10-30 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0879</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three major Wall Street firms capitulated to an
investor outcry, abandoning or curtailing a computerized trading
strategy widely blamed for turmoil in the stock market.
   In addition, an insurance company that manages more than $8.6
billion in assets stopped doing business Friday with brokerages
that conduct program trading and the New York Stock Exchange said
it would contact members about possible reforms.
   Morgan Stanley Group Inc. and Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., two of the
biggest users of program trading, said they would stop using a form
of the strategy known as index arbitrage to trade for their own
accounts. PaineWebber Group Inc. ended use of all forms of the
strategy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income, dealt a blow by
Hurricane Hugo, rose a lackluster 0.3 percent in September as
consumer spending posted its weakest advance in a year, the
government said.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that personal income in
September rose $12.8 billion at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
to $4.47 trillion, the smallest increase in four months.
   Spending increased 0.2 percent, the most anemic gain in 12
months, to an annual rate of $3.53 trillion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal budget deficit totaled $152.1
billion in fiscal 1989, marking the third year of essentially
unchanged fiscal red ink, the government said.
   For the first time, interest on the $2.8 trillion national debt
exceeded Social Security spending, pushing the interest category
into second place, behind military expenditures.
   The budget gap for the year ending Sept. 30 marked a $3.1
billion, or 2 percent, improvement over the $155.2 billion deficit
in 1988, the Treasury Department and the Office of Management and
Budget said Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's financial markets were buffeted by the
political storm over the abrupt resignation of Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's treasury secretary.
   The markets were jolted Friday by uncertainty over the
government's exchange-rate policy and were highly nervous that a
resulting steep decline in the British pound would prompt the
government to push up interest rates above their 8-year high of 15
percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LIN Broadcasting Corp. and BellSouth Corp. have
agreed on a revised plan to merge their cellular telephone
interests in a deal that would create the nation's largest cellular
operation.
   The deal announced Friday, which will be presented to LIN
shareholders for a vote in December or January, could prompt
revision of a pending buyout bid for LIN from McCaw Cellular
Communications Inc., the current leader in the cellular field.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. is selling its Baby Ruth,
Butterfinger and Pearson candy businesses to Nestle Foods Corp. for
$370 million.
   The sale, announced Friday, leaves RJR Nabisco about $230
million from its goal of $5.5 billion in asset sales for raising
cash to reduce the company's debt load following its $24.53 billion
leveraged buyout by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   The deal with Nestle, a division of Switzerland's giant Nestle
SA, includes a manufacturing plant in Franklin Park, Ill.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joyful Costa Rican President Oscar
Arias thanked President Bush for the U.S. role in restructuring
Costa Rica's foreign debt in ways expected to save his country $100
million a year.
   Arias announced the debt restructuring Friday at an airport
welcoming ceremony for Bush, who arrived for a meeting with
hemispheric leaders.
   Arias said the agreement would reduce Costa Rica's $4.5 billion
foreign debt by $1 billion. The annual cost of paying interest on
the debt will be reduced from $150 million to $50 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manufacturer of an inhaler for asthmatics
is recalling the medication after just one month on the market
because of reports of coughing, choking and gagging after use, the
Food and Drug Administration said.
   The drug is a new formula of a commonly prescribed metered dose
inhaler _ alupent.
   The FDA said Friday the medication is being removed from the
U.S. market because there has been a sharp increase in reports of
adverse reactions with the reformulation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. has resigned from the National
Wildlife Federation's corporate advisory board, calling the
conservation group unfair in its criticism of the Alaska oil spill.
The unrepentant federation responded by calling Exxon ``a corporate
pariah.''
   The federation, with 5.8 million members nationwide, accused
Exxon on Friday of repeatedly ignoring requests to meet and discuss
the spill from the tanker Exxon Valdez.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market capped off a week-long run of losses with
another broad decline amid worries over weakness in corporate
earnings. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 17.01 to 2,596.72
Friday, extending its loss for the week to 92.42 points.
   The dollar weakened substantially against all major currencies
except the British pound.
   Bond prices sagged.
   Gold futures prices surged to their highest levels in 3{ months;
silver and platinum futures rose sharply; copper advanced; oil
prices rose; livestock and meat were mostly lower; and grains and
soybeans were mixed.
</TEXT>
