<FIRST>r f PM-ChannelOne     10-30 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Channel One,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Signs 500 Schools for Channel One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 schools with nearly 345,000 students
have signed up for the launch of the advertiser-supported Channel
One daily news show for the classroom set to debut this spring, the
project sponsor said.
   Whittle Communications, a Knoxville, Tenn.-based media company,
said Sunday the subscriptions during the first eight weeks of
active recruitment of schools puts the project halfway toward its
goal of having 1,000 schools equipped to receive the show at launch
in March 1990.
   It now expects to have 1,000 schools signed up by the end of
this year.
   The Channel One project has come under fierce attack by national
educational groups, state officials in California and New York and
others who object to giving advertisers a platform for pitching
products to students in the classroom.
   Channel One plans to send a 12-minute news show geared toward
students to participating schools every weekday. Each show will
contain two minutes of paid advertising. In exchange for the
running the show, schools get about $50,000 each in television
monitors, videocassette recorders and satellite dishes.
   Christopher Whittle, chairman of Whittle Communications, said
his salesmen have approached about 1,290 school districts
representing 3,855 schools in 24 states so far. He said 10 percent
of the districts have rejected the offer, schools in 238 districts
have signed up and talks continue in the rest.
   He said he expects to have no trouble meeting the longer-term
goal of having 7,000 to 8,000 schools participating in the program
by the end of 1990.
   ``This documents what we thought: that local educators would
view this very differently than national ones,'' he said. ``Some
critics are going to be very surprised.''
   Installation of equipment is expected to begin in January.
   Whittle has previously said it had signed contracts with
advertisers who have bought 56 percent of the available commercial
time on Channel One for the first year of programming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 0742EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Bounced-CheckFees     10-30 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bounced-Check Fees,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Average Cost of Bouncing Checks Going Up, Newsletter Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average fee banks charge for
bouncing a check has increased in the past two years, and it varies
widely from city to city, according to a survey by an industry
newsletter.
   Today's edition of Bank Rate Monitor says the average fee for
writing a check on insufficient funds in a checking account was
$16.13 on Oct. 25. That's up from $15.30 in April 1987, when it
last did the survey.
   The highest fees were found in Philadelphia, where some banks
charge as much as $30 for a bounced check, while the lowest were
reported in New York, where some charge customers less than $10,
according to the Palm Beach-based newsletter's survey of 110
institutions in major markets.
   The publication said it found much the same variance in 1987.
   Cynthia McGeever, a vice president of Atlantic Financial Federal
in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., gave competition as the reason
Philadelphia-area banks charge more. Atlantic Financial raised its
fee from from $25 to $30 on Oct. 1.
   ``We perceived the whole market was moving upward,'' she told
the newsletter. ``People who had been at $20 were going to $25.
People at $25 were going to $30. I think it was a competitively
driven decision.''
   But she thought $30 would be the upper limit, at least for
awhile.
   ``You may see some people below $30 coming up to $30, but I
don't think you'll see a lot who will go higher than that.''
   The newsletter also reported that the number of banks and
thrifts charging more than $15 per bounced check increased to 44
from 34.
   David Allen, a vice president of First City Texas in Dallas,
which raised its bounced-check fee from $17.50 to $20 last year,
said banks need to consider the fact that bouncing a check is
against the law, not just what it costs to reprocess the check.
   ``If you write checks in excess of the amount in the account,
you are attempting to get an interest-free loan from the bank,'' he
told the publication.
   He suggested customers have an account with overdraft
protection, perhaps covered by a credit card.
   Bank Rate Monitor tracks average interest rates, fees and
charges by major banks, thrifts and credit unions nationwide on a
weekly basis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 0742EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CNWBonds     10-30 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CNW Bonds,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Junk Bond Woes Prompt Rail Company To Change Financing For Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A skittish junk bond market forced buyers of CNW
Corp. to make significant last-minute changes in the financing of
their $1.6 billion buyout of the railroad company, officials
involved in the plan said.
   The group planned to issue $475 million in high-yield, or junk,
bonds as the final financing of the leveraged buyout to take the
company private. But in a two-week trip to nearly two dozen cities,
officials of Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp., the
underwriters of the bond offering, discovered buyer resistance.
   The buyout group consists of DLJ, railroad company Union Pacific
Corp., CNW and Blackstone Capital Partners L.P. of New York.
   Chicago-based CNW is the parent of Chicago and North Western
Transportation Co., a 6,000-mile railroad with 8,500 employees that
operates in nine states, most of them in the Midwest.
   Garrett Moran, head of DLJ's high-yield securities operations,
said Friday that potential buyers of the railroad company's
securities indicated they wanted equity as well as better terms for
the junk bonds.
   ``It's a skittish market,'' Moran said.
   The result is that CNW's buyers will make a public equity
offering amounting to 10 percent of the ownership.
   Blackstone, which holds 72 percent of the stock, and DLJ, which
took 22 percent, each will give up a portion of their holdings on a
pro-rata basis for the initial public offering. The remaining 6
percent is held by management, led by Chairman Robert Schmiege.
   In five years, Union Pacific is expected to convert $100 million
in preferred shares into 25 percent ownership.
   The buyers also agreed to raise the yield on the junk bonds by
one quarter of 1 percent to 14.75 percent. CNW spokesman James
Foote said DLJ estimates the added interest will amount to $2
million a year.
   In addition, the buyers have agreed to reset the interest rate
12 months from now to a level that will allow the bonds to trade at
101 percent of face value. That lowers the risk for buyers who are
leery of the value of junk bonds in the current market.
   Trouble in the junk bond market erupted last month when Canadian
retail company Campeau Corp. said it would have trouble making
payments on its high-yield debt. Since then, other junk bond issues
have plunged in price.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 0743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-IATA-Airlines     10-30 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IATA-Airlines,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congestion Problems Grow With Record Number of Passengers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airlines carried a record number of
passengers last year, boosting worldwide profits to $1.6 billion,
the International Air Transport Association said in a report for
release today.
   IATA's annual report, released on the eve of its general
assembly in the Polish capital, predicted another bumper year in
1989, but warned that air congestion would limit future expansion,
especially in Europe.
   In a bid to improve security and safety measures, IATA said it
planned to step up checks on airport security and review the
problem of human error in air crashes.
   Air congestion and security are expected to be the main themes
at IATA's annual meeting.
   The report said IATA's 187 member airlines carried 632 million
passengers last year, a 2 percent rise over the record set in 1987.
Of these, 190 million flew on international scheduled flights, more
than 6 percent more than in 1987.
   A further 22 million people flew on domestic and international
charter flights.
   It predicted international scheduled passenger traffic would
grow 8 percent in 1989 and 1990, although it should drop back to
about 7 percent in the following three years.
   The report said the most rapid expansion should be in Asia and
the Pacific. Air traffic in Europe and North America is expected to
grow at a rate of about 6 percent a year.
   Insufficient airport capacity could limit growth in Europe,
where congestion problems are most acute, it said.
   ``The lack of adequate airport and air space capacity to meet
current and future demand continues to be the major problem facing
the air transport industry today,'' the report commented.
   IATA has identified 35 airports in West Europe as ``congested,''
and has said that Sydney, Bombay, Hong Kong and the Japanese cities
of Tokyo and Osaka also are suffering from lack of airport space.
   The report said that the bomb explosion aboard Pan Am Flight 103
over Lockerbie, Scotland, showed flaws in the implementation of
security measures.
   It said that IATA planned to increase the number and frequency
of airport surveys around the world under its Intensified Aviation
Security Program.
   There were 20 plane crashes in 1988, five more than the previous
year. Human error was the main cause of 16 of the crashes. The
statistics did not list losses caused by terrorism or sabotage.
IATA is to hold a conference within the next two years to overhaul
the industry's approach to the problem of the ``human factor,'' it
said.
   It said recent accidents have led to growing concern about the
structural safety of older aircraft. But excess demand for new
planes was forcing many airlines to modify rather than replace
older aircraft. This would add to costs and impose yet another
constraint on the industry's growth, it added.
   The increase in demand for air travel boosted total profits of
airlines belonging to the Geneva-based association to $1.6 billion
last year, up from $900 million in 1987 and compared with a loss of
$300 million in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891030-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 0743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-China-Business     10-30 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Business,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Business Executives Find Chinese Managers Cautious, Scared</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign business executives who attended an
international forum here found Chinese managers preoccupied with
the government's current ideological campaign and imbued with a
``wait-and-see, cover-your-back attitude.''
   Foreign executives who attended the 9th symposium in China of
the Geneva-based World Economic Forum also said it was clear during
the three-day session last week that Chinese leaders were willing
to let many private and collective business enterprises ``go down
the drain.''
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Chinese also said they were studying devaluation of the yuan and
for the first time in 1990 may roll over some the nation's foreign
debt.
   They said that in meetings with Communist Party General
Secretary Jiang Zemin and other officials the Chinese emphasized
that the nation's economic reforms and open-door policy were
unaffected by the June crackdown on pro-democracy dissent and the
subsequent conservative backlash against Western liberalism.
   They said the Chinese urged the delegates from 65 foreign
companies to see for themselves that China remains eager to do
business with the outside world.
   But they said that during the meetings, which ended Friday,
there was constant reference to upholding the socialist line, and
that ``everyone was quite careful to put themselves in an
ideological framework.'' They said this was quite different from
past meetings, when politics was never mentioned.
   The sources said the more than 100 Chinese managers who attended
the forum were preoccupied with the question of increased Communist
Party interference in the workplace, one aspect of the campaign to
assure the party a leading role in all areas of society.
   ``The relationship of party and manager was clearly foremost in
their minds,'' one of the sources said.
   They said they received conflicting signals on whether increased
party authority would apply to joint Chinese-foreign ventures, and
whether employees of joint ventures would be subject to government
plans to have recent college graduates work at the grass-roots
level for several years.
   The sources said the Chinese were generally more subdued than in
previous years and were cautious in their statements. ``They are
very scared to say anything that might backlash on them,'' one said.
   They said the central role of state companies was repeatedly
emphasized, and that, in contrast to previous years, only one
private entrepreneur participated in the forum.
   China's conservative leaders, in stressing that China must
remain a socialist state, have relegated the nation's thriving
non-government companies to a minor role in the economy. Higher
taxes and the inability to obtain credit have driven many smaller
enterprises out of business.
   The sources said party chief Jiang was convincing in his pledges
that China will remain open, although he was blunt in stating that
the nation's open-door policy will always have a socialist
framework.
   Chinese officials said the government might resort to taking out
new loans to repay loans due next year. They said China, which has
a foreign debt of more than $40 billion, owes somewhere between $4
and $9 billion next year.
   Officials also said the current austerity program designed to
curb economic growth and slow inflation could last two to five
years more. The squeeze on credit and cutback on building projects
has affected many joint ventures, and the business executives were
told foreign investors will have to bring their own money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
