<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Jaguar     10-30 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Jaguar,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Plans to Build New Engine Plant in Europe, Sources Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. is planning to build a new
engine plant in Europe, which might encompass plans for a joint
components venture with Jaguar PLC, sources said Monday.
   Alternatively, a separate engine plant might be built as part of
General Motors planned tie-up with the British luxury car maker,
the sources said.
   GM has 31 manufacturing centers in Europe.
   Jaguar, which has spurned advances from Ford Motor Co. because
it wants to remain independent, has been negotiating a cooperation
agreement with GM for several weeks.
   A GM spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping
with British practice, said the U.S. auto maker was committed to
guaranteeing Jaguar's independence, and described recent talks as
``well-advanced.''
   A ``complex and detailed'' announcement of a joint agreement
between General Motors and Jaguar is to be made by Jaguar ``some
time in the next two and a half weeks,'' a source said.
   The deal is expected to include plans for a jointly developed
new auto model between General Motors and Jaguar, and a number of
agreements for joint component production, sources close to the
talks said.
   General Motors, which eventually is expected to take a minority
stake of up to 30 percent in Jaguar, would inject cash into the
British company and make available its technology. In return,
General Motors hopes to benefit from the Jaguar name, and thwart
Ford from either linking up with, or taking over, Jaguar.
   Sources close to General Motors said it hasn't decided yet
whether the new European engine plant would be built either in
Britain, West Germany or Austria.
   ``A key factor deciding if the plant will be built in Britain is
whether the group can reach an agreement with unions at Vauxhall
that they will speak with one voice,'' a source said.
   Four unions represent workers at Vauxhall, a General Motors unit.
   Though the company isn't necessarily calling for a single union
deal, it is ``looking for a new approach,'' a source said.
   General Motors announced Friday that it had received early U.S.
regulatory clearance to begin buying up to 15 percent of Jaguar.
   Ford, which previously obtained the same clearance, has raised
its stake in the British company to 13.2 percent. It has said it is
prepared to launch a full bid after takeover restrictions are
dropped.
   Both companies are prevented from raising their share in Jaguar
to over 15 percent by a ``golden share'' the British government
holds in Jaguar until the end of 1990.
</TEXT>
