<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-30 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Open Lower On Harvest; Wheat Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices were mostly lower
in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade while wheat
futures were narrowly mixed.
   The slight drop in corn and soybean values partly reflected
ideas that mild, dry weather allowed harvesting of those crops to
continue at a rapid pace over the weekend.
   Rain forecast for later this week in the Corn Belt could hamper
harvest activity. But with most of the crop already in, traders are
focusing more on foreign demand and on the South American soybean
crop, which is now being planted, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   ``They're behind normal and they need rain,'' he said of soybean
producers in Brazil and Argentina.
   The soybean market also was pressured by expectations that a
large number of deliveries will be posted against the November
soybean contract on Tuesday, the first day for traders to declare
their intentions to deliver soybeans against the contract.
   Wheat futures were supported by expectations that the Soviet
Union will soon make a major purchase of U.S. wheat, Lespinasse
said.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1} cents lower to 1 cent
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $3.99{ a
bushel; corn was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with December at
$2.41\ a bushel; oat futures were { cent lower to { cent higher
with December at $1.43\ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 2{ cents
lower with November at $5.60 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .15 cent higher with December
at 74.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .23 cent
higher with November at 82.45 cents a pound; live hogs were
unchanged to .27 cent lower with December at 45.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .10 cent to .45 cent higher with February
at 52.20 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Friday.
</TEXT>
