<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0028 10-30 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed sharply higher in the year's
thinnest volume Monday on the London Stock Exchange, supported
largely by a technical bounce after last week's steep declines.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 30.1
points, or 1.4 percent, higher at 2,112.2.
   The key index finished below a session high of 2,117.1 posted
after Wall Street opened stronger. But it had showed strength
throughout the London session, hitting a low of only 2,102.2 within
the first few minutes of trading.
   Volume was only 256.6 million shares, breaking the previous 1989
low of 276.8 million recorded last Monday. Volume also was down
dramatically from 840.8 million on Friday.
   The Financial Times 30-share index settled 23.2 points higher at
1,701.7. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 15.08 points to
close at 1,172.16.
   Dealers said the market was supported to some extent by a
stronger British pound. Share prices were up across the board, with
most blue-chip stocks registering solid gains.
</TEXT>
