<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Decline Under Harvest Pressure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed
slightly lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade as the corn and
soybean markets succumbed to harvest pressure and pulled wheat
prices down as well.
   The selling mainly reflected a perception that mild, dry weather
allowed harvesting of corn and soybeans to continue at a rapid pace
over the weekend, analysts said.
   Rain forecast for later this week could hamper harvest activity
in the eastern Corn Belt and the Southeast. But most of the
Midwestern crops have already been gathered and traders are
increasingly turning their attention to export demand, which
remained slack on Monday.
   The soybean market also was pressured lower by expectations that
a large number of delivery notices will be posted against the
November soybean contract on Tuesday, the first day for traders to
declare their intentions to deliver soybeans against the contract.
   At the close of trading, wheat futures were { cent to 2 cents
lower with the contract for delivery in December at $3.96{ a
bushel; corn was { cent to 2 cents lower with December at $2.41 a
bushel; oats were \ cent to { cent lower with December at $1.42} a
bushel; soybeans were 1} cents lower to 1 cent higher with November
at $5.61 a bushel.
</TEXT>
