<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-30 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Close Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed against the major foreign
currencies Monday while the British pound advanced for the first
time since last week's political upheaval in London.
   Gold prices slipped in domestic trading after rising overseas.
   There was no news to affect currency dealings, and analysts said
investors spent the day squaring their positions following the
pound's sharp decline late last week.
   Sterling chalked up its first gains since Chancellor of the
Exchequer Nigel Lawson resigned last Thursday night and caught many
traders by surprise.
   Robert Ryan, an analyst with the Bank of New York, said
sterling's rise reflected short-covering, the buying of dollars to
fulfill previous agreements to sell them.
   The pound rose to $1.5825 in New York, up from late Friday's
$1.5795, after closing earlier in London at $1.5785, up from
$1.5750 Friday.
   Some dealers warned, however, that sentiment toward sterling
remained bearish.
   ``You're bucking the trend if you try to take the pound higher
right now,'' said a corporate dealer at a U.S. bank in London.
``I'm not convinced the pound's fall has stopped.''
   Overseas dealers said trading was lackluster as dealers waited
for fresh economic news later in the week.
   Traders said they did not expect the dollar to move far away
from its current levels this week unless Tuesday's release of the
September Index of Leading Economic Indicators or Friday's
unemployment report provided some surprises.
   Late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8340 West German marks, up from 1.8295; 1.6050
Swiss Francs, up from 1.6005; 6.2265 French francs, up from 6.2150;
1,346.00 Italian lire, down from 1,348.00; and 1.1735 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1747.
   The dollar rose to 141.90 Japanese yen in New York from late
Friday's 141.75. In Tokyo, the dollar fell to 142.17 yen from
142.75 Friday, and in London, the dollar declined to 142.05 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8360 West German marks, up from 1.8300; 1.6065
Swiss francs, up from 1.6005; 6.2325 French francs, up from 6.2190;
2.0727 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0820; 1,348.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,342.00; and 1.1747 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1746.
   Gold edged lower in New York following gains in foreign trading.
   Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid of $376.65
for a troy ounce of gold, down from late Friday's $377.25. Earlier,
a troy ounce of gold fell 70 cents to close at $377.80 on the
Commodity Exchange in New York.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $376.75 a troy ounce,
up from $374.25 bid late Friday.
   In Zurich, Switzerland, the metal rose to a closing bid of
$376.75, up from $373 bid late Friday, and in earlier Hong Kong
trading, gold rose $1.45 to close at a bid $378.75.
   Silver prices also were mixed.
   A troy ounce of silver fell 3.8 cents to $5.243 on the Commodity
Exchange in New York. Earlier, in London, silver rose to a late bid
price of $5.22 a troy ounce from $5.19 bid late Friday.
</TEXT>
