<FIRST>u f AM-Miller-Alcohol-Free     10-30 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miller-Alcohol-Free,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miller Introducing Its First Non-Alcoholic Brew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miller Brewing Co. on Monday introduced its
first non-alcoholic brew, a product it said was spurred by growing
anti-drinking sentiment in the United States.
   Miller also announced plans for a 12-week Super Bowl advertising
campaign featuring two celebrity-coached teams battling on a
football field over rival ``taste great'' and ``less filling''
claims for Miller Lite beer.
   Miller's Sharp's brand non-alcohol brew will be introduced for
sale nationwide Jan. 1 and will be backed by a national marketing
effort but no test-marketing, Miller officials said.
   Non-alcoholic beers have been popular in Europe for some time,
and other U.S. brewers, including Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc., Pabst
and G. Heileman, already sell non-alcohol or low-alcohol brands.
   Miller touts Sharp's as having a taste like real beer due to a
new brewing process the company developed.
   Miller experimented in 1984 with a low-alcohol beer, also called
Sharp's, but the brew did not advance beyond test marketing.
   Annual U.S. production of non-alcoholic beers is about a million
barrels a year, compared with the national beer market of more than
182 million barrels. But the non-alcoholic segment is growing at
the rate of 10 percent to 15 percent a year while the overall beer
market has been stable, analysts said.
   David Krishock, new products category director for Miller, said
growth in the non-alcoholic beer market prompted Miller to bring
Sharp's out nationwide without test marketing.
   The new brew will have 74 calories per 12-ounce serving _ about
half the calories of regular beer _ and will be sold in bottles,
cans and kegs.
   Jerry Steinman, publisher of the industry newsletter Beer
Marketer's Insights, said Miller's introduction of a non-alcohol
beer was not surprising in view of an anti-alcohol atmosphere he
said prevailed in the United States.
   Steinman said non-alcoholic beers had not proven widely popular
in the United States largely because they lacked the taste of
regular beer, and because brewers had found it difficult to brew a
non-alcohol beer with real beer taste.
   Krishock said most brewers produced a non-alcoholic product by
using a normal brewing cycle and then removing the alcohol along
with the ``real beer'' taste.
   Under Miller's new brewing process, when the yeast is added to
the wort _ the end product of the barley-cooking process _ the
temperature is kept low so that fermentation is slow and produces
minimal alcohol, at the same time that the yeast contributes its
taste to the brew.
   Miller said its Super Bowl ad campaign, which will begin Nov. 5,
will feature 12 weeks of television, radio and print advertising
and a consumer sweepstakes offering expense-paid trips to Super
Bowl XXIV in New Orleans.
   The celebrity teams will be coached by pro football Hall of
Famer Larry Csonka and actor George Wendt, of television's
``Cheers,'' while actor Richard Moll of television's ``Night
Court'' will referee.
   Last year, Anheuser-Busch ran a Super Bowl ad campaign featuring
battling teams of animated helmet-clad beer bottles pitting its
Budweiser and Bud Light brands against each other.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
