<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-30 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices drifted lower in moderate
trading Monday led by weakness in the wholesale gasoline market.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
unleaded regular gasoline fell 1.21 cents to 53.41 cents a gallon.
   The contract gained nearly a penny on Friday amid reports about
possible problems at a Chevron Corp. refinery in El Segundo, Calif.
Chevron confirmed late in the day that a catalytic cracking unit
with an output of 60,000 barrels a day of gasoline had been closed
for repairs. The company said, however, that the closure would not
seriously affect output.
   ``(Gasoline) gained Friday on news about the Chevron refinery.
It shouldn't have gained and today it came back off,'' said Bob
Baker, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Weakness in the gasoline market dragged other oil prices lower,
traders said.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, closed at $19.72 a barrel, down 5 cents.
January WTI fell 10 cents to $19.47 a barrel.
   No. 2 heating oil for November delivery settled 0.04 cent lower
at 57.64 cents a gallon, while December heating oil rose 0.07 cent
to end at 58.03 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said crude prices, which have weakened in recent days,
could drift lower in advance of the Nov. 25 meeting of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries in Vienna, Austria.
Traders have attributed the decline to concern about higher OPEC
production in the face of slackening U.S. demand.
   Various estimates have put the cartel's total output at around
23 million barrels a day, well in excess of its official quota of
20.5 million barrels a day. And while various OPEC members have
suggested that increasing worldwide demand supports the higher
output, some analysts argue that world oil prices could weaken if
the United States, the largest consumer of oil, cannot absorb some
of the excess.
</TEXT>
