<HEAD>Copper Market Extends Decline On Easing Supply Fears</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 17th graf pvs to CORRECT West Texas Intermediate prices
to 5 cents, 26 cents sted 0.5 cent, 0.26 cent; picks up 18th graf pvs bg'ng,
Grain and ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices fell sharply Monday on New York's
Commodity Exchange, extending the market's two-week-old slide amid
new selling prompted by a continued easing of supply fears.
   On other futures markets Monday, precious metals retreated; pork
bellies surged while livestock futures were mixed; oil futures
fell; grains and soybeans slipped; and stock-index futures were
narrowly mixed.
   Copper settled .30 cent to 3.35 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in December at $1.128 a pound, its lowest price since
Aug. 10.
   Copper traders began selling at the opening bell in reaction to
the London Metal Exchange's report of a smaller-than-expected 550
metric ton decline in warehouse stocks of copper last week. The
market had expected a drawdown of as much as 4,000 tons.
   The report reinforced perceptions that pressure on copper
supplies is easing following the recent settlement of a two-month
Canadian mine strike and the expected reopening of Mexico's largest
copper mine after a two-month shutdown.
   ``Two-thirds of the near-term production problems seem to have
been resolved,'' said metals economist Fred Demler of Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc., referring to the Canadian and Mexican mines.
A third major copper mine, in Papua New Guinea, has been shut down
since mid-July due to terrorism in the area.
   The market appeared to ignore news of a potential new supply
threat in Chile, where workers at two mines, two mills and a
smelter operated by an Exxon Corp. affiliate took a strike vote
Friday that could result in a strike as early as next Thursday,
when their contract expires.
   The Chilean operation, known as Exxon Disputada, produces about
115,000 metric tons of copper annually, less than any of the
aforementioned three mines, said Tom Torget, a spokesman for Exxon
Coal and Minerals Co. in Houston.
   Under Chilean law, a strike would be required next Monday if no
agreement is reached by then, Torget said. But, he said, ``we think
both sides are interested in an agreement.''
   Gold and silver futures fell modestly on the Comex, but
sustained most of the gains made last Thursday and Friday, when
gold rose more than $9 an ounce.
   Demler said the gold market's refusal to sell off sharply could
be construed as a bullish signal.
   But analyst Stephen Platt of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. predicted
gold would ``encounter some formidable resistance'' at about $383 a
troy ounce in the December contract.
   Gold settled 40 cents to $1.20 lower with December at $380.80 a
troy ounce; silver was 3.7 cents to 3.8 cents lower with December
at $5.283 a troy ounce.
   Frozen pork-belly futures rallied strongly on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange on reports that Yugoslavia had bought 200
metric tons of U.S. bellies for November delivery and was
considering buying up to 800 tons more. A pork belly is the part of
a hog from which bacon is made.
   Pork bellies settled 1.25 cents to 1.75 cents higher with
February at 53.60 cents a pound; live cattle finished .25 cent
lower to .13 cent higher with December at 74.15 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .40 cent lower to .15 cent higher with November
at 82.55 cents a pound; live hogs were .42 cent lower to .05 cent
higher with December at 45.75 cents a pound.
   Oil futures retreated on the New York Mercantile Exchange, paced
by the November gasoline contract, which expires on Tuesday.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 26 cents
lower with November at $18.34 a barrel; heating oil was .16 cent
lower to .07 cent higher with November at 57.64 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was 1.17 cents lower to .35 cent higher with
November at 53.45 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed slightly lower on the
Chicago Board of Trade as the corn and soybean markets succumbed to
harvest pressure, pulling wheat down as well.
   Wheat futures settled { cent to 1} cents lower with December at
$3.96} a bushel; corn was { cent to 2 cents lower with December at
$2.41 a bushel; oats were \ cent to { cent lower with December at
$1.42} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with
November at $5.60{ a bushel.
   Stock-index futures were narrowly mixed on the Chicago Merc,
where the contract for December delivery of the stocks in the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled unchanged at 337.20 points.
Each point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
