<FILEID>AP-NR-10-30-89 2004EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Chrysler     10-30 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iacocca: Chrysler Plant or Plants Likely To Close by End of 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least one of Chrysler Corp.'s 12 North
American assembly plants will have to close by the end of next year
and some projects may be delayed as the automaker wrestles with a
smaller market, Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca says.
   Iacocca, in an interview published in Monday's Automotive News,
didn't say which plants would be closed, but speculation centers on
the company's St. Louis car plant as being the most likely.
   That plant makes the Dodge Daytona and the Chrysler LeBaron
Coupe and convertible. Last year, when the company renovated its
Newark, Del., plant for Dodge Spirit and Plymouth Acclaim
production, it modified tooling to enable it to make the two
LeBarons as well.
   ``You have got too much capacity chasing too few customers in
the richest market in the world,'' Iacocca said. ``It will only be
solved one of two ways. The way we will probably have to do it is
that General Motors, Ford and Chrysler will have to close some
plants. Period.
   ``Or there would be a trade bill, and we would shut our
borders,'' he said. ``But we won't do that and I don't advocate
that.''
   GM plans to idle its Lakewood assembly plant in Georgia in
March. The company already has closed plants in Framingham, Mass.,
and Pontiac, Mich. Ford officials have said they will deal with
overcapacity by trimming overtime, which has been high in some Ford
factories.
   ``We definitely will have to close more than we have closed to
date, which is a 100-year-old plant called Kenosha,'' Iacocca said.
``There is a plant or two that probably will be closed.''
   Chrysler inherited the plant in Kenosha, Wis., when it bought
American Motors Corp.
   Besides the plant closing, Iacocca said some projects may be
delayed, but that the company's new LH and LX car programs will
continue. Cars derived from the two platforms will be introduced in
the early 1990s.
   ``That one is not going to be deferred because it is in the
heart of the market,'' he said, ``and we would like some
strengthening there.''
   Iacocca indicated that the No. 3 U.S. car company may abandon
parts of the automobile or truck market if it determines that it
isn't profitable.
   ``I don't think we can afford to be in every car and truck
segment,'' he said. ``In this world market now, you cannot go it
alone and you cannot be all things to all people. ...
   ``So we're going to have to continue to try to develop car
niches that are profitable to us.''
</TEXT>
