<FIRST>r f BC-QuotronLayoffs     10-30 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Quotron Layoffs,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quotron Announces Layoffs, Blaming 1987 Market Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quotron Systems Inc. said Monday it will lay
off 400 of its 2,500 employees because demand for financial
information has plunged due to Wall Street cutbacks and
consolidations since the October 1987 stock market crash.
   The layoffs will affect a wide range of job levels at Quotron
offices around the world, said the Los Angeles-based subsidiary of
Citicorp, the New York banking company.
   Quotron provides financial information such as stock prices
through a network of more than 100,000 computer terminals in 23
countries. Its competitors include Telerate Inc., Reuters Holding
PLC and Knight-Ridder Inc.
   Quotron's president and chief executive, J. David Hann, said in
a statement that the layoffs ``will continue to keep operating
expenses in line with revenues in response to changing conditions
in the retail securities industry, which has been contracting since
October 1987.''
   Quotron revenues had been growing at the rate of 25 percent a
year when Citicorp acquired the company two years ago for $680
million, about three times Quotron's annual revenues at that time.
   Citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding concern, does not
provide financial results for Quotron.
</TEXT>
