<FIRST>u f AM-AmericanAirlines     10-30 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American Airlines,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Airlines To Expand Transatlantic Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines will expand its
transatlantic service by 30 percent beginning in 1990 with six new
daily flights between the United States and Europe, officials
announced Monday.
   The new nonstop flights starting in May 1990 include
Chicago-Warsaw, Chicago-Helsinki, Miami-Madrid, Dallas-Barcelona, a
second daily Chicago-Paris flight and a second daily
Chicago-Manchester flight, officials said.
   ``These new flights emphasize American Airlines' commitment to
building a strong European service and continuing the expansion of
our international network,'' said Donald J. Carty, executive vice
president of American.
   The announcement also was made at a news conference at the
International Air Transport Association meeting in Warsaw, Poland.
   Carty said Chicago was targeted as the originating point of four
of the transatlantic flights because of its large Polish population.
   ``Chicago has the largest population of citizens of Polish
heritage in any city except Warsaw, and thus we anticipate a great
deal of personal and pleasure travel,'' Carty said.
   With the new service, American will fly 161 flights a week to 17
European cities. The additions solidify American's position as the
third-largest U.S. transatlantic carrier, behind Pan American World
Airways and Trans World Airlines.
   American is the nation's largest airline. Its parent, AMR Corp.,
recently was the target of a $7 billion takeover proposal from New
York developer Donald Trump.
</TEXT>
