<FIRST>u f AM-AntifungalDrug     10-30 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antifungal Drug,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Antifungal Drug Approved by FDA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schering-Plough Corp. on Monday announced
that an over-the-counter version of a prescription antifungal drug
that treats athlete's foot and other fungal infections has received
federal approval.
   Lotrimin AF, which is manufactured by Schering-Plough's health
care division, will be the over-the-counter version of Lotrimin, a
prescription drug that also treats topical yeast and fungal
infections, such as jock itch and body ringworm.
   The medicine, which was approved by the Food and Drug
Administration last week, will be introduced to head off generic
forms of Lotrimin AF, which could appear on store shelves when
Schering-Plough's patent expires Dec. 5, said company spokesman
Ronald Asinari.
   Schering-Plough already manufactures Tinactin, a leading topical
antifungal in the general consumer market, Asinari said.
   He said the topical antifungal market has grown at an annual
rate of 12 percent. Worldwide sales of dermatological products
contributed $401 million to Schering-Plough's total sales of $2.97
billion last year, he said.
   Lotrimin AF will be on the market in 1990 and will be available
in cream and liquid forms.
</TEXT>
