<HEAD>Boeing Reports Strong 3rd Quarter Profits, But Says Strike Will Hurt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Boeing released ...,' with talks ending for
day.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. enjoyed record third-quarter profits
68 percent higher than in the same period in 1988, but the jet
builder warned Monday that a lingering strike by Machinists will
hurt badly the rest of the year.
   The company also said it is having ``substantial'' losses on
some government and defense programs.
   Boeing released its earnings statement as its negotiators met
with those of the Machinists union in an attempt to end the
four-week-old strike. Six hours of talks produced only an agreement
to meet again Tuesday.
   Federal mediator Douglas Hammond, who called Monday's session,
said he hoped to keep the two sides at the table until a new
contract offer can be worked out.
   Boeing Chairman Frank Shrontz said the higher profits for the
quarter and first nine months were due mostly to higher sales
volume and lower research, development and other new business costs
for commercial aircraft and computing.
   But he said that performance was partially offset by losses and
higher research and development costs for defense programs, and a
higher effective federal tax rate.
   Net earnings for the quarter ending Sept. 30 were $242 million,
or $1.05 a share, on revenue of $6.36 billion, compared with
profits of $144 million, or 63 cents a share, on revenue of $3.72
billion a year earlier.
   Boeing spokesman Paul Binder said both profits and sales for the
most recent quarter were records for the company.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Boeing's profits were $598
million, or $2.60 a share, on revenue of $15.43 billion, compared
with net earnings of $440 million, or $1.92 a share, on revenue of
$12.09 billion.
   ``While that looks good at first glance, closer inspection
indicates our net profit was only 3.9 percent'' for the first nine
months, Binder said.
   ``Our profit margin is approximately 1 percent less than the
average of all U.S. manufacturing companies and we simply must do
better to remain competitive.''
   Union spokesman Jack Daniels read it differently: ``That falls
into line with our contention that their profits indicate they
should make a better offer to the Machinists union.''
   Stock analysts said Boeing's performance was about what they
anticipated, although they took special note of the downbeat
forecasts for defense work and strike effects.
   ``That's the first time I've seen any indication they feel there
will be a severe impact on the fourth quarter,'' said Paul Nisbet
of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``At the end of the second quarter, they mentioned matter of
factly that the company's defense and space programs would not be
profitable at the end of 1989,'' said William Deatherage, analyst
at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New York. ``Now they're saying it's
a significant loss.''
   Boeing announced on Friday a major reorganization of its defense
division.
   The third-quarter figures don't show effects of the strike by
about 57,800 union Machinists who walked out Oct. 4 after rejecting
a 3-year contract offer.
   ``The strike by the Machinists union will have a serious adverse
impact on fourth-quarter sales and earnings and on the company's
cash and short-term investment position,'' Shrontz said in the
earnings statement.
   That was one of the strongest acknowledgments from Boeing about
damages from the strike, which has severely slowed aircraft
deliveries.
   When the strike began, Boeing had hoped to deliver another 94
aircraft by the end of the year. So far, it has delivered only 15.
</TEXT>
